Community Housing Limited (CHL) is involved in developing housing solutions for good quality affordable rental housing for those in need and/or assisting those who are disadvantaged by market failure in securing a pathway to home ownership. The charity is dedicated on developing viable accommodation options for those experiencing housing difficulty. The charity is committed to its object for providing shelter to persons in crisis and who have inadequate access to safe and secure housing. CHL also provided housing advice and referral services, which may assist homeless persons to stable and long term housing. Internationally CHL is involved in developing housing strategies in partnership with communities and their government to assist people who live in informal and slum housing who are unable to secure long term affordable housing.  CHL has always worked in partnership with national and state government authorities, social support agencies and local community groups to address local housing affordability problems. Thus CHL has pursued its charitable objects by providing good quality affordable rental housing for people who are in need.

The principal activities of the Association during the financial year were: 1. To function as a non-profit association whose Members comprise Volunteer Fire Brigades registered by the Country Fire Authority under the Country Fire Authority Act (1958) and its Regulations. 2. To liaise and consult on the operation of the _Volunteer Charterî in the interests of CFA volunteers about all matters which might reasonably be expected to affect them. The Volunteer Charter is an agreed tripartite commitment between the State of Victoria, the CFA, and CFA Volunteers, committing the State of Victoria and the CFA to consultation with volunteers about all matters which might reasonably be expected to affect volunteers. VBFV represents its Members and CFA Volunteers in that consultation process. 3. To assist in maintaining high morale, ongoing health and welfare of CFA volunteer members and their families 4. Support CFA volunteers experiencing personal financial hardship/crisis by providing small welfare grants that may assist in alleviating stresses impacting on the individualês ability to maintain their involvement as a volunteer. 5. Preserve and strengthen CFAês community and volunteer based foundations by enabling members of CFA brigades to consider and bring to the notice of CFA all matters affecting their welfare and efficiency (other than questions of discipline and promotion). 6. To promote to CFA volunteers the comprehensive support services available to them including but not limited to: legal assistance, OH&S, equity and diversity, counselling and welfare, training, employment support and compensation for accidents, injuries and illness.7. To develop awareness, respect and support for CFA volunteers and their fundamental and pivotal role in the CFA as a community based, volunteer based fire and emergency service for the people of Victoria.  8. To take any other action as determined by the Association Board consistent with these purposes.9. To maintain and pursue a balanced focus on issues affecting CFA volunteers across all brigades from all risk profiles.

Hands On Learning Australia (HOLA) is a PBI charity that partners with schools to target students at risk of early school leaving and build the individual wellbeing critical to improved learning outcomes and life long achievement. The Hands On Learning (HOL) method significantly increases attendance, improves vocational and academic pathways, and reduces youth unemployment.HOLA provides the necessary training, project management, and ongoing support so schools can use the HOL method effectively. Ten students work with two artisan-teachers one full day each week on creative building projects that benefit the school and local community. Student engagement increases through formal safe respectful relationships that cultivate a sense of belonging, and through providing opportunities for these students to experience success with real world tasks.Schools are successfully using the HOL method as a targeted early intervention for students in Years 5-10 who have experienced bullying, social isolation, or difficulty learning in the classroom. HOL is highly effective because vulnerable students remain connected to their school, develop an alternative peer group, form positive relationships with adults, and receive ongoing long-termsupport. As a result HOL participants experience permanent, positive change.

2015-16 has been an important year for Kildonan, not least celebrating its 135th year, but also marking the completion of its Strategic Plan for 2013-2016; a three year commitment which saw it continue to facilitate thriving and inclusive communities by creating and delivering integrated solutions that lead to social and economic inclusion. The positive outcomes from programs such as Families@Home, ChildFirst and Youth services solidified Kildonanês reputation as a driving force in the delivery of programs which empower families in need, with particular focus on family violence. Its Menês Behaviour Change Programs now include culturally specific programs for South Asian and Arabic speaking men. Kildonan continued to build strong partnerships with the corporate sector through CareRing-identifying and helping banking and utility customers at the earliest stages of financial stress. In 2015-16, CareRing supported more than 1,000 people, impacting on more than 3,150 household members. The final report for the Koorie Energy Efficiency Program (KEEP) showed almost 3,000 Aboriginal households were reached and more than 1,000 home energy visits enabled a large proportion of the Victorian Aboriginal community to learn more about energy usage and managing their bills. Partnerships remained crucial to our work and the year saw 25 different agencies brought together by Kildonan to deliver holistic and integrated services to those in need.

A Real Meal is more than providing hot food to the marginalised communities of Melbourne, we aim to create friendships, build trust and give the most important thing one can give - our time.TBU House in Nepal is home to 20 ex-street children providing transformational support and care through rehabilitation, education, love and stability.In 2015 a devastating earthquake struck Nepal, killing close to 9,000 people and destroying hundreds of thousands of homes, schools and essential public buildings. In the 2015/16 year we increased our programs offered to the community significantly, providing more opportunities to connect people to each other in our neighbourhood. We work collaboratively with other local agencies to maximize the resources we have. Contributions from local businesses and fundraising added to the grants we receive from DHHS and Hume City Council. Some of the highlights include:‚ Introduction of a new sewing program for both adults and primary school children which are booked out every term. We acknowledge the generous support of Homestead Community House in Roxbrough Park for the loan of sewing machines. Huge donations of fabric and sewing accessories have also been received from members of the community which has helped enormously.‚ A new Soul Sisters Group started. Soul Sisters is a small gathering of women who support one another through deep conversations and fun events. They meet every second Friday.                                 ‚ The Aboriginal community gathering supported by Sunbury Community Health, held here every Monday morning.‚ Knitting circle, learning how to create useful items from recycled materials.‚ Creative Expressions, a new art therapy group for young adults struggling with anxiety and depression.‚ Auslan, Australian Sign language course was popular at the start of the year.We continue to work with Sunbury Community Health, VU, Macedon Ranges Further Education, Goonawarra House, Hume City Council and other Neighbourhood Houses in our area to seek constant improvement, resource sharing and support for our respective communities. This year we joined with Goonawarra House and Sunbury Community Health to work on a collective community development plan. This has helped us to focus on the needs of our immediate neighbourhood, and work will begin this year on collecting stories from participants, members and locals to feed into our next strategic plan focus group in January.The House has benefited greatly from the free resources, professional development opportunities and we are very grateful to the board of SCH for this opportunity.        We continue to have a close working relationship with Macedon Ranges Further Education, and have regular planning sessions to discuss new courses and adult learning opportunities to Sunbury.The success of our seniorês computer programs would not be possible without the generous support of Hume City Council. We have seen many participants thrive and gain confidence through this class.

100 Story Buildingês mission is to provide opportunities for the most marginalised children and young people in Melbourneês west to build the literacy skills, confidence and sense of belonging that are fundamental to their future success. We do this through authentic writing programs that connect our beneficiaries with creative individuals, in collaborative creative projects that have authentic outcomes. Our programs are designed in collaboration with schools, councils and other community and arts organisations, and are specifically tailored to suit the needs of the relevant beneficiaries. Our flagship project, Early Harvest, is a literary journal created by an editorial committee of upper primary students from disadvantaged schools, and features writing and artwork by children and adult contributors. Other programs involve storytelling forms such as film, comics, and radio plays. A key element to our work is the provision of a creative hub, where children from different cultural and socioeconomic backgrounds can work together on projects, helping to open up the doors of the classroom and their understanding and experiences of conventional social structures. We work in schools to offer teacher professional development.

column2: The Walter And Eliza Hall Institute Of Medical Research
column39: Medical Research - Mastery of disease through discovery.
column41: The advances in medical science at the Walter and Eliza Hall Institute are made possible by our generous supporters.  In 2016, about one-quarter of vital funding for the Institute was generously provided from philanthropic sources, including donations, grants, gifts in wills and interest earned on endowed funds.  It is our individual supporters who have been willing to support an innovative idea with seed funding, back a young scientist through the challenging early years or purchase a new piece of equipment that will provide astonishing insights into medical biology.  this has allowed the Institute to be committed to making fundamental scientific discoveries that can be translated to better treatments, bringing real benefits to the community on a global scale.  Clinical trials based on discoveries made at the Institute include trials of vaccines for coeliac disease, diabetes and malaria; trials of new anti-inflammatory agents; and trials of a new class of anticancer drugs, called BH3-mimetics, for treating people with leukaemia and other cancers.At the Walter and Eliza Hall Institute of Medical Research, donors are a vital part of the research teams.  Without our supporters we would not be able to take a risk on innovative blue-sky research, fund the challenging initial phase of drug discovery, or support the early work of our most promising young scientists.  In 2016 our donors funded fellowships for early career scientists, helped us to purchase equipment, provided funding for some of our most innovative research projects, and directed legacy gifts to our endowment fund in order to support our future discoveries.  Philanthropic grants and donations, and interest earned on our endowment funds, represents one-quarter of the funds available for our research.  In 2016, grants and donations contributed more than $23m to the Institute's research endeavours.  The Walter and Eliza Hall Institute is committed to making fundamental scientific discoveries that can be translated to better treatments, bringing real benefits to the community on a global scale.  Clinical trials based on discoveries made at WEHI, include trials for vaccines for rheumatoid arthritis, coeliac disease and malaria, and trials of a new class of anti-cancer drugs.  Our researchers are committed to tackling some of the most challenging diseases facing humanity. We focus on cancer, immune disorders and infectious disease.

At TDi we fundamentally believe that if youêre passionate about seeing change in the world, building businesses where social and financial returns are aligned is the best way to achieve it. Through our method we seek to build better businesses with alternative, sustainable revenue streams, ultimately helping us crack entrenched social and environmental challenges. We know that on-going grant reliance is no longer the long term strategy the social sector once thought it was, and all businesses need to explore their role in building a stronger and more sustainable world. At TDi, we return to the roots of business by building strong, high impact business models and enterprises where there is no compromise on either profit or purpose. Whether it's a Business Model Workshop, our Two Feet Program, our Bespoke Consultancy services or our International Development work, we help businesses at all stages of development. From the start-up phase, to growing enterprises, right through to well established businesses that want to have more impact. We help them bring into focus their mission, the business and financial model that helps them deliver and the management team that makes it all possible.

Uplift Project collected and distributed around 200.000 bras in the 15/16 activity year. Over 250 Breast forms were shipped also, and fitted to women post mastectomy, primarily by our Fiji fitting team and Cancer Foundation PNG. The primary aim of our charity is to provide the dignity and comfort of a bra to women who do not have access to them. Seconday gains are often made in education about breast health and domestic and sexual violence during distribution sessions which are attended by up to a thousand women per day.From Victoria, full shipping containers holding about 30,000 bras each, plus medical, educational or crisis relief supplies, were sent to Solomon Islands, Oxfam PNG, and to Medical Services Pacific, Fiji.Our NSW branch shipped the equivalent of 2 full containers to Fiji also. In addition they have supplied a number of women's shelters and the Asylum Seekers Shelter. Further donations have gone from NSW to Philippines, Vanuatu, Tonga, Solomons and PNG in containers sent by Rotary, LMA and ADRA.About 8,000 bras were donated from South Australia to Stronger Families in Tennant Creek for distribution through the local remote communities. Stock collected by Mt Gambier branch was transferred to Melbourne and included in outgoing shipments.Our Queensland branch shipped around 5,000 bras to Sri Lanka, and a further 2,000 to Solomon Islands.WA branch had a year of collecting, but not being able to ship out. Their stock has since been shipped to Red Cross Vanuatu.Our New Zealand branch shipped 2,500 bras to Samoa, and about 5,000 to Tonga.Singapore branch shipped about 800 bras to Philippines over the year also.Postal donations were received and distributed in Botswana, about 300 bras total, and Uganda, 60 bras total. The Botswana branch is now legally formulated as a charity.Money donated is used only for shipping costs, and covering the residual expenses of setting us up as a legal charity, which we have been given the great courtesy of paying off slowly. All storage used by the project is donated.9 businesses donated new stock to Uplift Project during this year, donations ranging from 2,000 to 40,000 garments each. Donations of new underpants in NSW and Victoria have been shared with Days for Girls. and in return, they have contributed Menstrual management kits to some of our outgoing shipments.We are pursuing Deductible Gift recipient status.

column2: The Trustee For The Inner North Community Foundation Charitable Fund
column41: The Inner North Community Foundation is an independent community foundation based in Melbourneês Inner North, and is one of more than 35 community foundations across Australia.The Foundation was established in 2007 as an initiative of IntoWork Australia, and is supported by the three local Councils; the Cities of Moreland, Yarra and Darebin.The Foundation manages philanthropic dollars to provide funds for projects that create prosperous, connected, and cohesive communities in Melbourneês Inner North, particularly encouraging pathways to employment.  The Foundation is not a destination for community gifts, rather we are a safe pair of hands to link donors and community groups.To fulfil our vision, we:    invest in local not-for-profit organisations through grants and other support    connect donors to local community groups by managing a donor network for people to contribute small and large donations    build partnerships to expand community leadership across the region.Since its establishment, the Foundation has granted more than $2.4 million in grants to the municipalities of Darebin, Moreland, and Yarra.   Our grants have been awarded across 30 different suburbs to 130 community organisations, running innovative and creative programs that unlock the potential of local people.  From Preston to Pascoe Vale, Reservoir to Richmond, Fawkner to Fitzroy the Foundation serves nearly 400,000 people across 125 square kilometres.

PPHAês charitable purpose is _to promote the relief of poverty, sickness or the needs of the aged by providing affordable rental housing to persons in housing need as low-income households, or through infirmity or age.î This is captured in PPHA ês mission, which is _Building Affordable Homes and Local Communitiesî.PPHA undertook its charitable purpose in 2016 through the management of 1,083 homes at 32 sites spanning six municipalities in metropolitan Melbourne, providing affordable rental housing for over 1450 individuals.PPHA continues to house those on the lowest incomes, with 83% of PPHAês primary tenants receiving Government income support. Over 70% of PPHA's stock is for singles and couples, as this cohort faces the greatest battle in finding affordable housing in the private market; and 53% of PPHA's tenants are aged 55 or older.PPHA works in close partnership with local governments, and is the Trustee for the Port Phillip Housing Trust. Best known in the City of Port Phillip for its high-quality rooming houses, PPHA is also the leading private provider of affordable family housing in the municipality.PPHA is a major developer of affordable rental housing in Victoria. In July 2015 PPHA completed a new residential development in Essendon, providing secure and high-quality homes to 60 low income singles, couples, families and older persons who would otherwise be unable to live in the City of Moonee Valley.For more details of PPHA's activities in 2015-16, download our Annual Report from http://www.ppha.org.au/news/annual-reports/ppha-annual-report-2016/download (PDF, 7.6MB).

column2: Piers K Fowler Scholarship Fund Ltd
column41: Report for the Year to June, 2016:  Year 3Piers passed away on 4th June 2013.  We miss him.  We miss his basic goodness and kindness and talents and warmth.  The familyês aim in establishing this Scholarship Fund and an associated Trust has been to invest Piersê own assets for donating to recognised educational and charitable institutions associated with his life.  Piers was a senior training pilot with Qantas so our first aim has been to donate in the area of aviation education and training.  Piers also had volunteer involvement with the Salvation Army, Arthritis Victoria, and Scienceworks.  He was concerned for disadvantaged children and their education, and for homeless people.  He was an organ donor.  All of the things which represent Piers guide the work of the Scholarship Fund and its associated Trust, the Piers K Fowler Trust.  Details relating to the Fund may be found on the website of the Australian Charities and Not for Profits Commission (ACNC).  The Fund must deal specifically with scholarships.  The Trust may distribute benefits more widely but always to DGR-recognised institutions and always to the benefits which Piers would have sought.  The Fund and Trust together made donations of just over $90,000 in this latest financial year, bringing total donations and grants since inception to almost $200,000.  As in the previous year, our donations and gifts were virtually equal to the income earned during the year.  Reflecting Piersê own life, Aviation education, training and development forms a major part of the Fundês work.  We have a wide-ranging program of aviation-related Scholarships and awards with Swinburne University of Technology (SUT), including one overseas exchange award, support for an instructor rating course, a research award and a number of development / leadership awards.  We also support the SUT Mentoring Program for aviation students developed by Captain Mark Kreiger of Qantas.  Similarly, with the Aviation School of RMIT University, we provide a number of scholarships plus funds to support a Technical Library for all students.  We express our thanks to SUT and RMIT for their support and guidance in establishing our scholarship programs.  In other activities, the Trust is involved with Museum Victoria in the establishment of an interactive aviation-related display at Scienceworks.  Additionally, The Trust continues to support 15 Smith Family children and has provided funding to Melbourne City Mission, the Salvation Army and the Lighthouse Foundation in support of training and activity programs for homeless or potentially homeless people.  The Trust has made contributions in support of Move Arthritis Victoria, a Monash Medical School Scholarship, Ovarian Cancer Australia, St Yared a school for children in Ethiopia, and the Indigenous Literary Foundation.We are pleased to accept public donations (which have to be directed through the DGR-approved Scholarship Fund) but will not be seeking to develop that avenu

column41: SCCFA is run purely by volunteers and all funds raised are used for the intended objectives.  None of the committee members are remunerated, even when they're on a mission to meet beneficiaries and partners in Cambodia.However, SCCFA covers most of the airfares and health-cover for the Cambodian entertainers who travel to Australia in order to take part in our annual fundraising concerts.  Food and accommodation are usually provided by the local Cambodian community and local businesses.Therefore approx. 70% of the funds raised are used to support educational projects in Cambodia and 30% is used to raise awareness in Australia of the plight of the poor children of Cambodia.Every year SCCFA submits the organisation's audited financial statement to Consumer Affairs Victoria of the Department of Justice as stipulated by our incorporated constitution.  Also, all of our banking transactions require two signatures from authorised committee members. Hence, ensuring our goals are continually met.

column41: Our theme for 2016 is Bald Canvas. The idea behind this is to generate awareness, promote positive self-awareness and to capture some images /footage to promote our social media accounts. Judy started of the campaign in November. Head talk saw strangers write words of inspiration on Judy head.  In a continuation, Greg Motherês day event was the second of our videos.  The last in the series was the Removal of GST.  At each event we got a handful of people with Alopecia attending, but we were not successful in getting an alopecia person to run their own bald canvas event.Shopnate -.  The idea is a % of the sale 9differnet % for each retailer) is donated back to AAAF.  In November AAAF will be the charity of choice.  We currently have 6 regular people shopping and received our first $50.00 donation. Online GST Petition was created in May 2015 and advertised thorough our newsletter. It was encouraging to see 100 signatures prior to advertising this though our social media platforms.  It currently sits with 1800 signatures.  Manual forms were sent to Wig suppliers in August and we currently have 300 manual signatures.Wigs For Big Kids program was a huge success with $38,000 dollars granted to over 50 individuals.Scalp Micro Pigmentation  (SMP) has been big this year, with many providers offering their services.  Attempts to run competitions to give away these services have seen NO uptake within the community.RMIT Discipline of Exercise Sciences _ research possible benefits of physical activity on quality of life and mental health in alopecia areata patients has been funded by AAAF.  There will be ongoing research into the barriers that participating in physical activity impacts on patients with AA..Why Does my Hair Fall Out DVD _ was picked up by our Dutch friends with further discussions being held to obtain the footage in raw format so that it can be translated.  The youtube version had subtitles assigned to it.In keeping with our aims of Awareness, support and funding for research the following activities were undertaken.? Window Sticker for Donate Hair? column2: THE TRUSTEE FOR THE RACV COMMUNITY FOUNDATION
column41: IntroductionThe RACV Community Foundation is a Public Ancillary Fund (PuAF), colloquially known as a community foundation. Community foundations act as a bridge for philanthropic giving between donors and beneficiaries. A great supporter of community foundations globally, the US Mott Foundation has written that there is a _simplicity and the power that underlies the community foundation concept, which is to create a local vehicle that can empower the residents of a community to support causes close to home and close to the heart.î  The RACV Community Foundation is that local vehicle for its supporters; the link between the donor, and the charities as the recipient.With a clear focus of improving quality of life of disadvantaged Victorians through mobility, the RACV Community Foundation provides grants to eligible charitable organisations in Victoria. Since its establishment in 1997, the Foundation has distributed $4 million in grants to eligible organisations.  Around half of the grants have been awarded to groups in rural and regional areas, and the Foundation has a strong focus on small, community-based groups.  The Foundation continues to gain understanding of current and emerging community needs. It undertakes investigation and exploration with policy makers, peak bodies, researchers and charities at the coal face to ensure its direction and focus on addressing important needs in the community.The annual granting program and corresponding review with recipients provides data and insight, enabling the Foundation to evaluate its activities against its mission, vision and aims.Along with mandatory strategies such as an investment strategy, the Foundation develops and implements multi-year strategic plans which provide a framework on which the Foundation can continue to build its impact.The Foundation complies with statutory obligations according to the relevant Tax and the Fundraising Acts, Public Ancillary Fund Guidelines, and the Australian Charities and Not For Profit Commission (ACNC). What are we here for?In challenging economic times, the community services that the Foundation helps to fund are being called upon more than ever. It is important that the RACV Community Foundation makes a significant contribution to the social fabric of Victoria. Through our fundraising, management of funds and distribution of grants, we aspire to the Foundationês current vision and mission.Vision: To provide a source of philanthropic funding for Victorian charitable and community organisations in order to enhance quality of life.Mission: To provide funds to grassroots community service organisations that look to increase mobility in Victorian communities, with a view to enhancing social cohesion, safety, and/or environmental sustainability. More information of the Foundation including its online animated annual report can be foundation at racv.com.au/foundation

column41: A key focus of the IASRB is helping the elderly isolated Irish in Victoria. Their health and wellbeing is of upmost importance. Staff and volunteers provide the following health focused outreach services to people in need ‚ visiting isolated Irish people in hospitals, nursing home, aged care facilities and private homes ‚ providing transportation to medical appointments ‚ assistance to Irish people who experiencing difficulty due to accidents or have a chronic illness. Where necessary liaise with family members in Ireland. ‚ assistance with organising funerals and/or helping with the formalities associated with the repatriation of remains back to Ireland ‚ providing food parcels and vouchers to people in need We see our role as assisting in filling the gaps between the existing government systems. Our clientês wellbeing is our primary concern. We recognise that isolation and loneliness have a negative impact on a personês health and feelings of wellbeing. This is particularly relevant for people who are unwell and are far away from loved ones and where they grew up. The IASRB centre in Northcote is a point of contact for people to enjoy regular activities, have a cup of tea and make new friends. column41: Our purpose is to equip and empower troubled youth, individuals and families to overcome crises and experience full restoration in their hearts and lives. We exist to strengthen, train and influence at-risk youth, individuals and families to reach their full potential and become contributing members of our society. We accomplish this through professional Counselling; life-skills training; street outreach services; support groups; programs for at-risk youth; family mediation; inductions to drug and alcohol rehabilitation and a 24Hr Help-line.Our vision is to see a continual decrease in the overwhelming crises so may individuals and families experience as we impact our society one life at a time. Recipients of our services are individuals and families living in crisis: family breakdown; relationship problems; physical, sexual and emotional abuse; depression; suicidal tendencies; drug and alcohol addictions; anger; and many other life-controlling problems.Our life-skills training is strategically combined with professional counselling, support groups and Outreach services, to ensure a wholistic approach to the care we provide. In every service we provide, our emphasis is to coach and empower individuals to build character and life-skills and address emotional and mental trauma or weakness. column2: Medical Association For Prevention Of War - Australia Inc.
column41: MAPW NATIONAL REPORT 2015/2016Nuclear WeaponsIt has been a big year for nuclear disarmament. We have given talks, written opinion pieces and many published letters. We have liaised with health organisations and done what we can to support the work of ICAN (set up by MAPWA in Melbourne nearly a decade ago). We have corresponded with Foreign Minister Julie Bishop, Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull , Opposition Leader Bill  Shorten and (then) shadow defence minister Tanya Plibersek.We have had articles in both medical and nursing journals.We sent an open letter to Malcom Turnbull signed by many, urging him to support the UN vote for negotiations next year towards a nuclear weapons ban treaty.We have met with a number of MPs. We have a follow up open letter to the PM asking that Australia join in the negotiations in 2017.Marshall Island Atomic test survivor Abacca Anjain _Maddison went to New York in the lead up to the vote at the UN First Committee. She was a very powerful and effective advocate with the Pacific Island nation representatives. And the nuclear weapons ban treaty negotiations start next year- 123 in favour, 36 against with 16 abstentions!ArmamentsOur year has included putting in submissions, visiting MPs,writing letters to government, having opinion pieces and letters published regarding war powers reform, Australiaês role in Syria, our rapidly increasing defence spending (while slashing foreign aid) and controversial purchases such as the Joint Strike Fighter planes.We have been coordinating the No Airport Arms Ads campaign against weapons advertisements at Canberra Airport. This has been both effective and very informative, with regular bulletins on the state of the weapons industry worldwide. The ads have reduced considerably, and the campaign is working towards their total removal.War powers reformWith the release of the long awaited Chilcot report, we conducted a survey about views in Australia.We gave talks, had articles and letters published calling for Australia to have a similar inquiry into our forces joining the invasion of Iraq. We also called for the decision for Australia to go to war needing debate by both houses of parliament, instead of the current situation of being a captainês pick.MAPWA had speakers at the Independent and Peaceful Australia Network conference in Alice Springs about the health impacts of war in the context of our alliance with the USA and on nuclear weapons.Health workers under fire We have been lobbying government regarding health workers under fire in war zones, to support UN measures to provide better protections and independent investigations of all incidents.

Presbyterian Ladiesê College (PLC) is one of Australiaês largest girlsê schools with over 275 teaching and non-teaching sta , and a rich culturally diverse student population of over 1,600 from the Early Learning Centre (ELC) to Year 12. Although proud of its rich heritage, having been established in 1875, PLC very much re ects modern and forward-looking Melbourne. It provides a warm, welcoming, and cohesive community within which to educate todayês girls.As detailed in the Collegeês Memorandum of Association, the Collegeês Objectives are:? To provide for the students of the College an education of a humane, scienti c and general nature consistent with the values and principles of Christianity.? To provide religious instruction and education in the Holy Scriptures of theOld and New Testaments interpreted not inconsistently with the Westminster Confession of Faith, the 39 Articles of Religion of the Anglican Church and the Basis of Union of The Uniting Church in Australia.? To encourage each student to achieve the highest standard of which she is capable in all her activities.? To encourage the full development of the personality and sense of responsibility of each student.? To encourage in each student respect for others and the capacity to work with them.? To promote the development of the Christian ideals of good citizenship, sound personal character and a spirit of reverence in the entire life and work of the College.? To provide for the students of the College, opportunities for religious observance and worship not inconsistent with the usage of the Presbyterian Church.

Breast Cancer Network Australiaês (BCNA) vision is for a better journey for all Australians affected by breast cancer. We work to ensure they receive the very best support, information, treatment and care appropriate to their individual needs.We support, inform, represent and connect people whose lives have been affected by breast cancer.Every day in 2016, 43 women were told they have breast cancer. We know that no two breast cancer journeys are the same. Women differ in how they like to receive information and support. We develop and provide high quality information in a range of formats including information that can empower participation in decisions about treatment and care. Nearly 13,000 Australians newly diagnosed received our My Journey Kit in 2016, which goes some way towards providing that vital information and support.We know that it is not only the person diagnosed, but families, friends and whole communities that are affected by a breast cancer diagnosis. This is often a time when people turn to the internet.While there is plenty of helpful information to be found online, there is also information that may be unhelpful, inaccurate and scary. Our website provides a significant and credible resource for anyone looking for answers about breast cancer. The support of family, friends and colleagues is vital after a breast cancer diagnosis. However, even with a support network to draw on, our members often tell us their diagnosis made them feel isolated and alone. Communicating with someone who has experienced breast cancer can be of enormous benefit. In 2016, we connected our members in person and online. Since its launch in September, at all hours of the day and night, our new online network saw great geographic distances breached as visitors connected through their shared breast cancer experience.We also presented free information forums around the country. They provided information about the latest treatment and care, wellbeing, and services and support available in local communities. Our forums are developed from identified needs in the community and help establish connections with people who have had similar experiences.  Whether 10 days or 10 years post-diagnosis, all Australians affected by breast cancer deserve to have their needs represented and their voices heard wherever important decisions about breast cancer are made.We draw on the strength of our network to advocate on behalf of Australians affected by or at risk of breast cancer, and work to ensure best practice in treatment for all Australians. BCNA improved access to treatments in 2016 by successfully advocating for two key drugs to be made available through the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (PBS) _ Nolvadex (tamoxifen) for women at increased risk of developing breast cancer and Herceptin SC (the subcutaneous form of Herceptin). In 2016 alone, BCNA supported, informed, represented and connected many thousands of Australians affected by breast

mainly music (Australia) Limited is not only about music sessions. It exists to become a vital connection point for families in local Austrlaian communities.An African continent proverb states, It takes a village to raise a child. With that proverb underpinning some of our thinking, we encourage local groups to be that village. This extrapolates to being a place of care, an environment of learning, a setting where genuine encouragement provides mothers with the knowledge they are involved in a great and worthwhile role, and a space of fun, laughter and enjoyment.In a world of passive connection like Instagram and Facebook, mainly music provides an active connection, face-to-face, and memory-building.Here are comments passed on:mainly music is such a wonderful support for families just generally. And things like this [mainly music] are just what we need to keep our minds thinking positive thoughts. Thank you for all you do!!!Thank you for all the work that each of you ladies put into your amazing music sessions. I thought that you might like to hear the conversation that I had with Patrick while driving home today. He was reading his attendance certificate that he had been looking after with great pride. He piped up from the back seat, Hey Sarah, they love me!  I asked who? All the girls at music. Then he pretended to read the certificate out loud, We love Patrick. (hehehe)From a team member. Recently while shopping in my local supermarket, I encountered a young child, obviously distressed. He came around the corner of the aisle and approached me saying. _Blue shirt, blue shirt. Whereês Mum, I asked. He kept repeating the words _blue shirtî. A little while later, a worried looking young woman rounded the corner and a wave of relief washed over her face. Her son exclaimed loudly, with a sense of joy, _Mum, mum, blue shirtî. She looked at me and my attire and said _Oh, I see you are involved with mainly musicî. I realised I was wearing my mainly music T-shirt, having just come from our church's session. This mother and child do not attend our group, but he recognised the shirt and obviously thought I was a safe person to approach to help him find his Mum. I thank God for the mainly music program, and the impact it has _ sometimes in unexpected places!Aims and valuesThe organisation continues to uphold honour, connection, creativity, celebration and generosity as the five values from which to measure our activities and guide the planning and decision making. This ensures that the resources and support provided have an anchor point as well as an ongoing ´flavourê.

Backpacks 4 VIC Kids supplied children aged from birth to seventeen years with a care pack full of essential items and 'extra love' items to help them get through the first 24-48 hours of being removed or relocated from situations that were unsafe. Children receive our filled nappy bags and backpacks when entering out-of-home care or emergency accommodation. We supply packs by the clothing size and gender to DHHS, Foster and Kinship Care agencies, secure facilities, Victoria Police, emergency accommodation facilities and refuges, upon Supply Request. We do this without any funding and we do not charge for the packs, nor for delivery. We entrust and appreciate the agency and Child Protection workers taking on the responsibility of handing the most appropriate packs to children in necessitous circumstances. Often children are removed or relocated with little more than the clothes they are wearing. Donations and items bought from money fundraised are collected and sorted at our headquarters in Cranbourne, Victoria, then selections are made carefully and thoughtfully to ensure that packs include the most useful and needed items. Our packs not only give children some belongings of their own, encouraging self worth and a sense that someone cares, but also assist workers to focus more on the task of finding a safe location and carers more time to concentrate on welcoming and settling children being brought into their care. Prior to June 2, 2016, Backpacks 4 VIC Kids did not pay any overheads nor wages. We are hoping to successfully access funding as soon as possible as now we have a commercial premises with many overheads and our operational workload has increased significantly.

The Menês Tjilirra Movement partners CASSE with Aboriginal communities in Haasts Bluff (Ikuntji) , Mt Liebig (Amunturrngu), Kintore (Walungurru), Papunya (Warumpi)  and Kiwirrkurra in Australiaês central western desert region, with Remote Jobs Community Program (RJCP)  in collaboration with the Royal Flying Doctors Service.   Through the program CASSE achieves its purpose through the empowerment of local communities- bridging the gap between the traditional and current very different world.CASSE, in partnership with the Central Australian Aboriginal Congress (CAACAC,) aims to develop and evaluate an Aboriginal model of best practice of Menês sheds in Central Australia that can provide support for men to heal from traumatic experiences and support the empowerment of men in their communities in order to create safe and supportive communities for all members. CASSE Australia has also been working in partnership with the Central Australian Aboriginal Congress (CAAC) since 2011 to understand and address issues of violence and underlying trauma that currently exist within Aboriginal communities.  This helps address CASSE's purpose and goal to develop and secure relations and psychological wellbeing in vulnerable societal groups.Further, CASSE contributes funds to the AAAC annual Horse Cultural Trek, funding two Aboriginal elders to mentor the youth on the ten day trek.  The AAAC Cultural Horse Trek builds strength, capacity, connections and spirit on country- thus helping to achieve CASSE's purpose of creating supportive environments for the development of pride, purpose and value in vulnerable communities.

We helped secure a state renewable energy target in Victoria (a VRET) of 25% renewable energy by 2020 and 40% by 2025. It is expected to double wind energy capacity in the state by 2020 and triple renewable energy capacity by 2025, creating 10,000 jobs and unlocking a $2.5 billion investment opportunity in the process. It is expected to cut carbon emissions in the state by around 15%.We helped sustain the moratorium on onshore gas drilling in the state of Victoria. FoEA invested considerable time and effort into involvement in the SA Royal Commission into nuclear waste, producing extensive research materials and submissions. We also participated in the SA government's 'Citizens Jury' process as an invited witness.We researched the likely social and environmental implications of synthetic biology and new genetic modification (GM) techniques, to identify potential risks.We worked to ensure that ingredients derived from new technologies such as nanotechnology, synthetic biology and new genetic engineering techniques undergo adequate safety testing.We completed a major research project into pesticide contamination in waterways across Australia. The impacts of many chemicals on freshwater ecosystems (for instance on amphibians) is widely documented.We researched many commonly used chemicals (for instance Simazine) and produced education materials on the impacts on natural ecosystems and ways to reduce harm and/or minimise the use of these chemicals in land management practises.We provided major research support for the Australian Pesticide Map, which highlights which pesticides have been detected across the Australian landscape.We worked to ensure the Regional Planning Scheme for the Atherton Tablelands in far north QLD adequately protected World Heritage listed landscapes from inappropriate development.We helped establish a new initiative called Cassowary Keystone Conservation, which aims to reduce predation on cassowaries and other native wildlife by wild dogs.We helped support the work of Frog Safe, which is a group that researches the cause of the decline in frog numbers, which is mainly attributed to a new class of pesticides.We have been supporting the campaign to eradicate yellow crazy ants which is an invasive foreign pest in the Kuranda and Cairns areas which spreads quickly and eradicates virtually all native species. We worked with plantation owners and managers in a number of states to improve land management and remnant indigenous species within their plantations (through actions like wider buffer zones and wildlife corridors).We engaged with Australian, US and European banks, calling on them to avoid investment in new fossil fuel projects on environmental and human rights grounds.We hold concerns about the possibility some trade agreements to undermine the ability of the government to adequately protect the natural environment. We carried out a range of research, education, lobby and public outreach efforts highlighting dangers of ISD

View our full Annual Report at: http://snuffpuppets.com/wp-content/blogs.dir/933/files/2017/05/2016-Annual-Report.pdfFrom Snuff Puppets Artistic Director/CEO, Andy Freer:Iêm writing this now in the 25th year of Snuff Puppets existence. Amazing where we have come to, all the while retaining our core principles of experimentation, collaboration, challenging the status-quo, exploring the unknown, making art with a multiplicity of peoples and cultures worldwide, consistently breaking through the ordinary, and creating the extraordinary. 2016 was one of our busiest and most successful years to date. The company undertook 12 local engagements, 5 national presentations and 4 International tours all managed by an amazing hard working team of dedicated staff and artists.Despite funding cuts 2016 saw Snuff Puppets continue to do what it does best. Two new works created internationally through workshops and collaboration. A major international presentation of our biggest and newest work to date, Everybody, and a new in-house puppet training and exhibition model that brought and brings a whole new eager audience and participation into the wonderful world of Snuff Puppets.A big part and the gritty reality of this wonderful world of Snuff Puppets is the managing and maintenance of hundreds of giant puppets that have been created, brought to life, travel the world then come home to rest in Footscray: their home a giant corrugated tin shed built in 1905. With the ongoing support of Creative Victoria and Maribrynong City Council we are able to create, house and manage this enormous collection of giant puppets in Snuff Puppets HQ the Footscray Drill Hall. For the first time in 2016 Snuff Puppets hosted numerous in-house events and workshops in the Drill Hall that saw hundreds of curious public come through our doors, looking, listening and participating in the Snuff Puppets world and philosophy. To be intimately engaged locally with our audience resonates deeply with the companyês ethos and it is hoped that this kind of public program of activity will grow and continue for years to come, expanding the function of the Drill Hall into a locally and internationally recognised building for the creation and experience of giant puppets, theatre and art making. Thatês the dream but for now 2017 is reality, 2016 a mere memory and 2020ês where itês at, full steam ahead.

column2: The Australian Council For Educational Research Limited
column41: The Australian Council for Educational Research Limitedês (ACER) mission is to create and promote research-based knowledge, products and services that can be used to improve learning across the life span. ACER is involved in the collection, analysis, interpretation and use of reliable information to assist educational decision makers _ from individual teachers to system leaders and policy makers _ in two ways: to help them help learners by identifying educational progress and challenges, and to help them identify and implement effective policies and practices on the basis of good evidence. ACER works both within Australia and internationally, and focuses on supporting learners and their needs, supporting the learning professionals who work with those learners, supporting those who maintain the educational institutions and systems in which learners and learning professionals work, and supporting our learning society. The mission of the ACER Foundation is to work in collaboration with external partners to initiate, establish and manage projects that address the needs of educationally disadvantaged groups in the community. The Foundationês projects may be funded by corporate, government or philanthropic bodies, or by ACER itself. For further information see the latest ACER Annual Report: www.acer.edu.au/about/annual-reports

column39: Advancing the science of astronomy
column41: AAL pursued its charitable purpose of advancing the science of astronomy by allocating, contracting with and supplying funds to organisations for the establishment, development,enhancement or operation of, or for access to, astronomy research infrastructure.AAL invested $10.6M in 2015/16, giving Australian researchers access to facilities worth more than $500M. Over 2900 astronomers used the AAL funded facilities in 2015/16, of whom 54% were Australian-based researchers and 46% were international collaborators.In 2015/16, AAL provided funding under the National Collaborative Research Infrastructure Scheme to keep critical facilities, such as the Murchison Widefield Array and gSTAR GPUpowered supercomputer, operating. Funding was also provided for the Australian Square Kilometre Array Pathfinder and access to overseas telescopes.Further funding was provided for development and operation of the All-Sky Virtual Observatory, which was mainly funded by the National eResearch Collaboration Tools and Resources.Access to AAL-supported facilities resulted in publication of 313 refereed journal papers from collaborative research projects, with 80% of the publications involving Australian-international collaborations. These publications span a wide range of astronomical fields, including radio, optical, theoretical, and high-energy astrophysics.Details of AAL activities are in the 2015/16 Annual Report athttp://astronomyaustralia.org.au/files/publications/combined%20file%20for%20web.pdf

Human Variome Project International Limited maintains an international consortium of researchers, policy makers and health care professionals working to integrate the free and open collection, curation, interpretation and sharing of the world's genomic knowledge into routine clinical care. The Human Variome Project works with consortium members, Ministries of Health and other relevant stakeholders in individual countries to build capacity around medical genetic and genomics and develop knowledge sharing initiatives and infrastructure. National repositories of de-identified genetic variation information and their effect on human health and well-being that are affiliated with the Human Variome Project form part of a global knowledge sharing architecture. This means that a particular finding made in an accredited diagnostic laboratory in any one country in the network is immediately available to assist in the diagnosis and treatment of patients in all countries. This leads to faster, cheaper and more accurate diagnostic tests, treatment options and more robust and cost-effective health service delivery planning. In the last financial year, the HVP Country Node network grew to twenty three countries in six continents and is an official associate partner of UNESCO and has a MOU with the World Health Organisation

MCRI undertakes research into infant, child and adolescent health. During the last financial year our researchers worked to make discoveries to prevent and treat common and rare childhood conditions. Research took place over the areas of laboratory work, clinical research and broad population health studies and addressed five main research themes _ cell biology, clinical sciences, genetics, infection and immunity and population health. In addition, cross-disciplinary research programs bring together research from across the main themes. Due to its size, MCRI can bring together large teams of researchers to work on related areas to stimulate scientific collaboration, both within MCRI as well as nationally and internationally.Major strategic initiatives undertaken during the year included: the Gen V study aimed at improving current standard models of care; development of genomics and personalised medicine to improve child health outcomes; Global Health program to support and implement research addressing health issues of the worldês poorest children; health service research aimed at improving healthcare and education delivery to children; Stem cell medicine program preparing Australia for delivery of human stem cell-based products and clinical practices; and establishment of a single clinical and community trial precinct to deliver the latest clinical trials and care to children.Further information can be found at https://www.mcri.edu.au/aboutThe MCRI annual report is available at https://www.mcri.edu.au/about/annual-reports

Australian Book Review (ABR) is one of Australiaês leading cultural magazines. Created in 1961, it publishes reviews, essays, commentaries and new creative writing. The magazine is national in readership, authorship, distribution, partners and influence. It is available in print and via ABR Online. ABRês diverse programs include three prestigious international prizes, writersê fellowships each worth $7,500, special issues, national events, and paid editorial internships.ABR is a fully independent non-profit organisation. Its primary aims are several: to foster high critical standards; to provide an outlet for fine new writing; and to contribute to the preservation of literary values and a full appreciation of Australiaês literary heritage.ABR is committed to highlighting the strengths critical and creative writing around Australia and presenting them to an international audience. The magazine is unusually open to new talent, including younger writers and critics. We pay for everything we publish _ print and online _ and our rates have more than doubled in the past two years.Through ABR Arts, ABR now engages with the full culture and publishes lengthy, stylish, timely reviews of new films, plays, operas, concerts, dance, and art exhibitions.

Over the past year we facilitated the establishment of 8 new community gardens across Melbourne, along with our first expansion into more rural communities facilitating projects in Wangaratta and Mildura. We have relaunched our website to create a more user friendly platform to connect people with land, resources and each other. We have advocated for changes in the Victorian Government's planning policy and prepared a set of draft guidelines to address the changes we believe will reduce the regulatory burden impeding the establishment of more community gardens in urban environments. We also built on our strategic relationships with significant statutory land holders such as Melbourne Water, with whom we are now working in partnership on a number of projects to better utilize their land as an asset for the wider community.We have also coordinated and delivered a range of multi-scale events throughout the year to promote awareness and engagement with urban food growing - from practical skill sharing workshops and working bees, to facilitation seminars on community garden establishment and management, to a number of large scale community festivals to promote local and sustainable food growing.

column39: distribution of hygiene essentials
column41: The continued rapid growth and awareness of our concept this year has resulted in significantly higher numbers of product donations from both individuals and corporate/community groups.  This has meant an additional 5 major projects have been created with the focus to reach some of the more rural communities of Victoria and down the eastern sea board. The most significant of these _ Rotary and Lions club collaboration on a Personal Care Project providing small/isolated at high risk towns with relief from various situations of disadvantage and in anticipation of the dangerous bush fire/flood season period. This project alone was an 80,000 product investment and continues to grow. We have expanded aid into to area of street sex workers and prostitutes where customised products packs (both essential and non-essential items) are used as engagement tools to help rehabilitate lives. Our vital school support program has also continued to grow _ now reaching into areas of NSW in addition to the 50 plus schools in 4 major regions across Victoria who order twice a year to support students in need.We have continued our strong focus on promoting the role personal hygiene products play on our everyday lives and the key role they have in rehabilitating that of the homeless in particular. Using various large scale event key note speaking invitations- we have educated over 15,000 students and professionals of our mission, vital statistics on personal hygiene product access and affordability for every day Australians. This has resulted in group volunteer packing days, work experience students and an increase in our regular volunteer list.

column4: Currently SCA Operates From the Premises
column41: Specialisterne Australia was formed on 11th September 2015. As a result of Specialisterne Australiaês activities during 2016, at 30th June 2016, 35 people with Autism Spectrum Disorder were employed in long term career roles that utilised their unique talents and capabilities and provided them with appropriate career and personal support. In addition, during 2016 Specialisterne Australia promoted the opportunity to hire people with ASD in order to attract unique talents capable of adding strength to the workforce. As a result, five additional organisations had committed to programs in 2016/17 which will translate into career opportunities for a further 60 people with ASD in roles in IT, Cyber security, records management, engineering and animal husbandry.It is anticipated that by June 2017 Specialisterne Australia will have created long term career positions in major Australian companies for over 150 people with ASD. A great start on our goal of 12,000 jobs by 2025.A key to the success of the Specialisterne program is our ability to reach potential employees with ASD when job opportunities arise. By establishing relationships with the major Autism bodies in Australia and understanding the capabilities of existing Disability Employment Services providers we have been able to establish a very effective pipeline to talent. In addition, by participating in industry events and through the development of a social media communication platform using Facebook and LinkedIn we have made direct contact with over 3000 people with ASD and their families. During 2016 a generous donation of $30,000 from the Telematics Trust Course Development Fund will allow us to develop a program of STEMLabs to allow people with ASD to assess their skills ahead of employment. This will have the added benefit of establishing a pipeline of talent for future employment programs.Looking forward we have plans to establish programs across Australia and also to extend our services to meet the needs of small to medium businesses who often lack the resources to independently administer diversity initiatives like ours. We have designed a program that will allow smaller employers to join together to manage an effective program that can attract and assess autistic program and also draw on shared support resources to help their new colleagues to succeed.

column39: Social work interviews, through office appointments, home visits, or telephone counselling.Retrieval of historic institutional documents that provide information about early life and separation from family; and records that reveal family medical histories.Counselling in relation to the long term impact of institutional abuse on personal identity and family relationships.Pre and post reunion counselling.Resolution of citizenship status.Advocacy to assist former child migrants address issues of justice and recognition.
column41: CMT activities broadly fall into two categories, family restoration and counselling in relation to historic, childhood institutional abuse.  It may assist to provide a brief overview of the issues and human consequences arising from the Commonwealth Child Migration Scheme, which have now been the subject of Government Apologies in both Australia and the UK.Approximately 7000 children aged 3-15 were deported from the UK to Australia without their families between 1912-1970.  Of that total, approximately half were sent during the post war years 1947-58.  These are the Trust's primary clients in Australia.  The human cost of child migration was profound;  we estimate more than 90% experienced physical or sexual abuse in Australian institutions.  Most never received adequate documentation and as a result lived their adult lives without information about their personal or family identity, nor a truthful understanding of the reasons for their original separation from their family.In addition, many children were deceived by those responsible for their care, that they were orphans, or 'war orphans';  which prevented many from searching for their families until it was too late to find them.  Parents were often told by churches and charities that their children had been adopted in England, whereas they had actually been deported to cold, brutal institutions in Australia.

New Life Evangelical Church (NLEC) is based in Melbourne, Victoria serving the local community and supporting the overseas mission. The purpose of our Church is to bring people to a life-changing encounter with Jesus Christ; to disciple them in such a way that they enter into a life-changing and transformative relationship with Jesus Christ. Through teaching, fellowship, Worship, evangelism and mission we endeavor to fulfill Christês Great Commission.Our main activities over last year are: (a) Weekly services: NLEC holds weekly services in English, Mandarin and Cantonese.(b) Discipleship training: programs are ongoing in all congregations (c) Fellowship: As a large church, NLEC is mindful of strong Christian bond among members. Life group ministry is vital for living out Jesus commandment, _to love one anotherî. We have a very high participation rate in life groups among all three congregations. (d) Leadership development: we invited guest speakers to train our leaders; organized leadership training, retreat, and sending pastors/leaders to attend conferences and to pursue further theological studies.(e) Pastors appointment: appointed a pastor in the Mandarin congregation and re-appointed a pastor in the Cantonese congregation(f) Property acquisition: NLEC has acquired a property in Bayswater. Our vision is to build a hub church that different congregations can gather together in one site.(g) Evangelism: our home based outreach programs in Cantonese, Mandarin, and Alpha course in English congregation have been very fruitful. Many have come to Christ through these programs.(h) Mission: we continue to support our missionary in China and to partner with mission organizations. Many of our members are encouraged and inspired by their experiences during their short term trips. Domestically, some of our members are also participating in the outreach program in various towns in the remote areas.

column41: Penington Instituteês vision is that communities are safe, healthy and empowered to manage drug use.Our mission is to actively support the adoption of approaches to drug use which promote safety and human dignity.We understand that:_ The ´war on drugsê approach has failed. Innovative approaches connecting substance use research to practical action are required._ The drug control system should emphasise public safety and public health._ Substantive change is required. Change should be driven by evidence, transparency and cost-effectiveness _ not fear and prejudice._ Prioritising personal responsibility, family and community will empower people and yield better results than centralised government drug control.Key outcome areas:1. Encourage and empower people affected by drug use to make safe and healthy choices.Penington Institute works to: ‚ Increase individualsê health literacy and capacity.‚ Promote public discussion and understanding _ contributing to a community rethink on how to tackle drug use, promoting hope and eliminating stigma. ‚ Raise awareness and educate people from diverse communities about the harms associated with drug use and ways to reduce them.2. Support professionalsê capacity to deliver high quality interventions to address the harms associated with drug use. Penington Institute works to:‚ Deliver professional development and support to various groups and workforces.‚ Develop resources using all available media to support the delivery of interventions.‚ Facilitate the sharing of ideas and connections between services, professional groups and workforces impacting local communities.‚ Help individuals and organisations to overcome their resistance to working with people affected by drug use, promoting a civilised approach to improve health and wellbeing.3. Achieve the right policy and legal frameworkPenington Institute works to: ‚ Review evidence of and support for effective policy and interventions.‚ Recommend further research to address gaps in the evidence base.‚ Engage with policy makers in government and with communities to address the challenge of drug use in an integrated and comprehensive way and with a focus on public health and public safety.‚ Partner and engage with communities, and the public and private sectors to effect change.4. Build a dynamic, engaged and sustainable organisationPenington Institute will:‚ Ensure a high standard of corporate governance.‚ Improve systems and processes to ensure a well-managed, efficient and effective workplace.‚ Develop and support staff and volunteer engagement and capability.‚ Generate financial resources to ensure effectiveness and sustainability.

Communities That Care Ltd is a not for profit training and consulting company formed with the objective of implementing, evaluating and disseminating strategies for building community prevention capacity in Australia. Our vision is to _work with communities to build prevention capacity, strengthen relationships and advocate for the widespread adoption of prevention strategies throughout the Australian communityî. In 2015 to 2016 our company achieved our seven strategic performance targets to progress our charitable purposes relating to the three areas of: A. Funding: (Performance Target PT1) We maintained funding from contracts with the Victorian Government Department of Justice and Regulation, VicRoads, Transport Accident Commission and through community agencies. This enabled us to maintain our core staff - Rachel Smith and Dr Bosco Rowland worked as Deputy Chief Executive Officers, and Tina Hosseini and Amber Donnelly as Community Relations Officers; and (PT2) we maintained funding to increase support for our community partners. B. Capacity. (PT3) Two new Directors were appointed - Dr Nicola Reavley and David Ali; (PT4) Our Chief Executive Officer Professor John Toumbourou worked with the Australian Research Alliance for Children and Youth to develop the What Works for Kids website that will provide the foundation for revising our Prevention Strategies Guide. C. Community Progress. (PT5) Phase 1 and Phase 2 training events were completed in two new communities in Stonnington and Mandurah Western Australia. (PT6) Community readiness for prevention  was measurable advanced (based progress on assessment of our five Phase model) in Communities That Care sites in - Bendigo, Cardinia, Geelong, Knox, Mornington Peninsula Shire, Myrtleford, Yarra, and Warrnambool; (PT7) Working with our partners at Deakin University economic evaluation analyses were progressed with NHMRC funding.

Our success has come through a shared vision and effort by our teams in Australia and in Nepal, a lot of hard work, and our very generous and dedicated supporter base.Whilst not without their challenges, exacerbated by the major earthquakes that struck Nepal in April and May 2015 which impacted many of the families we support, our programs in Nepal continued to move ahead in a positive direction;‚ 100 new children were provided education scholarships, taking the total to 581‚ 15 more children and youth were permanently reintegrated back to family from our Residential Child Care Home, taking the youth in our reintegration program to 32 ‚ 5 new children joined our Residential Child Care Home, taking the total to 44 ‚ 39 more youth attained their School Leaving Certificate (SLC) and 12 passed year 12‚ 250 children were supported indirectly through sponsorship of 17 teachers and school staff at our community school‚ More youth moved towards a life of independence in various fields of work In addition to our regular programs, SCAI Nepal worked tirelessly on the ground to provide immediate assistance following the earthquake, including distribution of over 3500 tarpaulins, mosquito nets and torches, some food and medical items, 156 temporary shelters for single mothers, tin for classrooms at 17 schools, 34 large games/sports kits and pre-fabricated classroom blocks at 3 schools.

Peninsula Community Legal Centre Inc. provided free legal services on a wide range of legal issues, with ongoing assistance targeted to clients experiencing disadvantage. During 2015/16 the Centre assisted 7,966 clients with legal advice, undertook 3,109 cases and provided court and tribunal assistance including representations for 2,167 clients. The overwhelming majority of clients that accessed the Centre in 2015/16 were on low and/or no incomes with 75% earning less than $500 pw, with  50% of clients reporting government benefits as their main source of income. Clients were able to access the Centre's services by daily telephone intake services and appointment sessions both during the day and evenings. Client activity sessions were conducted at our Frankston, Cranbourne, Bentleigh, Rosebud and Frankston North branches as well as visiting services in Dandenong, Chelsea, Hastings and Mornington. The Centre undertakes community legal education which aims to increase awareness about legal issues, how to deal with them and where to get help.

column41: The Foundation provides programs that aim to reconnect marginalised and disadvantaged people with their community. Our community meals and community pantry program provide easy access to fresh, nutritious and welcoming meals and hampers to the Melbourne community. In 2016 we delivered more than 15,000 sit down meals across the City of Port Phillip. We prepackaged more than 9,500 take away meals for people that are unable to attend our programs and distributed more than 6,000 hampers of fresh fruit, vegetables and other essential items. Our education programs supported 14 young people in secondary education with scholarships and our mentoring and tutoring program engaged many local young people to assist them in their studies. Our volunteer group filled around 2, 475 different shifts across the year to make it all possible and supported our 3 staff members with fundraising events, meal preparation and mentoring. During the period when a fire damaged our warehouse space and closed the building for 2 months our volunteers and staff opened up their homes to continue the service and not one meal program was cancelled. Our partnership with Monash Oakleigh Legal Service has allowed clients to access legal support in a welcoming and non confrontational manner - it has also assisted in educating law students about the realities and practicalities of working with marginalised people. Free counselling services and case management support, offered by volunteers and managed by a staff member continue to be important and critical local services.

Summary Statement from Christ Church Hawthorn  drawing on material presented to the  Annual Parish Meeting, 13th November 2016 by the Vicar, Church Wardens and Parish Council  This year the wardens have been Raechel Forster, Peter Whitehill and Susan Block. We are grateful for their input and collaboration. Staff and volunteers: We are grateful for the hard work and commitment of Andrew. We farewelled Steve Sonneman in March. Steve was a valuable member of staff and together with his wife Jenny, made a substantial contribution to our community. We are grateful for the presence of Steve, Jenny and their children in our lives. Olivia Yarlett has been a stalwart in the office. She has managed the administration of the church in a very capable and timely way. She has also made an important and appreciated contribution to our Wood Hall program. Amy Dircks has also been a very active participant in the life of our church. She has managed a childrenês program in Wood Hall, has shared in the Kidsê Church program. Josh Coulson, and earlier Alyce Verheijden have conducted a mentoring program for our young adolescent. Similarly, James and Lookkaid have given generously to the Kidsê Church program. Mei Whitehill and John Lucas have generously contributed many hours to our financial management.  We have a core group of very generous musicians. They have numerous skills and talents and we appreciate their commitment to our services.  Our congregation members lead community groups, co-ordinate outreach activities, cater for morning teas, manage the AV for our services, maintain our propertyê organise social events and generally support CCH. Finally, our Parish Council members have worked hard with us throughout the year. We have been blessed to have participants on the Council from each service group, with a range of ages, backgrounds, expertise and experience.  Property: Planning for the management of the property and stewardship of the physical resources was highlighted by the Wardens and Parish Council in 2015. Continuing that process, we have been active in several ways. Peter Whitehill has managed ongoing repairs, co-ordinated working bees, managed the repair of the carpet in the main hall and organised sub-floor work in the Wood Hall in preparation for the repair of the floor there. A working group has been formed to co-ordinate planning for the new kitchen for the Memorial Hall.  Longer term property plans include the renewal of the toilet block and replacement of the carpet in the main hall. With much thinking and praying and discussing, the PC articulated a new Christ Church Vision Beliefs and Values Statement.   A new kitchen for the Memorial Hall is the most significant development right now, but the Parish Council has also been exploring a bigger development for the church property. There is always need of generous financial help for the continuing property management and development.

column2: Empower Australia Overseas Aid Fund Inc
column41: AID AND RELIEF Our Aid and Relief program has two dimensions: Emergency Relief In nations troubled by conflict and natural disasters, Empower Australia Overseas Aid (EAOAF) seeks to provide emergency relief as required. This includes all circumstantial relief, rather than ongoing assistance. Assistance to the poor EAOAF provides practical and economic assistance to the poor, to help them achieve a better future. Local social workers identify needs among local villages, and the wider community. National Centres of Leadership Development & Management Training Our indigenous leaders felt the need to start some Centres for Leadership and Management. These centres help identify potential leaders from existing social workers as well as the wider community and provide them with: ‚ Leadership and management skills ‚ mentoring ‚ Practical training in Administration and Management with special focus on Computer and Internet Technology, Accounting and English . ‚ Teaching and communication skills. DEEP CORE BORE WELLS Installation of deep core bore wells continues in places where access to water is a problem, particularly for the marginalized and poor. The sustainable community benefit is clear. TOILETS AND SANITATION Open defecation is part of their everyday life for an estimated 636 million people in Asia. This has dramatic consequences on human health, dignity and security, education, the environment, and social and economic development _ particularly for vulnerable populations such as persons with disabilities and women, who are more exposed to sexual violence. We have started this project to build 1000 public toilet blocks, all in communities where EAOAF has an existing social worker and network of people. SAFE HOMES FOR CHILDREN India has an estimated 27 million street children. Without the security of a family and home, street children face an alarming array of physical, psychological and social threats. Whether they were abandoned, trafficked, lost or are runaways, the immediate survival and future thriving of these street children is dependent on finding a safe place. 30 boys and 32 girls are currently in care.
