Hope For Tomorrow Inc is a not for profit organisation whose main purpose is to work directly to relieve hunger, homelessness, poverty, sickness and suffering for people who are in need of direct relief.  Hope For Tomorrow is raising awareness of sustainable change, social inclusions and empowerment for people who are homeless or at risk of homelessness. We are committed to the community by providing compassionate services to marginalised residents throughout Victoria. Hope For Tomorrow supports all people, all ages, from birth to elderly, culturally and linguistically diverse (CALD) people, by building relationships with families and individuals in need, creating avenues of trust. Together we supported and assisted 87  people who are experiencing homelessness or at risk with emergency food relief, essential clothing and personal items and link into much needed supports; mental health services, legal support, family violence support and community education.We encourage our clients and volunteers to be involved in our community education projects by breaking down the barriers of understanding, which helps create a more inclusive community where all people can become more confident about participating in activities that are informative and educational.

column2: The Centre For Excellence In Child And Family Welfare Inc.
column41: 2015-16 was a year of significant collaboration between the Centre, sector and government in creating and implementing a change agenda to improve the lives of vulnerable children and families.The Centre looked to build its membership base to ensure we have a strong collective voice for advocating on behalf of children and families, but also to ensure we have a strong network for sharing knowledge and expertise and collective problem-solving.The Centre took on important projects in 2015-16, including managing the Fostering Connections project on behalf of the sector to recruit more foster carers for children in need, as well as the Raising Expectations project aimed at encouraging more young people leaving care into higher education.Through all of our work, we have sought to advance the rights of children and young people experiencing vulnerability _ through our project and social research work; through our collaborations with sector colleagues; through our strategic policy and campaign advocacy efforts; and through our work building capacity and knowledge across the sector.Throughout 2015-16, the Centre increased its advocacy activities, running a community-focused Federal election campaign aimed at raising awareness of key issues facing children, young people and families experiencing vulnerability and disadvantage.In collaboration with the sector, the Centre also promoted the interests of children and families through policy advocacy at a state and national level.The Centre contributed submissions on a range of policy issues ensuring the issues and needs of children, young people and families experiencing vulnerability were considered in Government policy development.  Throughout 2015-16, the Centre worked closely with the sector, researchers, Government and allied organisations to enhance the delivery of services and supports to children, young people and families across Victoria.The Centre worked closely with child, youth and family services professionals to build their skills and knowledge in key areas and help to engender a sector culture of continuous improvement and innovative practice.The Centre delivered a range of learning and development opportunities to build the knowledge and capacity of sector practitioners.The Centre ran a series of sector network forums in 2015-16, providing an important opportunity for people to come together with other professionals in their area of expertise.Centre staff focused on building a strong organisation, responsive to the needs of the sector, well-connected across the community, able to work effectively with Government to deliver good outcomes and with a clear direction for the future.http://cfecfw.asn.au/sites/default/files/CFECFW_AnnualReport16(A4)_web(spreads).pdf

column2: Institute Of Notre Dame Des Missions Inc
column41: The Sisters of Our Lady of the Missions ( Institute of Notre Dame des Missions ), an international missionary community of women founded in Lyon, France in 1861 by a courageous and visionary woman, Euphrasie Barbier. Her deeply contemplative spirit enabled her to recognise God's immense love for all people in every nation and culture. Following her lead the Sisters of Our Lady of the Missions dedicate themselves to humanitarian works of charity particularly among those marginalised in society. They work as teachers, nurses, social workers in formal and informal education, health care and nutrition s well as community development programs in villages, parishes and small communities, wherever they can offer their services. The Sisters are committed in a special way to working with women and with the young because they believe that when you educate women you help to educate families and build a better world.. As an international community the sisters promote hum an rights, economic justice and a culture of reconciliation and peace. Today there are 1,000 Sisters of Our Lady of the Missions from many different cultures working in 22 countries: Australia, Bangladesh, Canada, China, England, France, India, Italy, Ireland,  Kenya, Laos, Myanmar, New Zealand, Philippines,  Senegal, Sudan and Vietnam

In 2016 Earthwatch continued to  undertake critical research uniting citizens and scientists to protect the integrity and diversity of life on Earth and to transform the way business, government and individuals think and act in relation to nature.In the year of 2015-2016, Earthwatch Australia supported a total of 16 national and 1 international research projects engaging thousands of members of society. These projects were delivered through scientific partnerships with 34 national research institutions (10 universities, 18 state or federal government institution and six NGOs). The projects span across our four priority research areas: Climate Change, Wildlife and Ecosystems, Ocean Health and Archaeology and Cultural Heritage.Earthwatch also formed a new partnership with Orpheus Island Resort, broadening opportunities for involvement in our vital research on the Great Barrier Reef. We expanded our existing partnership with Qantas, providing ongoing opportunities for indigenous students to engage in experiential STEM and we sent a record number of teachers into the field on TeachLive.

column41: The Cerebral Palsy Support Network (CPSN) is a not-for-profit organisation providing information and support services to people living with cerebral palsy and their families. We help empower individuals to lead more independent lives and provide support in a variety of ways to their families.The CPSN office is based in Melbourne, Australia and offers people a number of programs and services throughout Victoria.At the Cerebral Palsy Support Network, the focus is on our members and in providing the best possible service for every person. Each person is unique and our members are no different. We assess and address the needs of all of our members individually.Our vision is that we are known leaders empowering people with cerebral palsy and their networks to flourish through the provision of support, resources and services. We are highly adaptable and responsive to changing needs.Our mission is to empower and enable people with cerebral palsy and their networks to maximise their choices and opportunities.

With an emphasis on improvisation, The Australian Art Orchestra (AAO) explores the meeting points between disciplines and cultures, and imagines new musical forms to reflect the energy and diversity of 21st century Australia. In 2016 the Australian Art Orchestra led and resourced activities with other cultural traditions, provided workshops for young musicians, advocated for Australian music, provided employment for Australlan composers and musicians, and conducted an annual programme of activities. The Australian Art Orchestra's activities reflected our mission to create opportunities for composers and musicians, to facilitate cross-cultural conversation and learning, to advocate for new Australian contemporary music and, to be an ambassador for Australian music internationally.The AAO has completed a year of exceptional work that has been rewarding for audiences, board members, musicians, composers and workshop subscribers alike. Artistic Director, Peter Knightês programme has branched into new areas while continuing to build upon the legacy of his predecessor, Paul Grabowsky (1994-2012). Peterês outreach programme for young musicians through the Creative Music Intensive, in its third iteration in 2016, is going from strength to strength. New commissions and collaborations with composers, like Nicole Lizee (CAN), and Alvin Lucier were not only artistically desirable, they also attracted invitations from festivals that, in turn, afforded the AAO audiences in major venues that were supported by the festivalês marketing. A new work, Diomira by Peter Knight won the 2016 Albert H Maggs Award and will be developed into a full-length concert work in 2017. Southern Cross Care (Vic) (SCCV) is a Catholic not-for-profit aged care provider, and has been supporting older Victorians across metropolitan Melbourne and regional Victoria since 1969. Currently SCCV provides services to more than 3,000 client per annum supporting them to live a meaningful and fulfilling life.  A life where older people are supported to make decisions relating to their care and support.  This work is supported by SCCVês Imagine Fund, a fund that was established to support people who are socially and financially disadvantaged access to funds for necessary equipment and life experiences that they would not otherwise be able to afford.Our vision to see older people living well has led to the development of our ´Valuing Every Personê (VEP) philosophy which was implemented across the Organisation early last year.  VEP advocates a unique person-centred approach to the care and support which is central to the work we do with clients and residents. VEP is made up of three key components, i.e. Spiritual Wellbeing, Healthy Active Ageing, and Valued Roles, and underpinned by five principles: ‚ A good life _ living a meaningful and fulfilling life‚ Honour _ honouring a personês experiences, hopes and dreams‚ Relationships _ maintaining good relationships ‚ Choice _ respecting a personês right to choice and decision-making‚ Image _ influencing how we think through action and words

The principal activity of Business for Millennium Development Ltd during the financial year was to encourage and facilitate inclusive business activities by Australian companies that contribute to the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) (ended January 2016) and the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGês).B4MD continued its joint collaboration with the Business Call to Action (BCtA) to identify companies in Southeast Asia and the Pacific that have implemented these inclusive business models. The purpose of this collaboration was to build a new presence in these markets where BCtA has not previously been active, build a new pipeline of potential BCtA member companies and to engage in advocacy around inclusive business in the region on behalf of the BCtA. Acting as regional partner to the BCtA, B4MD secured 10 new member companies for BCtA across Australia, Singapore, Thailand, Bhutan and Indonesia. The organisation also carried out thought leadership activity through a series of events in Indonesia, Singapore and Australia in partnership with BCtA. These events were attended by over 550 people. The formal partnership concluded in June 2016.In November 2015 B4MD launched a new website detailing case studies of the organisationês lead projects in order to demonstrate how B4MD creates inclusive business initiatives in partnership with the private sector.In November 2015 B4MD was a lead partner of the Responsible Business Forum on Sustainable Development in Singapore. As the leading sustainability event in the region, the Forum was attended by NGOs and policy makers from around the world to share practical solutions to achieve the SDGs.Throughout the course of the year the organisation was represented as inclusive business subject matter experts providing best practice insights at a series of partner events in Australia, China, the Philippines, USA, New Zealand, Singapore, Indonesia and Kenya. In June 2016 B4MD was commissioned by the Asian Development to lead its China Inclusive Business Market Scoping Study. The objective of the study is to provide an overview of inclusive business models in China and Chinese companies with inclusive business models abroad as well discuss opportunities to strengthen the enabling environment for inclusive business support in China.

Eastern Victoria GP Training Limited (EV) was contracted by the Commonwealth Department of Health to deliver the Australian General Practice Training Program from 1 January 2016 in the eastern half of Victoria. During the past 12 months, EV has trained medical registrars to specialise as General Practitioners in a training footpirnt from Richmond in Melbourne, through Gippsland to the east coast of the state, and up to the Murray River on the border with New South Wales. EV had 358 registrars in training during 2016, of which 88 were fellowed and became members of the two GP Colleges. It is through this ongoing training program that EV increases to pool of GPs in both metro and rural communities, which in turn improves the level of primary healthcare services in these communities. Through the delivery of the AGPT Program and the training of medical registrars to specialise as GPs, this allows EV to meet its charity purpose to assist in the prevention and control of human diseases in the wider community, and through the GPs that it trains, the relief of pain and suffering. EV also has specific training workshops in its training program that focuses on indigenous healthcare. Through these workshops and in-house cultural educators, EV widens a registrar's training experience so that they are better placed to engage with the ATSI community on healthcare issues, and in doing so, support the Closing the Gap initiatives of the Commonwealth. This also involves the administration of:‚ 1500 volunteers across the state,‚ 18-20 rostered casual staff,‚ training of volunteers and staff,‚ communication with current and potential donors (30,000),‚ a complex database, automated SMS and email and direct internet contact,‚ processing of 11,800 donations,‚ marketing, media and education programs

column41: Red Stitch is Australiaês leading actorsê ensemble. Established in 2002, we are unique in our structure: an artist-driven company led by our resident actors with the support of a small, dedicated staff and board. Performing contemporary Australian plays and award-winning new writing from around the world, we are renowned for the intimacy of our venue, and for presenting bold theatre produced with raw integrity. With a national reputation for the quality of our work, Red Stitch remains at the forefront of contemporary Australian theatre practise.In 2016, Red Stitch undertook a main-house season of eight Australian premiere theatrical productions, including the world premieres of two new Australian works. In partnership with Geelong Performing Arts Centre, we produced and toured the Victorian and ACT premieres of Hannie Raysonês ´Extinctionê. We also undertook our annual, site-specific PLAYlist event at Bakehouse Studios in Richmond, featuring 10 new short plays by local writers, inspired by 10 musical works. Red Stitch plays a vital role in the development and presentation of new Australian works through our unique INK playwriting program, and offers opportunities for theatre-makers at all stages of their careers to hone and develop their craft. Through INK, we undertook developments for six new Australian plays, with the intention of programming these in our 2017-2019 performance seasons. We advocated for Australian playwrights and productions internationally, with Red Stitch Artistic Director Ella Caldwell meeting with leading theatre-makers, publishers and agents in London and Edinburgh.We also offered year-long Graduate placements to a young actor and designer, as well as several internships and work experience placements to emerging artists and arts-workers. Our 2016 activities represented our continuing commitment to promoting Australian theatre culture through presentation of outstanding new work of uncompromising standard.

column41: The Wantok Musik Foundation has made a major contribution to the performing arts in Australia and in the Pacific region. We have released CDs by artists across Indigenous Australia, PNG, Vanuatu, the Solomon Islands, Bougainville and Fiji. In the last year Pitjantjatjara musician Frank Yamma was recognised for his Wantok-produced album Uncle with an AIR award for Best Independent Country Album. We embarked on a tour of Australia to mark the 40th anniversary of independence for PNG with celebrated Tolai musician, George Telek, and released the debut album from emerging Anindilyakwa musician Emily Wurramara. We traveled to Port Moresby and Port Vila to facilitate a series of workshops for youth groups to learn songwriting skills and the importance of copyright. But perhaps the most significant evidence of the important contribution of the Wantok Musik Foundation is the success of the SingSing ensemble. Haunting, uplifting, exhilarating - Wantok: SING SING is an epic journey that follows the songlines of the indigenous peoples of Oceania in an exuberant fusion of music and dance. Anywhere from 6 to 30 of the region's most talented artists collaborate in a powerful mix of traditional drumming, multi-part choral vocals, sublime world grooves and street hip-hop from the most dynamic urban environments on the planet. Most recently, Sing Sing performed at the PNG National Museum and Art Gallery in Port Moresby.

Our vision is every child and young person in cancer treatment in Victoria, and their families, will benefit from Koala Kids programs.  Our mission is to provide the small things that make a difference to the lives of children and young people in cancer treatment in Victoria each year and their families.  Our purpose is to bring happiness to children and young people and their families during cancer treatment.  Koala Kids provides children and young people (0 to age 24 years) with cancer, their siblings and parents, extended family and carers with the opportunity to enjoy ´normalê things while they are in hospital as inpatients or when attending day cancer treatment or consultations as outpatients.  Koala Kids provides entertaining, engaging and educational activities that are designed to distract children and young people from the often invasive and painful treatments and procedures associated with cancer treatment.         The programs and resources that Koala Kids provides children and young people and their families in hospitals arenêt traditionally offered in a hospital or treatment situation.   Koala Kids acknowledges and celebrates local, national and international events and celebrations for all children and young people with cancer and their families including Australia Day, Chinese New Year, ANZAC Day, Easter, Greek Easter, Passover, Ramadan, Halloween, Indian Festival of Colour & Christmas.  Koala Kids aligns with families, children and young people aged from 0 to 24 years  Our proposed objectives over the next 1-3 years include:  To touch as many of the 1,700 children and young people (up to 24 years) in cancer treatment in Victoria and their families 1:1 with a view to being able to communicate directly with them (rather than having to rely on the hospitals/Childrenês Cancer Centres and Peter Mac as intermediaries).  Koala Kids provides patients, their families and the staff who care for them a range of resources and activities to support: ‚ music, art and procedural pain and play therapists. ‚ social work _ siblings activities, adolescents and young people aged 12 to 17 years). ‚ foods and beverages _ for the family pantries in the Childrenês Cancer Centres.  ‚ literacy activities including visiting childrensê authors to read to and expose the children in treatment to various forms of literacy. ‚ morning tea parties and pizza making events. ‚ recommended texts about all types of cancers including specific types for families when their children are diagnosed. ‚ special foods and small novelty items to celebrate local and national holidays.  To communicate regularly with Koala Kids volunteers and to encourage their communication with each other on relevant Koala Kids matters and maximize their ability to be involved in as many aspects of the organization, its business and activities.

In 2015-2016, the activities of the History Council of Victoria (HCV) encouraged greater understanding and awareness of history. As the peak body for history in Victoria, the HCV provides a reference point for an understanding of history through its website and public activities. The HCV brings together the major bodies relating to (A) history and heritage in Victoria (Royal Historical Society of Victoria, Museums Australia (Vic), Professional Historians Association (Vic), Heritage Council of Victoria, Museum Victoria, National Trust of Australia Victoria, State Library Victoria, Public Record Office Victoria and Womenês HERitage Centre Victoria), (B) the history teaching profession (via the History Teachersê Association of Victoria, the Victorian Curriculum and Assessment Authority and the state governmentês Department of Education and Training), (C) the media (Australian Broadcasting Corporation), and (D) the universities which teach history (currently, Deakin University, La Trobe University and Monash University).For general audiences, the HCV organised its Annual Lecture (22 Oct 2015) with support from Old Treasury Building and as part of the annual History Week. Professor Lynette Russell (Monash University) lectured on ´Australiaês Big Science Picnic 1914: Some New Evidenceê.For higher education and general audiences, the HCV collaborated with Monash University and State Library Victoria on ´Making Public Historiesê, a seminar series led by academic and professional historians. The seminars were: ´S. T. Gill as eyewitness: art as historical evidenceê (29 Sep 2015); ´Melbourne's Alice: Lewis Carrollês Alice in Wonderland as source, artefact and inspiration in art, science and historyê (26 Nov 2015); ´The Day that Shook Russell Streetê (24 Mar 2016); and ´First drafts of History: Rediscovering Victoriaês war correspondentsê (21 Apr 2016).For schools, the HCV delivered the History Roadshow to Year 11 and 12 VCE students and their teachers in regional Victoria. A grant from the state Department of Education and Training through its Strategic Partnerships Program supported the program. Established on 1 July 2011, the Young and Well Cooperative Research Centre (Young and WellCRC) is an Australian based, international research centre that unites young people withresearchers, practitioners, innovators and policy-makers from over 75 partner organisationsacross the not-for-profit, academic, government and corporate sectors. Over the five years from 1July 2011 to 30 June 2016, the Australian Federal Government Departments of Industry hascommitted funding of $27.5 million. In addition, The Young and Well CRC has secured $8.5million in cash and over $85 million of in-kind contributions from our 14 Essential Participants, andover sixty end-user beneficiaries and industry partners. Since establishment, the Young and WellCRC has grown its partner base from 63 to 77. The Young and Well CRC's public profile hasgrown considerably, with our work showcased in a range of national and international media. TheYoung and Well CRC team have been recognised with National awards, including the SuicidePrevention Australia Life Award. column41: The Pascoe Vale RSL operates a Pension and Welfare Office which is entirely supported by 2 Volunteers. A large proportion of the cases prepared by the Pension Office are Veteran Affairs matters. In addition to veteran claims, the Pension Office also handles claims for serving members of the armed forces in respect to military compensation and rehabilitation service. The Pension and Welfare advocates act on behalf of veterans, war widows and current servicemen to ensure that they receive a fair hearing of their case or an outcome which they seek. The Pension and Welfare Office Advocates provide support to veterans who are seeking entitlements, based on their service, from the Department of Veteran Affairs. Furthermore the advocates investigate cases and provide advice on the merits of appeals and provide veterans with representation to the Veteransê Review Board. The Pension and Welfare Office, supported by the committee and office staff of the RSL provide the following assistance to veterans and families during family bereavement. ‚Providing information about RSL funeral rituals, volunteers prepare and perform RSL rituals at funerals when required. ‚Providing funeral assistance. ‚Provision of laurel and poppies for a funeral service. ‚Providing advice on Department of Veteransê Affairs entitlements. ‚Providing advice on war grave entitlements. ‚Assisting with war widowês claims. The Pascoe Vale RSL actively participates in the raising funds for the yearly run Poppy and Anzac Appeals. A band of volunteers made up of the RSL Committee and members sell poppies and badges and organise BBQs to raise money for the Appeals. Through support from our valuable volunteers, and donations from individuals, groups and businesses within our communities, we work towards achieving our mission and hope to give back to those who sacrificed their lives for our country. The RSL's Women's Auxiliary are a small band, who work voluntarily, to assist the Pascoe Vale R.S.L Sub Branch in raising funds to help our members. We rely on bingo, fund raisers such as fashion parades, trading tables, raffles, etc. and this year our Christmas Concert. The monies raised go to the Sub Branch to help in making our R.S.L a place for all members. Fundraisers held for MND and Biggest Morning Tea.

column41: The 2016 Annual Report is available at: http://www.generalsurgeons.com.au/about-us/publicationsThe Society continues to advance the practice of General Surgery and emergency health for the benefit of the Australian community. This is achieved by delivering relevant ongoing professional development and continuing medical education activities for Trainees, General Surgeons, other medical professionals, and surgical educators. These included an Annual Scientific Meeting focused on Dealing with Unexpected Surgical Findings, two national Training Days on Breast & Endocrine Surgery and Surgical Oncology & Melanoma, and three Management of Surgical Emergencies courses.The Society administers the Surgical Education and Training Program in General Surgery in Australia, including the selection of trainee General Surgeons, hospital accreditation, curriculum development, hospital based teaching, assessment, performance management, exam preparation, and online learning. The Society also delivers regional based education and training programs around Australia, to enhance the clinical and basic sciences knowledge of trainee General Surgeons.The Society continues to provide expert advice to medical bodies and government on matters relating to the treatment and control of General Surgical diseases. The Society promotes research activities through its Research & Scholarships Subcommittee. In 2016, the Society awarded travel grants valued at $15,000 to three Pacific Island and South East Asian Surgeons for further education and training in General Surgery, and educational grants valued at over $11,550 to support trainees and IMGs demonstrating an interest in Rural Surgery.

DVRCV is a family violence specialist organisation dedicated to making a safer community for women and children, and  helping the community to respond to and prevent family violence. We provide statewide training and resources to professionals in the family violence and related sector, and also directly support women who are experiencing violence and their family and friends.We deliver training programs that help workers understand and deliver ´best practiceê whether itês in recognising family violence, risk assessment and management, supporting children and families, technology safety, or understanding how to navigate Victoriaês complex legal system. We host a suite of six websitesÜincluding Love: good, bad, ugly for young people, The Lookout for family violence workers, the home site dvrcv.org.au which includes survivorês stories and fact sheets, and a new technology safety website SmartSafe.org.au.We also produce printed materials, such as the international award-winning Sex, Love and Other Stuff for young men, Gathering support: safety for women, and the booklet for family and friends, Is someone you know being abused in a relationship?We take calls from women who are experiencing violence, and the wider community, and help them find their local outreach service to get support and further information. And we advocate to government and the legal system for reforms to laws and practice to help protect womenês safety and end family violence.You can find more information about DVRCV in our annual report: http://www.dvrcv.org.au/about/welcome-dvrcv/annual-reports

In 2016 Victorian Women Lawyers celebrated its 20th anniversary of assisting women working in the law and promoting the interests of women through the law. Over the course of the year, VWL has been committed to reaching out to members and potential members with a diverse range of events and initiatives. We have focused on ensuring that our association is welcoming and inclusive to women lawyers and law students from a diverse range of backgrounds and perspectives, whether that be cultural, socioeconomic, LGBTIQ, regional and suburban.  VWL delivered almost 40 events and projects that were aimed at examining topics that are important to our members. These included: pay transparency, family violence, revenge porn, addressing unconscious bias, closing the gender pay gap, incarceration of indigenous women, career progression, culturally sensitive legal advice, flexibility and tackling sexism, harassment and gender discrimination. A series of regional events in Geelong, Bendigo and Shepparton, as well as recording and posting videos of our events on our website, represented our efforts to reach out to regional women lawyers.  We continue to contribute to public discourse on law reform and policy. This year our Law Reform and Justice Committees made submissions to the Senate inquiries on the phenomenon colloquially known as ´revenge pornê and the Fair Work Amendment (Gender Pay Gap) Bill, as well as the Victorian Gender Equality Strategy.   In 2016, VWL matched a record number of 187 pairs of mentors and mentees in our Law Student Mentoring Program. The Program continues to be highly valuable to women who are preparing to enter the legal profession. The second annual Warren Moot saw over 30 VWL members participate in the competition with many adjudicators from the judiciary and the Bar generously donating their time to adjudicate the moot rounds.  Further information can be found in Portia 2016: the annual journal and report of Victorian Women Lawyers at https://vwl.asn.au/publications/

column41: National Exhibitions Touring Support (NETS) Victoria is the peak body for touring visual culture in the state of Victoria. NETS Victoria collaborates with art galleries, cultural institutions, artists and curators to co-create and co-present outstanding exhibitions and projects that are supported by engaging high quality publications and public and learning programs, which promote increased audience participation and educational engagement with contemporary art across regional Victoria.NETS Victoria incubates new projects across the state through the provision of seed funding the Exhibition Development Fund grants program. We provide regional galleries with best practice support services for our touring programs, free professional touring advice and support, and professional development opportunities for their staff. Through our program we build professional and community networks, fostering dialogue between our artists and curators and regional audiences and art practitioners.Organisational and project support is received from the Victorian Government through Creative Victoria, through the Federal Governmentês arts funding body the Australia Council for the Arts and via the Visions of Australia program from the Ministry for the Arts. As a Registered Cultural Organisation NETS Victoria also seeks public donations and bequests to support its artistic program and access initiatives.Over the last 20 years NETS Victoria has toured more than 70 exhibitions to over 370 destinations. Organisational records indicate that more than 2 million people have attended have NETS Victoria exhibitions since the early nineties.

Wingateês mission is to enable positive community wellbeing with a focus on learning and social activities, especially for people who are experiencing disadvantage. The centre is a Registered Training Organisation, Learn Local provider and is funded by the Department of Health & Human Services to deliver social and recreational programs as part of the Neighbourhood House Coordination Program.   Wingate is well recognised in the delivery of programs that create pathways to education and employment and has received a number of awards and accolades in recent years.  The centre is also a licensed Occasional Care provider with onsite facilities for up to 19 children and has recently constructed a Menês Shed facility.The Ascot Vale housing estate has a significant number of families from culturally and linguistically diverse (CALD) backgrounds with many young people who are either on a low income, unemployed or face drug and alcohol addiction issues. Many of the residents are newly arrived migrants and refugees.  The centre has many wrap around services including the Moonee Valley Legal Service, New Hope Foundation (settlement support for newly arrived migrants) and Uniting Care ReGen who provide AOD counselling services.  The co-located services complement our service delivery and offer our clients a holistic service by providing non vocational services.

column41: Over the past 25 years Cornerstone Contact Centre in heart of downtown Dandenong has provided a drop in home to many in our community who are experiencing hardship, and are in need of some extra support.Through providing a meal or food parcel, a safe place to meet, a place to belong, social connection, a positive environment, good friends or a listening ear, Cornerstone continues to be a home to many who come through their door (20,000 plus visits per year).Cornerstone is operated largely by a committed team of over 100 volunteers from the local community (including from a variety of local churches), and is located on the corner of Mason and Walker Streets in Dandenong (easy walking distance from Dandenong station).Many who come through the doors unfortunately do not have a safe place to call home, and many live without supportive family and friends around them. Many are experiencing homelessness, or living in unsafe and unstable housing, some have experienced relationship breakdown, mental health issues, addictions, unemployment, and some have come from overseas where they faced trials such as war and famine in their homeland, or any number of other complexities. Regardless of a personês background, everyone is welcome at Cornerstone, their home away from home.Cornerstone Contact Centre is open most days of the week, operates with a small part-time staff (just three) and relies heavily on a committed team of volunteers across their various programs.

Iramoo Community Centre provides a range of community programs and activities to advance social inclusion, vibrancy and resilience of local communities residing in the Wyndham municipality. Iramoo Community Centre works closely with Wyndham Vale communities to provide safe, accessible and functional spaces where community members can gather, socialise and collaborate. We help build strong, vibrant and resilient communities by providing access to high quality programs, activities and events; and ensure the longevity of the community centre by deploying effective and efficient management of its assets, finances and employees.  Our programs and events we provided throughout the year which have been successful in meeting our purpose were: arts program -mosaic, painting/drawing, craftees and quilters. Cooking programs - indigenous cooking group, men's cooking, pasta making, Indian cooking and community kitchen. Seniors exercise groups - tai chi, light exercise, yoga and ballroom. Woor-Dunginês core activity is the Aboriginal Partnership Program. We provide capacity-building services in three-year blocks to those Aboriginal community-controlled organisations (ACCOs) that meet program criteria to become our Aboriginal partner organisations. Alumni partners help to mentor new partners.In 2016 we have continued our work with four program partners, MDAS, Njernda, Willum Warrain and Winda-Mara, and two alumni partners, HICSA and ILBIJERRI Theatre Company.Through our Income Generation and Resources Group (IGRG) we introduce partners to potential funders, pro bono resource providers and student-placement coordinators. Further, we broker funding, promote projects to potential donors and facilitate briefings. Even in the event our partners receive funding, we continue to provide practical support in program implementation and grant acquittal and evaluation, and encourage the documentation of impact.Through introductions made at IGRG workshops, donor briefings and other associated activities, our partners have been successful in 2016 in obtaining philanthropic funding and pro bono support for key projects identified by their local communities. In this way our partner organisations' self-determination is supported.In 2016 we ran the Maarni Aboriginal Womenês Leadership Program, which supported eight women nominated by our partners with a tailored 12-month personal and professional development and mentoring program. Participants have reported their skills and confidence to take on leadership roles within their local communities have grown across the life of the program.In 2016 we progressed the Criminal Record Discrimination Project, a significant law-reform initiative addressing structural barriers to employment for Aboriginal Victorians. The project arose in response to feedback from our partner organisations around the urgent need for criminal-record law reform in Victoria.A broad range of stakeholders was convened to inform the project, including Elders of the Koori Court, the Law Institute of Victoria, and academic staff from Monash and RMIT Universities.Case-studies collected throughout 2016 highlighting_how current laws affect Aboriginal Victorians with a criminal record will inform a report to be presented to the statewide Aboriginal Justice Forum and the Victorian Attorney General in 2017.

MUHIês programs continued to deliver services that aim to achieve our purpose of reducing the obstacles of achieving good health. Our local programs focussed on education which we believe is vital to a health society. Our ever-popular Student Welfare Outreach Team continued to deliver outstanding tutorials for VCE students wishing to achieve good results at school while struggling to pay the exorbitant prices for the standard revision courses. SWOT aims to provide everyone with the equal opportunity to determine their own destiny regardless of their background which is essential to health and wellbeing. In contrast, our Public Lecture program along with our conferences, AusWHO and the Undergraduate Global Health Case Competition, aimed to more specifically educate the public about global health issues and provide them with the skills to take charge and make a difference. This yearês themes revolved around current topics including epidemics and gender and health and were extremely well received. The significant increase in attendance of these events and the feedback from participants has indicated that the events are both engaging and informative.Our global programs continued to provide ongoing support to under-resourced communities overseas. The Kenyan Village Medical Education program continued its tour of villages in Kenya, providing educational sessions on topics such as diarrhoeal disease, water hygiene and malaria. The 2016 KVME trip established deeper connections with communities by returning to villages visited in 2015 and expanded the repertoire of presentations. The Material Aid Program continued to collect equipment from hospitals and clinics, sending it along with university students to under-resourced clinics. It also began to expend by also collecting monetary donations to purchase much needed equipment that could not be donated without cost. In particular, MAP assisted the devastated communities in Fiji following Cyclone Winston with assistance of the Katalyst Foundation on the ground in Fiji through the Rebuild Fiji Fund. The ongoing work of this partnership has resulted in significant structural and functional improvements in the Nabouwalu Hospital and the recent purchase of a much -needed ambulance for the region.MUHI has continued to build on its previous successes over the year through the hard work of its volunteers. As final goal of MUHI, we hope that these individuals have grown through their involvement with the organisation and will use the skills they have attained in further improving global health in the future.

Consumer Action protects the community from exploitative and unfair businesses models and practices. Our mission is to ensure that everyone in the community benefits from fair and well-functioning markets. These are big goals, so this year we have for the first time produced an Impact Report, to demonstrate the impact our work has on peopleês lives.Our advocacy is grounded in the experiences of the people we serve. Our financial counselling service and legal practice have again supported around 20,000 Victorians this year. We also actively support financial counsellors and community workers throughout Victoria, particularly through legal advice and training. This helps us expand our reach and ensures we are responding to the issues affecting the most vulnerable people in the community.Consumer Action has achieved some significant wins with Australians marginalised by unfair markets and business practices, including on issues such as retirement living and energy affordability. On the former, we worked with residents to place this issue on the Victorian parliamentary agenda Ü this work led to an inquiry into the retirement housing sector which is now underway.On energy, our ´Heat or Eatê report, which shared the stories of Victorians who had been disconnected from electricity or gas and contributed to an inquiry into financial hardship practices of energy retailers undertaken by the Essential Services Commission.As part of demonstrating impact and, importantly, to continuously improve on our efforts, the centre has this year engaged in significant evaluation activities, including evaluations of our legal advice line, financial counselling and worker advice services. Reports have been published on our website so we can share lessons with others.Our broader campaign work also utilises reflection and evaluation. An example involves our efforts to fix unfair energy contracts through changing national energy rules, a joint project with the Consumer Utilities Advocacy Centre. While we werenêt able to get the change we were seeking, the evaluation showed we had an impact on industry practice and helped other advocates push forward with change. Our advocacy also led to a Victorian ban on early termination (exit) fees when energy retailers change prices.We continue to hold ourselves accountable for making a tangible difference. We encourage you to delve into this report which demonstrates the impact weêre having on Australians and the  community workers who help them with consumer issues.Our 15/16 Impact Report is available online: http://impact1516.consumeraction.org.au/

Gertrude has been building the careers of Australiaês artists for over 30 years.  Since our establishment in 1985, Gertrude has played an essential role in the visual arts sector, shaping the careers for many of Australiaês most celebrated artists.We are an incubator and launching pad for early-practice and mid-career artists. Our artistic program _ including our studio and exhibition program _ is unique in its equal emphasis on the production and presentation of contemporary art.  This enables us to support artists to explore new ideas and present risk-taking work at pivotal points in their careers.Gertrude's alumni distinguish themselves in major Australian and international exhibitions and collections, for example, 17 of the 20 artists representing Australia at the Venice Biennale since 1995 have been Gertrude studio or exhibiting artists.  Gertrude gives audiences unique insight into the creative development of artists. Our audiences engage with risk-taking, formative moments that define artist careers.Gertrude's 2016 Annual Report can be found at the following link: http://gertrude.org.au/docs/2016-gertrude-contemporary-annual-report.pdf

WAYSS Limited is a community based organisation which established many of its services in the late 1970ês. The agency has been operating under its current structure since 1997.  Our agency is a not for profit housing provider which caters to clients who are homeless or at risk of homelessness.   WAYSS support programs consist of Accommodation Options for Families (AOF), Drug Court Homelessness Assistance Program (DCHAP), Indigenous Tenants at Risk (ITAR), Initial Assessment and Planning Front Door services, Emergency Youth Accommodation Service (EYA), Women's Outreach Program, Private Rental Access Program, Social Housing Advocacy and Support Program (SHASP), Step Ahead Program, Youth Homelessness Support Program, Animal Assisted Education and Therapy Program, Childrenês Services, Family Violence Crisis Service, Family Violence Faxback Project, Family Violence Outreach Service, and the Safe at Home Program.   In the 2015/16 financial year WAYSS IA&P Dandenong office assisted 635 households to establish their tenancies, 109 to maintain their tenancies that were at risk and provided emergency accommodation for hundreds of families.  In Casey and Cardinia, 1368 households were assisted to either maintain or to establish their tenancies, as well as assisted with crisis housing.   284 of these households were assisted into private rental.   Our family violence outreach and our Womenês services outreach provided case management and supported 1443 women and their children.  499 women and their children were assisted by the family violence crisis service with accommodation.   The teams not only assist with the housing options but case manage these clients looking at both short term and long term goals.  All aspects of their lives are worked on including  financial, counselling service referrals, housing, childrenês issues, court support and legal referrals. Women have access to brokerage funds, HEF payments, and a psychologist all within WAYSS as well as childrenês workers and the Animal Assisted Education and Therapy Program designed to assist children who have been subjected to trauma in their lives.  Workers are currently working with an average of 15 clients, most of whom are looking for safe and affordable housing.  This is imperative to their recovery and breaking the cycle of abuse.   In total 9707 clients were assisted through WAYSS Womenês services for a one year period in 2015.   WAYSS also runs the Accommodation Options for families programs which assists families currently living in rooming houses to find more permanent and safer accommodation options.  This program has been a great success and is instrumental in getting these families out of inappropriate accommodation which is both unsafe and expensive.    Our Youth programs teams in Dandenong case managed 626 young people, 114 of these were residing in WAYSS transitional properties.  Our Emergency Youth Accommodation program provided 119 residential placements throughout the year a

Whales _ Antarctica As we were unaware of Japans intention of when they would resume whaling post the ICJ ruling, we launched operation Icefish 2, in a bid to clean up the remaining two of the _Bandit-6î illegal Patagonian and Antarctic toothfish poaching vessels. However with the whaling fleet also deciding at the last minute to head down to the Southern Ocean, we broadened our search for the illegal Japanese whaling fleet, but were unfortunately unsuccessful in finding them.With the Sam Simon and Bob Barker patrolling the Faeroes in protection of pilot whales in July/September, we were left with only one vessel, the Steve Irwin.As a result Japan was able to illegally kill their self allocated quota of 333 Minke whales, of which 200 were pregnant or with calf. IUU Fishing _ Operation Icefish - https://www.seashepherdglobal.org/icefish/Through SSALês operations (and in working with other Sea Shepherd countryês entities), SSAL was able to prepare the M/Y Steve Irwin from our Ships Operations Base in Williamstown and also the ports of Fremantle and Henderson, WA, for Operation Icefish 2 for the protection of Antarctic and Patagonian toothfish. We were in search of the two remaining vessels wanted by Interpol known as the _Bandit-6î.  It was later found that there was only one vessel remaining, being the Viking.As a result of our campaign, which departed Henderson, WA in January, we were able to successfully locate the Viking in Indonesian waters. We sent a team into shore and notified the Indonesian Fisheries minister, who then sent out the Navy to arrest the Viking. Subsequently, the Indonesian Navy decommissioned the Viking and now it sits off the Indonesian waters as a deterrent against illegal fishing.This meant that in less than two years, Sea Shepherd had managed to clean up the remaining six illegal Patagonian and Antarctic toothfish poaching vessels operating in the Southern Ocean. As a catalytic philanthropic organisation, ten20 is all about bringing inspiration and innovation to early childhood investment in AU to ensure all children thrive in learning and life. Our purpose is to catalyse, convene and support community led collective impact efforts. Our singular focus is vulnerable children between the ages 0-8 over the next 10 years. Our bold goal is to work alongside partners to reduce AUês child vulnerability as per the Australian Early Development Census.Our strategy and principal activities relate to providing funding and support that creates enabling conditions to set up the Opportunity Child (OC) initiative for success. OCês bold goal is to dramatically change the lives of the 65,000 five-year-old children who start school in AU each year with big challenges in learning and in life. Ten20 focuses on influencing the system through building partnerships, funding, capacity, and trust, playing a key role in stewardship, innovation and sustainability of early childhood investments.Ten20 works closely with, and is part of the OC Collective, comprised of various communities and organisations across AU in partnership and collaboration, together aligning individual  strategies and activities for collective impact and to deliver shared values and better outcomes in early childhood. This collective impact approach develops new ways of working together, innovation that leads systems to change.As a Collective, some highlights of activities and outcomes achieved in 2016:‚ Developed the OC initiativeês shared strategy and vision, delivered in the five key activity areas: Collective, Learning, Impact, Capital and Voice. ‚ Developed the OC data measurement and outcomes framework for partner communities, which is framed with the overarching national shared outcomes framework, reflecting state based efforts, including the NEST (part of the Australian Research Alliance for Children and Youth) and Results Based Accountability frameworks and Efforts to Outcomes enabling technology. ‚ Strengthened our voice with improved outreach campaigns such as a new website, social media, and regular distribution of ten20 Concentric and OC enews. This informs about the latest developments in our work and influences early childhood investment in AU by encouraging new forms of thinking, funding and solutions, create more opportunities and resources for all.‚ Advocated for change in systems, practices and mindset through speaking at public dialogue and presentations, eg. the Leadership Conference in Canberra, the Asian Venture Philanthropy Conference, influential Discussion Panels and Funder Roundtables across AU‚ In partnership with the Harwood Institute for Public Innovation in the US, developed the _Funder Roadmapî, a tool to support others who seek to undertake a collective impact approach and other funders looking to align and in need of a road-map to more effectively align with the communities that they serve and to de-risk the work.

Please refer to GWP constitution. 6.1: In FY1516 we focused on supporting our two grassroots partners to be better equipped to deliver educational and economic programs for women. In Cambodia, we funded a feasibility study and business plan in Stung Treng for a social enterprise training restaurant for women. In Nepal, we provided ongoing relief for earthquake survivors developed an action plan with our partners to ensure the regeneration and sustainability of womenês livelihoods. 6.2: We focus on ensuring womenês agency and control by resourcing women-led organisations and the women they serve as a way to catalyse transformative social change. All of the activities undertaken by us in 2015-16 have worked toward this purpose. 6.3: During FY15-16 we identified and funded various education and economic opportunities for women deemed relevant to the local context. In Cambodia, we provided a consultant to develop a business plan for a social enterprise training restaurant. The program is a contemporary solution to womenês poverty and is appealing to a younger demographic. In Nepal, prior to the earthquakes, we had been developing a suite of vocational training programs. After the earthquakes it was necessary to pivot towards relief work, and this remained our focus for the duration of FY15-16. 6.4: Provided our two partner organisations with ongoing financial support and technical support on the development of the following specific programs: Gender responsive earthquake relief in Nepal; shelter for pregnant women and new mothers displaced by the earthquakes in Nepal; consultancy on feasibility and business plan for training restaurant for women in Cambodia.6.5: During FY15-16 we continued to actively grow our online and offline communities. Online, we achieved a direct mailing list of over 1000 supporters, over 3000 members of our Facebook community, 1140 followers on Twitter and 1223 followers on Instagram, and provided followers with daily content around our work and the project of gender equality more broadly. Our major offline event for FY1516 took place in November. Titled ´The Disaster Agenderê, the event brought together 100 community members from across Melbourne to take part in a panel discussion about gender-responsive disaster relief. During FY1516 we received considerable media coverage, with op-eds published in mainstream publications including Womenês Agenda, Daily Life and The Age.6.6: We remained committed to making progress towards this purpose in FY1516. This was reflected in both our international programs focus in Cambodia, as well as our development of a strategy around development of partnerships with small, medium and larger businesses. This latter strategy is to be enacted during the next financial year.

column41: The activities include: ‚ Continue to deliver a world leading training program for training SEM physicians and set best-practice clinical standards in SEM. ‚ Support and promote ongoing quality research in evidence-based SEM. ‚ Ensure provision of a structured Continuing Professional Development program that enables Fellows to maintain skills and expertise as specialists. ‚ Develop more comprehensive education programs for Clinical Training Supervisors to improve standardization of training between individual training practices. The ACSEP Program is applied: To develop and maintain clinical knowledge relevant to the practice of SEM. ‚ When consulting with individual patients, sporting groups or teams, taking into consideration the specific needs of particular populations such as female athletes, children, older people and athletes with a disability in a variety of environments. ‚ To assess and manage acute, chronic or traumatic injuries, and medical problems arising from, or affecting physical activity, in a broad range of patients from the recreational exerciser to the elite athletes. ‚ To prescribe exercise programs for patients to: - prevent injury and illness; - reduce risk factors of chronic disease; and - support the management of medical problems, including chronic disease. ‚ Educating patients, the public, sporting groups and teams, on the benefits of sport and exercise and other sport and exercise related issues. ‚ To manage the care of sporting groups and teams at all levels from community through to elite and professional. ‚ To manage issues relevant to SEM for national sporting organisations and cultural groups. ‚ To provide advice and representation to all relevant stakeholders on all issues regarding doping in sport. ‚ To support travelling athletes and teams prior to departure and while interstate or overseas, and provide follow up care after arriving home. ‚ To undertake professional development activities and contribute to the expanding body of SEM knowledge by participating in research projects relevant to the specialty.

Singleton Equity Housing Limiteds property portfolio comprises standard residential dwellings that are predominately used for long-term supported rental housing for people who meet the Companys eligibility criteria. During the year to 30 June 2016, the Company continued to actively pursue the divestment of unsuitable properties in accordance with proposals put to the Department of Health and Human Services which resulted in a number of properties being identified for disposal. The proceeds on the sale of the Companys properties are applied to the retirement of mortgage debt, extinguishing of share contributions and to fund the development and/or purchase of new property by Disability Housing Limited. A major compliance audit was undertaken by independent consultants. The audit covered OHS, access and fire risk compliance and the building fabric. The purpose of this audit was to refresh the status of the portfolio for the benefit of the Company and DHHS. Several upgrades have been undertaken on these properties through the year and additional works have been identified through the audit. Further details can be found in the annual report of the Housing Choices Group at http://www.housingchoices.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2016.pdf

The Skyline VCE Bursary Program reduces the financial burden of education for academically talented students from disadvantaged backgrounds. Open to students commencing Year 11 in government schools and providing ongoing support over the two years of VCE study, the Skyline Program is a partnership between the student, their school, their teachers, parents and the Skyline Education Foundation Australia. With an intake of 10 to 15 students each year, and a total of 25 students at any time, the Skyline Program provides a range of benefits and support (e.g. personal development and career education workshops) that relieve financial and social disadvantage that can hinder access to educational opportunities, and enhance young peopleês personal capacity and confidence to pursue their educational and life goals.

Our overall objective is an Australia where people have informed and inspired discussions about human rights, equality and justice.Our aims are to promote understanding of human rights issues through publishing stories that are accessible and engaging.Inform public debate with fact-based and jargon-free analysis.Produce credible and responsible content through transparency and editorial rigor. Foster artistic expression. Art can broach difficult topics, particularly when arguments seem to entrench long-held beliefs. Support a diverse range of voices. We are committed to inclusive and ethical storytelling. Provide a forum for insightful discussion. We are curious about fresh perspectives and encourage informed debate.We have published essays, columns, opinion pieces and voluntary submissions through the year to increase the awareness of human rights issues. We continue to utilise talented and quality writers to write on a range of human rights and social justice matters. They provide accessible and informative opinions on topical issues. All pieces are reviewed by a team of highly capable editors. This ensures they are up to a high standard.We have also published various pieces of accompanying art. This provides an illustrative example of the tone and contention of the piece. We also received hits from various different locations - including international traction. We aim to be as far reaching and impactful in all areas as possible. As part of this, we encourage all our readers and subscribers to get involved and submit a piece for us to review and potentially publish.Finally, we also provide open public events for our readers and publishers. We host end of year events with our writers and regular submitters to exhibit their pieces. This encourages people to get physically involved in the charity and meet our contributors. Overall, this means our readership and attendees are raised awareness of human rights issues as well as exposed to high quality publications.

STRATHEWEN LANDCARE GROUPPRESIDENTS REPORTNovember 20162016 was another strong year for Strathewen Landcare Group.  The successes of the previous years, particularly our engagement of the broader community through the Landcare Community Dinner, has seen our membership grow to 85 members, representing 46 properties and accounting for the management of 3,612 hectares which is nearly 50% of the Strathewen Landcare Group Catchment. Over the past 12 months, Strathewen Landcare Group has been successful in planning and delivering:‚ reintroduction of the weed management incentive programs‚ mapping and control of priority roadside weeds‚ our Landcare Community Dinner‚ 2 weed information events‚ pasture and shelter belt information events‚ a pilot project on invasive weed mapping on private land ‚ completion of the 3 years invasive weed program, targeting Chilean Needle Grass, Serrated Tussock, Patterson's Curse, and Bridal Creeper‚ GIS workshopsWeed ProgramsThe three year grant funded weed program concluded over this past year.  The program has actively targeted the four priority invasive weeds raised awareness of these and other threats to our agricultural and bushland areas.  Our thanks to Carol and Ross Cardile for their leadership in this program. We piloted a weed mapping concept for private properties.  The intent of this project is to provide expert knowledge and advice to land owners on the presence, location and management of priority weeds.  5 member properties participated in this pilot, reporting significant change in understanding of invasive weeds and commitment to managing them.  The positive outcomes for this pilot has encouraged us to pursue grant funding to expand the program over the Strathewen Landcare catchment.  We are still waiting on the outcome of this grant application.We are intending to approach Nillumbik Shire Council with an application to the Land Management Incentive Program fro funding to support our Weed Management Incentive Program.  We ran this program successfully for many years, providing reimbursement of spray costs to SLG members, but it was disabled by changes to the LMIP. Community DinnerOur 2016 Community Dinner was another outstanding success, with nearly 100 Strathewen residents attending.  The catering was excellent and the kids program is key to the success of the evening.  A presentation by Terry Hubbard was well received.  Now looking forward to the 2017 dinner. Future of Strathewen Landcare groupOur Landcare Group continues to provide support and encouragement to all our landholders, whether they be managing their land for agricultural production, conservation, or simply our wonderful rural community lifestyle.  Providing access to grants funding, Council programs, and informationand expert advice will continue to be our purpose.  Providing opportunities for ongoing community connectedness will also be important role for us in the Strathewen community.

Melbourne Fringe is a not-for-profit organisation that presents the annual Melbourne Fringe Festival. We provide artists with the tools to develop, present and promote their work, creating a community of audiences and artists that together represent a national arts network. The Melbourne Fringe Festival is an open-access event. Each year artists from a wide scope of art-forms and experience join our Independent Arts Program to develop and present their work as part of the festival. Through our Independent Arts Program we run the Festival Hub, a curated space that offers a cross-section of arts experiences throughout the festival period including the Fringe Club. Central to each yearês Melbourne Fringe Festival is our Creative Program; Melbourne Fringe produced projects which bring emerging and established artists together to explore new ways to engage audiences with free works in public spaces. The Melbourne Fringe Artist Development Program supports our Festival participants and the broader independent arts community. Year-round we deliver a range of programs across all aspects of building a successful and sustainable career in the arts. Our Artist Development Programs include mentorships, forums, training and awards. The 2016 Melbourne Fringe festival report can be found here: https://joom.ag/HZzW

column2: Human Rights Arts & Film Festival Inc
column41: The Human Rights Arts and Film Festival (HRAFF) delivered our annual art and film festival from 5-19 May 2016 in Melbourne, and toured Sydney, Canberra, Darwin, Perth, Alice Springs and Brisbane from 24 May - 8 June.    The festival explored a vast breadth and depth of human rights issues, presenting art and films on Refugees and people seeking asylum, gender equality, LGBTQIA rights, Indigenous rights, environmental issues, disability rights, and rights of children. HRAFF prioritises putting a human face and human story to global issues, sparking empathy and connectivity, and educating and empowering the community.   In 2016, we spotlighted the most pressing Australian human rights issues, featuring the award winning Chasing Asylum, and Prison Songs, on Indigenous incarceration rates. HRAFF is a platform for artists of diverse backgrounds, this year including 61 films from 46 countries in it's creative program.   Through HRAFF, the staff, board, volunteers, and artists, have created a vibrant and active community engaged with human rights.   For our full FY15/16 annual report, please click here: http://2016.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/hraff2016_annualreport_final-spreads.pdf

Ozford College provides its students with a fully integrated education pathway model. Both domestic and international students can enrol in the Ozford High School programs. These cover the final three years of secondary school in Australia: Year 10, 11 and 12. The main focus here is to assist international students to integrate their prior overseas based studies with the Victorian Certificate of Education (VCE) or the senior Victorian Certificate of Applied Learning (VCAL). In recent years, because of the small class sizes and a focus on the individual's needs, Ozford has also attracted a number of domestic students into its High School programs. Embedded within the High School program delivery is a strong emphasis on the study of English as both an Additional Language (EAL) and Subject Specific English.

Astraês 2016 opening concert on International Womenês Day in Abbotsfordês Good Shepherd Chapel was memorable not just for the performances of works by many unjustly neglected women composers, but also for the March heatwave that made audience and performers feel like labourers in the conventês old industrial laundry. The centenary of the grim battles on the Western Front was commemorated in April with a repeat performance of Helen Giffordês Choral Scenes and Kastalskyês Requiem. In May, two of Morton Feldmanês works for voices and instruments encountered mass music by Monteverdi and choral arrangements of Mahler, Liszt and Nietzsche. The August concert celebrating Andrew Byrneês 50th birthday was postponed to 2017, which allowed extra recording and rehearsal time for the remaining two concerts. Octoberês concert linked Brahms op 74/1 motet, a rare performance of Webernês cantata Das Augenlicht, Keith Humbleês previously unperformed Trio Iand new works by Rohan Drape and Neil Kelly. And the 3rd Lawrence Whiffin Memorial concert in December premiered many works from Australia and Italy.These five varied and wonderful concerts demonstrate once again Astra musical director John McCaugheyês vision and programming, his deep understanding of music and its contexts, his dedication to Astra and his strong relationships with musicians and composers in Australia and internationally.

Operation Newstart provided assistance to 164 boys and girls aged between 14 and 16 years who have become disengaged from their secondary schools. They may also have come to the attention of Victoria Police or other authorities and are referred into one of the 5 programs that are in place in Collingwood (Operation Newstart Northern), Dandenong (Operation Newstart South Eastern), Flemington (Operation Newstart Western), Geelong, (Operation Newstart Geelong), Narre Warren (Operation Newstart Casey). In the care of professionals from the teaching, police and mental health sectors, these students participate in challenging outdoor experiential activities, vocational training, community service and intensive therapeutic interventions. More than 85% of these students return to education and remain in school, meaningful employment or alternative education settings two years from completion. A comprehensive analysis can be viewed at www.onv.org.au.

Caroline Chisholm Society supports pregnancy, children and families.We offer support from the moment a woman learns of her pregnancy to the time her youngest child goes to school. We help women to achieve a safe and nurturing environment for their children. We offer 1) new and pre-loved baby and maternity goods to families to alleviate the impact of poverty, 2) one-off appointments for counselling and support to empower families, and 3) ongoing casework to support good parenting while at risk of or facing homelessness, family violence and mental health issues. We see 1000-2000 per year, depending on funds and complexity of client needs.We are a grass roots agency, led by a voluntary Board focused in our local communities of Caroline Springs, Moonee Valley and Shepparton.You will find more details in our Annual Report (http://caroline.org.au/aboutus.htm).

column41: Stroke is one of Australiaês biggest killers and a leading cause of disability. In 2016 the Melbourne International Comedy Festival celebrated its 30th anniversary with an event that featured more than 2,000 local and international artists presenting 6,322 performances that were enjoyed by an audience of more than 770,000 people.Melbourne International Comedy Festival has grown to become one of the biggest and most loved comedy events in the world. It is Australiaês largest ticketed cultural festival and one of Victoriaês hallmark events.The 2016 Festival generated $16.3 million at the box office and the suite of nationally broadcast television specials for Network Ten, ABC TV, SBS2 and Foxtel attracted more than 5 million viewers. The laughs also rolled across the airways with radio broadcast specials on 774 ABC Melbourne, triple j and Nova 100.A distinguishing feature of Melbourne International Comedy Festival is its focus on innovative programming, free events, all year-round national and international touring and educational development programs complementing the presentation of the annual four-week festival. More than a festival, the organisationês intertwined development programs continue to support career pathways for Australian comedy artists: RAW Comedy, Class Clowns, Deadly Funny and Deadly Funny Kids, Jeez Louise and The Comedy Zone.Dating back to the Festivalês inaugural launch with comedy legends Peter Cook and Sir Les Patterson _ through photographs, footage and ephemera _ the life and mood of the Festival was captured in a major anniversary exhibition presented in collaboration with Arts Centre Melbourne, Humour Us: 30 years of the Melbourne International Comedy Festival.Live panel discussions were held each weekend of the Festival in the surrounds of the anniversary exhibition and audiences were invited to hear the history of the Festival directly from the only person who has performed in every single one! The wonderful Rod Quantock OAM treated comedy lovers to guided tours of the exhibition.Free-flowing family fun featured the best and most unpredictable street performers from the worldês stage, The (Very) Big Laugh Out brought comedy, circus and all manner of curiosities to Fed Square and City Square for an action-packed _ and FREE _ program of sheer fun and frivolity. In 2016 the free family outdoor program ran across the Festival including the Easter school holiday period, attracting attendance of 100,000 kids and the young at heart.For nearly twenty years the Melbourne International Comedy Festival Roadshow has home delivered the best of the Festival to towns and cities across Australia. In 2016 the Roadshow travelled to 80 communities across Australia, performing just shy of 100 shows, and bringing laughs to all corners of the country. The Roadshow extended the brand internationally, showcasing the best in Australian comedy to audiences in Hong Kong, Singapore, Kuala Lumpur and Penang.

column41: The mission of WorldSkills Australia (WSA) is to actively engage in the development of policy and the practice of skills excellence in Australia through competitions, international benchmarking and applied research.  Our aim is to encourage Australians to celebrate vocational education and training. Our competitions operate on a two year cycle. Regional competitions flow into national competitions, with national competition winners competing internationally, if eligible.‚ Throughout 2015, regional competitions were held around the country, across our 31 WSA regions.  Over 5,000 young men and women competed in close to 500 regional competitions.   Following the regional competitions, over 500 competitors were eligible to compete at the 2016 National Competition in Melbourne in October 2016.  The competitors trained throughout 2016 with their trainers and mentors in preparation for the National Competition.‚ In August 2015, our Skillaroo team, consisting of 26 young men and women travelled to Sao Paulo, Brazil and competed in the 43rd WorldSkills International Competition.  Over four days of competition our team competed in a range of skill and trade disciplines, winning 5 medals and being awarded 11 medallions of excellence.‚ WSA conducted TryêaSkill activities around Australia, with many school students attending the events.  WSA delivers these interactive programs around the country to provide a range of opportunities for students to experience trade and skills based careers and to interact with experts about vocational education pathways.‚ In May 2016 the National Refrigeration Competition was held in Melbourne in conjunction with Air Conditioning, Refrigeration and Building Services (ARBS) Trade Exhibition, with three days of competition for the talented trainees and apprentices.‚ WSA continued to work with a number of partner organisations to deliver pathways and scholarships to many young Australian men and women, including:  o the Ern MacDonald Fellowship awarded in April 2016 to assist the careers of young tradespeople in the building and construction industry;  o the ABBTF World Class Bricklaying Development Scholarship which supports the Bricklaying Skillaroo;o the BBM Skilled Futures Program which is a joint effort by WSA and BBM Youth Support providing scholarships to eligible recipients with the opportunity to complete an international work experience program; and o Rotary Youth Leadership Awards (RYLA) whereby Rotary in conjunction with WSA, offer national competitors the opportunity to participate in their leadership development program.‚ WSA works closely with the Department of Education and Training who manage the Australian Apprenticeships Ambassadors Program.  Our past competitors who become Ambassadors work to raise the status of Australian Apprenticeships by promoting the Australian Apprenticeships system to schools, students and businesses.
