column39: Harm prevention: prevention and control of abusive behaviours experienced by women and girls, being any of emotional abuse, physical abuse, sexual abuse, suicide, self harm,harmful gambling and substance abuse.
column41: Harm prevention: prevention and control of abusive behaviours experienced by women and girls, being any of emotional abuse, physical abuse, sexual abuse, suicide, self harm,harmful gambling and substance abuse.Rosie is a dynamic resource for girls and young women to connect with the best of the web, helping them to navigate lifeês tricky situations and assisting to grow the resilience of girls and young women that lessens their vulnerability to harm. During 2015-16 the website recorded over 163,000 visits. Since its launch to end June 2016, the website has accumulated over 1,216,000 page visits. The Waratah Project - Exploring Menstruation & Menopause in a Positive & Contemporary Context - aims to influence the way girls and women collectively think about menstruation and menopause away from old notions of shame and towards a more positive way of understanding these universal aspects of female experience in a way that lessen feelings of emotional stress, poor self-esteem, body image and personal confidence. A research report was completed in September 2015. The next step is the completion of a final landmark publication which is in progress and it is expected to be completed in 2016-17Our documentary film titled ´Torn Apart _ Rebuilding lives after family separationê was completed and launched in the previous financial year, aiming to raise community awareness of the harmful impacts and long term effects of family breakdown, and to provide practical strategies to support women to build resilience and avoid the potential long-term downward spiral into poverty and hardship, which can often result. During 2015-16  Torn Apart documentary copies have been distributed to a wide range of agencies working nationally in the field of relationship counselling, family violence and the protection of children.The Fighting Friendship project aims to help address the harmful effects of dispossession experienced by Indigenous peoples across Australia. Three films were completed by June 2016 and will be uploaded onto VWT-DTWGês website after minor editing for web compatibility is completed.In 2015-16 the Dugdale Trust for Women & Girls was successful in securing multi-years funds necessary to develop and deliver the proposed Club Respect project. For the next three years, this project will support major sports codes across Australia in adopting respectful relationships programs that utilise the Be The Hero! bystander approach, embedding it down to junior levels. The Iramoo Zone project has been planned and designed on the success of the Be The Hero program. The aim of the project is to engage and empower indigenous men, on a national scale, through a positive and effective leadership platform that enables them to influence conversations and change behaviours around violence and violence prevention.

column41: Contemporary Music Victoria exists to support the growth, participation and development of the Victorian contemporary music industry.As peak body for the Victorian contemporary music industry, Contemporary Music Victoria Inc.a. is the point of contact for Victorians to engage with and participate in the contemporary music industry and related activities.b. provides advocacy on behalf of contemporary music within the music industry, the wider community and governmentc. provides an industry development role through provision of programs and services and the creation of a knowledge hubd. provides activities to encourage celebration and promotion of contemporary Victorian music and to create a supportive cultural communitye. represents Victorian contemporary music interests at the local, national and international levels and participation of Victorian interests in national projects and other activities.f. is a relevant and strong organisation focused on good governance and community participationg. engages and fosters strong partnerships between the music industry, government and the communityh. aims to work from an understanding of not replicating services that are provided elsewherei. is broadly inclusive of the entire contemporary music community: all music genres, industry sectors and professions as well as being accessible for metropolitan and regional Victoria.j. aims be valuable to music makers in its activities whenever possiblek. provides for the support and fellowship of its members.Music Victoria is a strong voice and getting stronger. Over the last twelve months, Music Victoria has increased by its membership by 30%.Music Victoria was chosen to manage the Good Music Neighbours grant program which was developed to help live music venues manage noise issues and the Live Music Professionals program which will help upskill live music workers across the state.Music Victoria has also continued to develop strong working relationships with the State Government and local councils.A major achievement for the organisation this year was to sign off on a three-year funding arrangement with Creative Victoria. The three-year deal provides operational security to the organisation in the short term and will enable Music Victoria to focus on providing better outcomes for membersMusic Victoria also established the Victorian Artistsê Advisory Panel to complement our Regional Music Industry Advisory Panel and Womenês Music Industry Advisory Panel. These specialist groups will be vital in helping inform and advise the organisation and representing the music community.Music Victoria was involved in more than 35 professional Music Victoria made a submission to the City of Melbourne in support of buskers to be able to continue to play amplified music in Swanston Street. Busking provides a vital performance and commercial outlet for emerging and established artists and is part of Melbourneês cultural DNA.

The Glencoe Foundation supports the Walk for Life (WFL) program in Bangladesh.  Each year approx 4000 children are born with Clubfoot.  This is a debilitating condition which often results in the child being unable to walk and secure employment & they become a burden on their families and society.  WFL has been reducing the instances of clubfoot in Bangladesh through training of medical professionals in the Ponseti Method (a non invasive technique to correct the feet through a series of manipulation/casting and braces) which builds local capacity in the health system as well as, increasing awareness of the condition and its treatment.During the 2016 year approx 1200 new patients were enrolled in the program and 350 health professionals received training in the Ponseti Method.

At Clayton Preschool, we create a warm and welcoming environment for children and families.  We believe that the early years are a pivotal time in children's lives, and that kindergarten is an important and meaningful place of learning for them.  We believe that children learn best when they are active in their own learning, and that play is the natural vehicle for this to happen in early childhood.  We create a rich and engaging learning environment, in which children are encouraged to learn through play, through direct experience, through creating, through inquiry and through interaction with each other. Our teachers and educators engage in intentional teaching which is actively designed to build on the children's present level of development, and to enable them to move forward.  We have a richly diverse, multicultural community, within which all children, families and staff are valued and respected as they share their heritage, experiences and contributions with us.  We believe in working closely with parents and families, building strong partnerships in which we can cooperate to achieve the best learning and developmental outcomes for each child.  We encourage children to develop and express their connection to the other communities which form part of their lives: their family and cultural communities, the Clayton Community Centre and it's services within which we are placed, and the broader community within which we all live.

column2: Victorian Gum Genealogists Using Microcomputers Inc
column41: REPORT TO THE 32nd ANNUAL GENERAL MEETINGEarlier in the year we made some minor adjustments to the website in order to streamline some minor issues and it is interesting to report that the number of members now paying their subscriptions through the website has increased and the volume of work carried out by the volunteers in the office has been reduced.We have, in conjunction with Software MacKiev taken out a major Sponsorship for the Australian History and Genealogy Expo in Adelaide in October to help formally _launchî the MacKiev FTM. Duff Wilson from Ancestry will be joining us for that week in October. FTM is Duffês _babyî and he is here on secondment to MacKiev. We are planning full day workshops in Melbourne and Sydney (in conjunction with SAG) as well as presentations at the Adelaide Expo.Our Membership remains fairly steady at around 750 with membership gains slightly exceeding membership losses. Member losses occur for many reasons which include advancing years and changes of interest.Inspection of the Balance Sheet shows that the groupês total equity has increased from $121,182 at the end of 2015 to $142,337 at the end of 2016. The nett income for this year was lower than the previous year due in part to reduced sales of software whilst income from membership fees continues to support the Group. We finished the year with a surplus of $21,155.With total net assets of $142,337 and liabilities of $1,790 the group is in an extremely strong financial position.We have concentrated on establishing a reserve as we will be facing higher costs in the future for office accommodation. We rent an office from the Genealogical Society of Victoria (GSV) for a nominal amount. The GSV lease expires in 2018 at which time they will vacate the premises. Accordingly we are reviewing our office accommodation in terms of both requirement and location. Whatever and where ever we find premises our rental will be higher than it is currently.VicGUM is run by volunteers who freely give of their time for the benefit of the group as a whole.VicGum functions efficiently due to the voluntary input of many people; these being Graeme Simpson our Vice President who also acts as Webmaster and Gumnet manager as well as providing general technical input for our various items of equipment. John Donaldson as well as being the FTM _guruî also manages the membership database as well as being newsletter editor. Our financial management is efficiently handled by our Treasurer, Bob Mullner and his able assistant, Della Markey. The secretarial role is capably filled by David Stephen and Meg Bate manages our Facebook page. Balanced input at table discussions is provided by our other Committee members, Robyn Peacock and Malcolm Kingston. Our group is fortunate to have a talented Committee who contribute their energy, skills and experience to ensure the continued success of VicGum. My thanks to all who assist in so many ways. President

Interact works in partnership with  people who need support to maximise their health, wellbeing and opportunities for community participation and social inclusion. Our trained and experienced staff support a variety of community programs that provide opportunities for people to develop skills and interests, increase their social networks and maximise the choice and control they have over their own lives. We recognise that people with a disability have the right to be respected and the right to have equal opportunities to participate in the social, economic, cultural, political and spiritual life of the community. Our model is a self-directed approach, recognising that the person with a disability is at the centre, and to the extent that they are able, is in charge of their planning, funding and support responses. Interact provides the Job Services Australia (JSA) and Disability Employment Services (DES) programs. Under the DES program we assist people who have a disability, injury, learning difficulty or medical conditions into employment opportunities.

As an arts leader, the Melbourne Symphony Orchestra (MSO) is recognised as a national icon and ambassador for the arts and contributes significantly to the social and intrinsic value of Victoriaês cultural economy.   Australiaês oldest and one of its largest professional orchestras, the MSO works to improve the quality and vibrancy of our season through artistic leadership, providing the best customer experience, developing our artistic family and continuing our commitment to Australian music and musicians, creation of new work and collaborations.  In 2016, the MSO engaged over 3.35 million people through digital and broadcast channels, live in concert, at festivals and free events, on tour, via workshops and in schools.  Through the generous support of government funding partners, corporate sponsorship, bequests and individual donations, the MSO evolves to inspire and engage audiences across Victoria, Australia and internationally by making orchestral music available to everyone.   Together with its vast calendar of concert performances _ 163 performances of 110 different productions in 2016 _ the  MSO delivers an extensive youth and education program in Melbourne and across regional Victoria, as well as a vibrant and celebrated talent development program to develop Australiaês next generation of musicians. A total of ten MSO programs champion Australiaês emerging artists, many of which could not exist without philanthropic support.  The MSO and its Chorus of 145 volunteers provided the Victorian community with 22 free concerts in 2016. Our Sidney Myer Music Bowl concert series is celebrated as an annual gift to the 30,000 people who attend each year; the MSO Chorus performances at ANZAC Dawn & Commemorative services (2016 live audience - 52,000) are also valued highlights. The MSOês extensive education and community programs continue to provide opportunities for people of all ages to discover, explore, and learn more about music through performance, workshops and online experiences. Thanks to the generosity of our donors, these highly-valued programs engaged over 41,000 students, teachers and families in 2016. The Pizzicato Effect continued as the MSOês flagship community music program to inspire enhanced social, emotional and educational engagement through musical accomplishments. Thanks to continued support of trusts and foundations, the MSO provided 70 students from 20 schools in Melbourneês City of Hume with 9,856 contact hours of free instrumental tuition.  The MSOês Meet the Orchestra is similarly supported by MSO donors and engaged over 5,300 primary school children in 2016. Meet the Orchestra is part of Education Week, an extensive suite of concerts and activities which also included workshops and performances tailored towards primary/secondary school students and families. Education Week 2016 attracted close to 12,000 people, 28% of those able to access the program through the sponsored school initiatives & provision of sub

The Charity operates Olivet Aged Care and provides residential aged care, community care and Day care services for the elderly and infirm. We have come through another successful year providing care at Olivet and planning the future development of services for brethren and sisters. The committee has endeavored to exceed Government standards, provide activities for fellowship and spiritual wellbeing.   With our Fathers care and guidance we have met our financial goals and His continues blessing allows our ongoing viability and future planning.  Our priorities are to provide those things that identify us as The Christadelphian Welfare Association and provide accommodation in Independent Living Units, residential care, Respite and Day Care.  We have the help of volunteers who run and assist in many activities during the week and on weekends. Olivet has 80 listed volunteers who interact with the brothers and sisters each week and many more volunteers who run the Auxiliary fundraising activities and the many different brethren and sisters who attend the Memorial meeting each week to Exhort, Preside and play the piano.  Key Events: Moving into Admin Offices: Weêve now collected our reception and office area into one location, away from the living areas.  Now when we take personal enquiries and other meetings, we donêt interfere with the privacy of residents and the new location is going to be nearer the centre of the facility and much easier to welcome visitors and relatives and attend to the day to day administration.  Christadelphian Homes Conference _ May 2016: This is a biennial event held between the states where we have a formal venue for discussing the individual performance of our organisations within the general industry and what we think the future might hold.   The Conference was held over two days with members of the Committees of Management coming from NSW, SA & WA.   The topics ranged from presentations by Dr. Helen Rawson around research in aged care and the recognition that Dementia related illnesses are becoming more predominant in our society and specifically how it is managed by Carers to the changing face of the industry to Government funding and expanding competition.  This Conference not only keeps the respective Committees of Management in touch every two years but encourages and promotes regular contact throughout the year to share information and, when possible, take advantage of opportunities such as national supply contracts.  I would also thank the volunteers who arranged the wonderful dinner for all of our 60 guests.  Future Planning: As we reported last year, the Committee has been concentrating of the ongoing building plan to replace the older accommodation areas. Whilst plans are still in the development stage we have a working concept and a town planning application has been submitted to the Maroondah Council for approval.

And drives them even further from the system which claims to be working so hard to re-engage them.At JCS, we see ourselves as an example of how the system can work. We value being different. We do it using a curriculum which reconnects young people to education and even more importantly to the community and to themselves.

Statement of Purpose (abridged): Western Emergency Relief Network (WERN) will make a difference to those of our Community in need by providing emergency relief and assistance through our Member Welfare Agencies.   Program Description: WERN is a non-profit Incorporated Association comprising of interested Rotary Clubs in the designated area of operations and designed to supply good quality second hand furniture, electronic and whitegoods, to people in need. WERN is located at 3 Cross St. West Footscray.  Modelled on the existing and very successful Eastern _Emergency Relief Networkî (EERN) established in 1995, which provides the collection and distribution of emergency relief, in particular furniture through their 130+ member welfare agencies. The people assisted are those who have been identified to have an urgent need as a result of experiencing trauma or loss, where they have a need to move or perhaps cannot afford basic living requirements, where they are struggling to buy essentials such as furniture and other household goods. Such traumas include long-term illness, unemployment, loss of home and belongings through fire, domestic violence, lack of family support, homelessness, or refugee status.WERN is run and staffed by volunteers and is totally dependent upon the support and generosity of individuals, organizations, businesses and local government to fund its operations and meet its goals through member welfare agenciesê referral of clients in the northern and western regions of Melbourne.  WERN manages a group of volunteers responsible for the collection, assessment, the repair and cleaning of donated goods. WERN facilitates the supply of all appropriate items to be available to individuals and families in need through our network of Member Welfare Agencies. WERN currently holds in excess of 1,000 donated items available for distribution now.Rotary Clubs from Bacchus Marsh, Melton Valley, Wyndham and Sunshine have taken a lead role in establishing WERN and membership has now extended to include Caroline Springs and Werribee Clubs to provide this service for the northern and western regions of Melbourne. The Program currently operates from a warehouse located in West Footscray.  Area of Operations:  The Municipal Councils in the WERN region are: Brimbank; Hobsonês Bay; Hume; Maribyrnong; Melton; Moonee Valley; Moorabool; Moreland and Wyndham.  WERN is currently seeking Expressions of Interest from like-minded Welfare Agencies interested in joining WERN in a Member Agency partnership with a view to providing your Clients with free access to the services offered by WERN. The service currently provides free donations of available household furniture, whitegoods and electronics to Agencies or Clients within the programês area of operation.

column41: The primary purpose of Hepatitis Victoria is a Victorian community where there are no new viral hepatitis infections and where those who are living with viral hepatitis maximise their health and well being in a community free of stigma and discrimination.  During 2015-2016, Hepatitis Victoria - undertook initiatives to raise awareness of the risks of viral hepatitis including the 'Be Free From Hep C' campaign, raised awareness of the availability of new treatment medications for hepatitis C and supported individuals undertaking treatment; lobbied for and assisted in the development of separate Victorian state strategies for hepatitis B and hepatitis C; introduced the HEPReady  workforce training initiative; expanded the HEPSpeak public speakers program; introduced the Prisons Hepatitis Infoline for people in custody; commenced the development of on-line hepatitis risk assessment tools; conducted the 'Art Inside the West' information and education program for people in custody; significantly increased the use of social media platforms for the provision of information and education programs; increased visits to the Hepatitis Victoria website by 160%, with in excess of 118,000 unique visits to the Hepatitis Victoria website; broadened reach to and contact with culturally and linguistically diverse communities particularity in relation to hepatitis B, through the 'Mums to B' and 'B understood' programs; increased awareness of stigma and discrimination around viral hepatitis through 'Hepatitis Heroes' and 'Community Advocates'; provided information and support to people living with viral hepatitis and their families and carers, including answering 926 individual calls on the Hepatitis Infoline; conducted 168 training and education sessions across metropolitan Melbourne and regional Victoria, reaching nearly 4,400 people; distributed 70 electronic bulletins to 70,448 recipients.

Core function:Women's Legal Service Victoria assists women experiencing disadvantage who are facing legal issues arising from relationship breakdown or violence.We provide lawyers, advocates, educators and financial counsellors to work alongside experiencing disadvantage to promote their rights to live free from violence and make informed choices about their relationships.Training:Womenês Legal Service Victoria is the state-wide specialist provider of family violence legal education, training and professional development in Victoria. Our team builds the capacity of organisations and professionals to better respond to the legal needs of women experiencing family violenceCreating change:We advocate for law and policy that respects and promotes the rights of women. In particular, we drive the development of law and policy by challenging laws that unfairly impact on women experiencing violence and relationship breakdown and informing and advancing policy initiatives that promote the rights of women.

Kaleidoscope Australia Human Rights Foundation has continued to drive all our activities towards our organisational purpose and to be a reliable and respected advocate for the human rights of lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and intersex people in the Asia Pacific region.As part of our core activities we continued to produce Shadow Reports, advocate further on refugee rights and raise awareness through our publications, press, workshops, conferences and through dialogue with both sides of the political spectrum.KAHRFês shadow reporting has developed further each year since its establishment.  Kaleidoscope submits independent ´shadowê reports on the state of rights protection for sexual and gender minorities in countries in the Asia Pacific region to the various UN bodies that monitor compliance with the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR), the International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights (ICESCR) and the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women (CEDAW), as well as for the UN Human Rights Councilês regular Universal Periodic Review of the human rights record of member nations.  During the review year we submitted reports to all these bodies.We have established collaboration with an international association that is a coalition of organisations advocating for the advancement of human rights in relation to gender and sexuality at the UN Human Rights Council.   Kaleidoscope Australia has worked together with this organisation to draft Shadow Reports on LGBTI rights, for submission to the UN Human Rights Council on several Asia-Pacific nations.Finally, our first grant from the Global Equality Fund, allowed us to develop and deliver human rights training for Tongan LGBTI activists.  The program focused on using international human rights mechanisms to advance LGBTI rights locally.  Following its success we have been successful in securing another similar and more significant grant to deliver a program in the next financial year, the LGBTI Pacific Youth Forum.

Whittlesea Community Connections is a place based not for profit incorporated association. WCC aims to identify and break down barriers to accessing information and specialised support services and works towards building individual and community resilience. For more details, please see link below to our 2016 Year in Review: http://www.redcross.org.au/files/Red_Cross_Year_in_Review_2015-2016.pdf
column41: The Australian Red Cross is made up of two divisions, the Blood Service and Humanitarian Services. The Blood Service plays an important role in the healthcare system by ensuring that patients in Australian hospitals receive life-saving blood products, delivering world-class research and provide expertise in diagnostic, transplantation and other clinical services. The Blood Service spent $576m in 2016, collecting and supplying 1.3m blood donations, with supplies remaining in inventory sufficiency bands for 339 days of the year. In 2015, Humanitarian Services spent $197.5m in delivery of humanitarian programs, emergency and disaster response. Most of our disaster and emergency work was carried out supporting the recovery from cyclone Winston in Fiji and the devastating earthquake in Nepal, the humanitarian crisis in Syria and the cyclone Pam in Vanuatu. We spent $180.8m on our everyday work to address disadvantage across Australia and overseas. Our program spend decreased from last year as a result driven by the down-sizing of our migrant support services. Our program activities within humanitarian services are defined according to our priority areas - Disaster and Emergency services, Locational disadvantage, Social Inclusion, International Aid and Development, International Humanitarian Law, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander programs and Migrant Support Services. Despite reduced government funds our spending on locational disadvantage and social inclusion increased this year.

The Shantideva Buddhist Foundation Ltd has had a busy and productive period disseminating Buddhist teachings and providing healing, private consultations, blessings and succor to its members and other interested people from the community in Australia and farther afield.A significant focus for the Board of the last 12 months has been applying for a Distinguished Talent Visa in the Profession category for our very important employee and teacher _ Ngawang Tenzin Tsadong Rinpoche.Since his arrival in Australia The Venerable Tsadong Rinpoche Ngawang Tenzin has provided great benefit to the lives of many people. His profound understanding of the Buddhaês principals of compassion, non-violence, harmony and self-responsibility, enables him to assist not only the expansive Buddhist community in Australia (this being the fastest growing religion in Australia), but also the broader Australian community.In a very short period since becoming a teacher for the Shantideva Buddhist Foundation Ltd, he has attained great respect and reputation. The Venerable Tsadong Rinpoche Ngawang Tenzin contributes both in and out of his teaching roles. He participates in a range of community activities providing spiritual guidance and support to a wide range of people. He is an outstanding leader and spiritual teacher. His personal qualities, his lineage and his profound grasp of Buddhist philosophy inspire people across cultures and generations.The wisdom and compassion Tsadong Rinpoche Ngawang Tenzin provides through his teachings, academic writings and personal interactions is of exceptional value to individuals, institutions and organizations and an on-going and precious asset to the Australian community.Another focus has been the establishment and upkeep of a website including videos of teachings and information of upcoming events, as well as the production of brochures, an email databhase, a Facebook page and other activities to disseminate the teachings, alert people of coming events and provide mindfulness training and Buddhist teachings. The teachings of Rinpoche and Buddhism in general help us to know the mind, to see how our mind works and how we often react habitually rather than respond thoughtfully, so that we can move beyond our narrow mind to embrace different perspectives. This openness and willingness to listen and embrace other perspectives helps our members and other people in Australia to adapt and thrive in a world where we are deeply interconnected and have to learn to collaborate if we are to survive and thrive. The principles of kindness and compassion emulated by His Holiness the Dalai Lama and all his monks and followers can only support Australians and the Australian culture. Buddhism propounds equality and that essentially we are all the same _ we all wish to be happy and to overcome suffering.The teachings of Rinpoche and the activities of The Shantideva Buddhist Foundation come from a position of understanding, compassion and humility.

column39: Working with children in trauma using all mediums of art to emotionally strengthen and empower.
column41: Our Purpose - A Not-for-Profit organization, The Art Cabriolet (AC) provides multiple platforms for art expression and experience that target remedial outcomes for children in trauma or living in challenging conditions. AC uses art in all its mediums and forums to emotionally strengthen children dealing with physical or psychological distress resulting from any type and level of trauma. Repetitive multiple forums of art are made available and accessible for remedial outcomes in children we work with. We custom design art programs in conjunction with health carers, social workers, psychologists, teachers and even parents. Our primary goal is to produce safe, creative and fun environments that divert and distract children whilst implementing educative and restorative art programs. The primary outcome is to nurture mental health, general well-being, increase self-esteem and self-empowerment. AC has artists, art therapists, play therapists and volunteers to implement art programs. Art strengthens childrenês mindset and emotions. AC provides and supplies all equipment and materials necessary for the production of art in all mediums. The art programs are ´profiledê to suit childrenês circumstances so that relief and release from physical, emotional and/or psychological suffering and distress can be harnessed and encouraged. We currently have ongoing programs running with partnered organisation such as, Monash Children's Cancer Centre - Art in Residence Program, Very Special Kids - EOL, - Holiday Program,

Our major campaigns are febfast, a national campaign that encourages Australians to take a ´pause for a causeê, and Ride the Night, a night time cycling event that is run in partnership with Bicycle Network. column39: Recording the history of Yallourn on our website
column41: Yallourn was built in the early 1920s and demolished in the early 1980s by the State Electricity Commission of Victoria (SECV). Its purpose was to house the workers of the Power Station, Briquette Factory and Open Cut. After it was demolished, if left nowhere for ex-residents and friends to visit, to show their children where they grew up and went to school. Our Association holds an annual reunion for everyone to attend and sends out two newsletters per year full of memories and stories. We also run two websites - www.virtualyallourn.com which has been recognised twice now with Commendation Awards from the Royal Historical Society of Victoria in both 2015 and 2016 (with a special note from the Judge that this website is the largest archive of Yallourn material) and our other website, www.yallourn.org which gives details of the reunions and how to join the Association, sale of memorabilia etc.

Review Of OperationsIn 2016 the Australian Centre for Contemporary Art (ACCA) developed a program of exhibitions of work by significant artists from around the world, commissioned ambitious new works by Australian and international artists, and delivered a range of sophisticated and engaging education and public programs including talks, lectures, symposia, performances, screenings, music and events. In 2016 105,557 people attended exhibitions, 147,698 attended public programs, off-site and special projects and events and 8,447 students participated in Artist/Educator led education programs, comprising a total audience of 261,702.In 2016 ACCA presented a dynamic and critically-engaged program of exhibitions within the gallery featuring Australian and International artists:The Biography of ThingsThe Biography of Things brought together work by eleven artists with a shared interest in_objects, archives and collectionsNEW16NEW16 brought together eight newly commissioned projects from emerging artists around Australia. Whilst independent and diverse in approach, the projects shared a common interest in navigation and negotiation: exploring thresholds in the relationships between the artistsê and their work; each other; the visiting public; surrounding architecture; and the wider environment. Ulla von Brandenburg: It has a golden sun and an elderly grey moonACCA presented a major survey of German artist Ulla von Brandenburgês work bringing together song, theatre, film, architecture and installation in theatrical presentations. Painting, More PaintingACCA presented Painting, More Painting the first major survey of Australian Painting for over decade.Gerard Byrne: A late evening in the futureGerard Byrne: A late evening in the future was produced in association with the Melbourne International Festival. The exhibition presented a curatorial reconsideration of the artistês work and was a considerable accomplishment from a curatorial as well as technical and exhibition design perspective. Sovereignty Sovereignty was a major new exhibition focussing on the contemporary art of First Nations peoples of South East Australia. Touring ExhibitionACCAês major survey of works by leading Australian artist Pat Brassington: ç Rebours continued its national tour travelling to the University of Queensland Art Museum in Brisbane.Special Projects, Public and Education Programs The exhibition program was supported by a diverse range of special projects, public and education programs. These included talks, lectures, symposia, performances, screenings, music and events designed to reach audiences of all ages across a broad demographic spectrum.PublishingACCAês publishing program continued with the production of three exhibition catalogues, ten artist videos and digital podcasts, and well as two international collaborations on major publications associated with international artists presented at ACCA in 2016.

The Victorian Principals Association conducted a comprehensive range of activities to help achieve its purpose of advancing education and public debate.  Through these activities the Association aims to be instrumental in optimizing the educational opportunities and outcomes for students in all government primary schools in Victoria.  To build leadership capacity in the sector, the VPA offered a high quality Professional Learning program to both members and non-members.  In 2015 - 2016 this included:  -  running and subsidizing over 35 full day workshops that encompassed the many aspects of school leadership. -  an Annual Conference with a two day program of renowned presenters and opportunities for collegiate discussions and networking.  -  the Principals as Literacy Leaders program involving five modules and ten hours follow up coaching for each participant.   This year 85 school leaders were involved in this program.  - a 16 day student study tour to China for 50 students and their teachers which provided outstanding opportunities for cultural exchange and understanding, language acquisition and personal development.   - a highly successful program for aspiring leaders.  - a Statewide Forum which included speakers who presented on a range of key areas in education and was attended by 160 schools leaders from across the state.   Another important aspect of the VPA's work is its advocacy role of advancing public debate in the education field.  This has involved the VPA representing the views and concerns of Victorian government primary school leaders and providing expert advice to government.  To this effect, the VPA was involved on an ongoing basis in government consultations, stakeholder groups and meetings with the various sections of the education department and associated government departments, with Ministers of Educations and other political leaders and with other professional groups and stakeholders.  The VPA has provided information and advice to school leaders through its Member Advisor service, a weekly VPA Newsletter and its website.   Collegiate networking has been facilitated by regular regional meetings where information about government initiatives and effective approaches to teaching and learning, student and staff welfare and school leadership are discussed and shared.   This year 37 such meetings were organised.  A particular focus for the VPA has been supporting smaller rural and remote schools to participate in professional learning.  Twenty scholarships were offered for leaders of these schools to attend the Annual Conference and casual relief teachers were funded to release teaching principals from their classes, enabling them to attend professional learning programs.  The VPA also facilitated four study awards for school leaders to explore initiatives in other states or countries that have direct relevance to students at their own schools.

As the diversity and size of Arabic speaking communities continues to grow, Arabic Welfare continues to respond to client and community needs with flexible and innovative programs. Our major strength is that we have a community based focus and respond to changing needs of our clients and their communities. We continue to advocate on their behalf and continue to be involved with both new and well-established communities to ensure that their needs are met.   In recognition of growing needs for settlement services in the growth corridor of Northern Metropolitan Melbourne, Arabic Welfare has established a permanent additional office in Broadmeadows. Our new office has been refurbished over the past few months and is now well-equipped for clients and service providers to access our programs and staff at the new location.  Throughout 2015 -16, we have continued to strengthen our working relationship with multicultural providers, government departments and the community. We have focused strongly on youth engagement in our Diversity and Social Cohesion project and have facilitated partnerships to deliver youth specific projects. We have partnered with the Brotherhood of St Lawrence on a youth engagement and transition project and we have also partnered with the Upfield Soccer Club to strengthen youth participation in local sports.   In the past year, we have undertaken many youth focused activities in our new Diversity and Social Cohesion Project. We have worked in collaboration with Victoria Police and developed joint youth programs and forums which have seen positive outcomes for young people of Arabic speaking backgrounds. With contributions from local schools, youth service providers and sporting clubs, our Diversity and Social Cohesion project has made significant inroads to young peopleês sense of belonging and active participation in their local community.   Arabic Welfare has continued to explore opportunities for service delivery that reflects the changing needs of aged/ageing members of diverse Arabic speaking backgrounds. Arabic Welfare has worked collaboratively with Dutch Care and the New Hope Foundation to identify the growing needs of aged/ageing CALD community groups. Although the nature of our future service delivery for our elders is a work in progress, we look forward to a productive year ahead as we seek to more clearly address the needs of Arabic speaking elders.

Kids Off The Kerb (KOTK) is headquartered in Thomastown, Victoria, where it has use of a significant amount of factory, office and training space from which to conduct its social enterprise projects. The social enterprises conducted by KOTK include whitegoods recycling; corporate uniform secure shredding and recycling; textile and shoes collections and recycling. KOTKês projects are most often run in conjunction with local government and other community organisations, including Job Service Providers. The 2016 year saw a significant increase in work for the dole programs conducted by KOTK.  For many years KOTK has operated a youth space called Our Place at 131B Hopkins Street, Footscray, which is a well-established centre that has historically been providing health and welfare services to large numbers of people each month. A new project is _Our Place Ivanhoeî which was established in 2016 as a community hub and social enterprise incubator, with space available to other community groups to collaborate on projects and share ideas and experiences.  A community caf_ was opened at the space in June 2016.   The primary focus of KOTKês work is young people, especially those who are _hard to reachî, such as homeless young people; newly arrived migrants and refugees; unemployed young people; young people from culturally and linguistically diverse backgrounds; and young people who are disengaged from the education system. See www.kidsoffthekerb.org for more detail.

Each year, 8.5 million Australians have some kind of legal need, and over half of them donêt receive professional help. Many cannot afford it, other are unaware that it is available. This is the justice gap. Justice Connect helps close the gap by giving people free legal help.  In 2015-16, with our network of hundreds of lawyers we provided thousands of people with high quality, free legal advice, representation and training. This represents tens of thousands of hours of pro bono work for people and organisations who would have otherwise missed out. Our work helps to close the justice gap for people experiencing disadvantage and strengthens the capacity of the community organisations who work with them.Across all our programs, we received 6,644 requests for assistance and provided legal advice or a referral to 2,713 people (including community organisations) and training sessions to 2,435 community organisations.Our efforts to close the justice gap rely on the skill and hard work of our pro bono partners and members. To that end, we worked with 1,329 lawyers, including 212 barristers, to provide over 30,000 hours of pro bono legal work to our clients. We also offered support and guidance to all these lawyers, providing specialist training to 1,134 people (more than double the previous year). Our members include law firms, corporate legal departments, community legal centres, university law schools, the Law Institute of Victoria, the Victorian Bar. We are grateful for our membersê continued willingness to partner with Justice Connect and to support our vision.We continued our efforts to challenge and change laws that increase or perpetuate the justice gap. Across all areas of our casework, we identified, and advocated to change, unfair laws and policies.Most notably, our Homeless Law and Seniors Law programs made submissions to Victoriaês Royal Commission into Family Violence, highlighting the interconnectedness of family violence and homelessness, as well as the importance of considering elder abuse in the broader context of family violence. The recommendations of both submissions were taken up in full or in part by the Commissionês final report.Our Not-for-profit program also had a big year, taking its lauded Information Hub national, as well as receiving a three-year, $825,000 grant from the NSW Department of Family and Community Services to take our training and advice services even further into NSW.Our Referral Service targeted the ´legacy caseloadê of asylum seekers needing protection visas; Victoriaês ´expungement schemeê, allowing men who had been convicted under since-stricken sodomy laws to have those convictions removed; and helping transgender teenagers seeking hormone treatment receive the legal permission they require.You can read more in our Annual Impact Report athttp://www.justiceconnect.org.au/sites/default/files/Annual%20Report%20split%202016%20FINAL%20Web.pdf

column41: CPSSN is a support group for carers who provide for individuals with intellectual disabilities. The organisation holds monthly information sessions, where disability service providers and government institutions such as Centrelink, Victoria Police and the NDIA etc., come and talk to the carers about their services and rights as carer for the individual with a disability. CPSSN facilities this mutual information exchange information by providing Chinese Cantonese and Chinese Mandarin interpreters and translators. In addition, the organisation organises annual recreation activities for the carers and the individual with a  disability. At these events, they are able to meet new people. During these events, carers are able to share their experiences with each other, which improves their overall mental wellbeing, as they are able to increase their self-esteem by helping others in need.

The Torch has two objectives that it seeks to achieve through the Indigenous Arts in Prison and Community program.Through art, cultural and vocational support, provide a forum for cultural exploration, expression and strengthening for members of the Indigenous community who are incarcerated and:Through supporting creative skills and connection to culture, work with participants to find a new way forward on their return to community and reduce recidivism. To achieve these objectives, The Torch runs a state wide Indigenous Arts in Prisons & Community program that is set within the context of the Victorian Aboriginal Justice Agreement. Its focus is on the role of cultural strengthening and artistic expression in the rehabilitative process of Indigenous prisoners and ex-prisoners and redressing the over-representation of Indigenous people in the Victorian Justice system. The last twelve months has seen tremendous growth in activity at The Torch. Better resourcing has meant greater program delivery both to incarcerated Indigenous men and women in the 12 prisons in Victoria in which we operate and to participants in our post release program. At the beginning of 2016, the state government launched the Aboriginal Arts Policy Model initiative. This allows The Torch to act as agents for participants of the ´In Prisonê program and to sell artworks on their behalf. Money received from artwork sales is held in trust by Corrections Victoria and made available to artists when they are released from prison. This important development acknowledges the scope for our cultural program to reduce recidivism rates for Indigenous people. Cultural learning and art making builds confidence and social capital and, if we can build markets for art sales, the chance to make a living by selling artworks offers participants an achievable pathway to greater economic stability. Participating artists receive 100% of the funds of artworks sales and image licensing agreements facilitated by The Torch on their behalf. The Torch produced three key exhibitions this year, each showcasing artworks made by the 120 + Indigenous women and men accessing the program.

column2: The Field Naturalists Club Of Victoria Inc
column39: The FNCV has eight special interest groups (SIGS) through which its activities are conducted. Fungi, Geology, Marine research, Microscopy, Terrestrial Invertebrates and Juniors.  These SIGS are engaged in education and research through activities, meetings, projects and publications.  The FNCV also publishes 6 editions of the Victorian Naturalist a year - a refereed journal.
column41: The 8 special interest groups listed in Section B above are  engaged in education and research through activities, meetings, surveys and publications.  The Fauna Survey group and the Marine research Group in particular,  but also other groups contribute to animal protection through their surveys, eg. the long running survey of Leadbeaters Possum in the central highlands and the ongoing Rushworth Survey,  The group has recently worked closely with Parks Victoria on projects s at Baal Baal,  Annuello, Metropolitan Melbourne parks etc.  All surveys are carried out under permit and the results are lodged with the appropriate body. The Fungi group has discovered  many new fungi species in Victoria and has contributed enormously to Fungimap.  Marine research has discovered new species and monitored the spread of pest species.   FNCV educates the public through its regular meetings through the 6 editions of the Victorian Naturalist published a year year - a refereed journal.  and through other publications such as 3 fungi DVD's.  The Juniors group introduces and educates  children from 5 to 18 to all aspects of natural history.  Over 50 families belong to the Juniors group.   All this is achieved by Volunteers.  The only paid person in the FNCV is an office administrator who works 2 and a half days a week. There is a lot more I could add to how this organisation achieves its purposes. Please read about its comprehensive program at fncv.org.au

column41: Deafness Foundation grants program is focussed towards achieving the purpose to improve wellbeing and promote equality for people who are deaf and hard of hearing by focussing on 1:  Access; 2:  Awareness; and 3:  Diagnosis, treatment and prevention.  The key priority areas for the Foundation are 1:  Minimising the incidence of preventable hearing loss;2:  Enhancing awareness of issues for people who are deaf or hard of hearing;3:  Strengthening and building partnerships and collaborative relationships;4:  Supporting people with hearing loss5:  Serving Australia wide.The Annual Grants Program provides funding to enable organisations across Australia to fund resources which benefit specifically their local communities.  This years grants included an Audiology Resource Booklet designed for Indigenous clients in the Barwon region; an Early Intervention program for children with partial hearing loss; a Sound & Light Integration Project at a school in NSW to assist students to recognise timings, etc. (eg by flashing lights); funding of an Online Hub for Musicians 4 Hearing to provide hearing awareness materials for musicians and gig-goers.   The opportunity to assist rural communities is vital to enabling those with a hearing loss to be included via the funding of a Soundfield System in the Church Hall; thus providing amplification for activities undertaken at the Hall, be they weddings, funerals, activities or community meetings.  The soundfield system is portable and can be moved from the church to the hall.  Our Grants program has funded significant research outcomes including a Hearing element of the ASPREE Project and the Peter Howson Clinical Research Fellowship for the 2016-17 period to Dr Kerryn Saunders on Early Identification and Management of Congenital Cytomegalovirus Hearing Loss / A New Clinical Model.  Congenital Cytomegalovirus (or cCMV) is a significant cause of deafness in babies.

WDV has a key focus on promoting the health and well-being of women with disabilities through a range of different strategies designed to directly empower women and to indirectly empower them by influencing government and the community. We delivered leadership and empowerment programs; distributed a suite of fact sheets to empower women; developed a violence prevention training program; developed a health position paper and developed a new fact sheet addressing NDIS facts for women. We wrote submissions to the Royal Commission on Family violence and the Victorian Inquiry into Abuse in Disability Care as well as multiple submissions regarding the NDIS, health and violence prevention. We piloted a Health Practitioner Education program in conjunction with the Royal Womenês Hospital about how to provide accessible quality health services to women with disabilities; and we have partnered with Deakin University in undertaking a national research program to better understand how family violence services respond to women with disabilities. Empowering women with disabilities is the focus of our Womenês Empowerment Program. WDV run Enabling Women leadership courses, mentoring programs and facilitate statewide safeguarding and leadership networks. We also have a Women Leading by Example workshop and the biennial Brenda Gabe Awards to further promote and encourage acknowledgement of community contribution and leadership of women with disabilities. Four Enabling Women leadership programs have been run in 2016 in the areas of Wangaratta, Bendigo, Doncaster and Footscray. These programs empowered women to be more involved in their local community and to understand how they can interact with local health and community services. WDV have also continued to liaise with the National Disability Insurance Agency regarding how policy and processes can respond to rights and needs of women with disabilities. Our Gender and Disability Project aims to prevent gender-based violence. We are continuing to implement and evaluate learning packages for disability services. In the past, we have trained women with disabilities to provide education to disability services to improve their sensitivity to the needs of women with disabilities.

Every day, Melbourne City Mission works with some of Melbourne and Victoriaês most vulnerable individuals, families and communities. Every week, we help thousands of people escape and avoid disadvantage, economic exclusion and social isolation. Weêve been around for almost as long as Melbourne itself and over the years have adapted and evolved alongside the people we work with, always responding to the changing needs of communities. Our staff are dedicated professionals, with the expertise to deliver holistic, integrated services that really make a powerful and sustainable difference to peopleês lives. We work with the most vulnerable and disadvantaged in our society. From children living with a disability, or young people with nowhere to call home, to people who need assistance into education or employment, we work alongside them, so they can build a better future for themselves. We help people find their own path to independence, providing them with the support they need along the way.  While we support people experiencing disadvantage, we also advocate for social change to reduce the number of people experiencing disadvantage and to intervene as early as possible to limit the damage done by the experience.
Good Cycles worked with over 270 people from disadvantaged backgrounds providing them with education, training, employment and affordable transport in the 2016 Financial Year.

column41: Mayflower's purpose is to provide care without compromise through responsive and innovative aged care services and independent seniors living options that enhance independence, wellbeing and lifestyle.  We achieve this through our accredited residential aged care services at Mayflower Brighton by providing holistic care options that suit the needs of residents, and their families, in relation to individual medical, physical, social, spiritual and emotional support.  At Mayflower we consult with every new resident and their family representative to develop an individually tailored Care Plan that meets the needs and wishes of that resident. This Care Plan is monitored and reviewed on a regular basis to ensure that Mayflower responds to any changes in health status or requirements.  Mayflower's focus on person-centred care is also reflected in our qualified nursing staff, who monitor and manage the health and wellbeing of our residents 24 hours a day.  In conjunction the personal care staff provides services including assistance with dressing, bathing, meals and other activities of daily living. Specialised services include dementia and palliative care plus we have respite places.  Each and every day our staff and volunteers continue to provide a range of social and physical activities as part of our buoyant resident lifestyle programs. These activities support the cultural and spiritual wishes of the residents.  Events such as concerts, outings, topical and celebratory functions are a frequent occurrence.
Sales of tickets helps to fund ongoing public dance performances and educational activities.
Resources received helped improve the facility for the residents we support that call home.  We also delivered a few small fundraising events.

Southport Community Legal Service (the Service) is a generalist community legal centre servicing the people of Port Melbourne, Garden City, South Melbourne, Albert Park, Middle Park and Southbank. It is a not-for-profit organisation established 28 years ago and funded by the City of Port Phillip. The Service operates a day service and two night services.The purposes for which the Service was established are set out in its Rules as follows:(a) to provide a free legal advice, assistance and referral service to the people of the western side of the City of Port Phillip (including South Melbourne, Port Melbourne, Beacon Cove, Garden City, Montague, Southbank, Fishermanês Bend, Albert Park and Middle Park); and(b) to promote community awareness of the law, and to encourage community participation in the legal process; and(c) to promote changes to the law that will be of benefit to the community; and(d) to assist the people of the western side of the City of Port Phillip in any way the Committee of the Service thinks appropriate.

column41: Lighthouse activities centre on three core priorities (i.e. Presence, Position & Performance) across all business divisions (i.e. Governance, Administration, Facilities/Support & Science. All divisions are dependent on each-others respective activities & appropriately balanced to be consistent, attainable, sustainable & expandable. In addition, our efforts sought to assure effectiveness & efficiency plus, best practice to meet the aspirations/expectations of all.  Our re-emergence from an imposed period of hiatus has continued to gather impetus & ground _ Notably in regard to our core priorities being progressively accomplished in many divisional activities. However, our research aspirations in terms of laboratory performance & outcome are still in need of more funding, to support our research endeavours. In prelude & in-keeping with our position priority, we have sought access to public research venues & considered the establishment of a private autonomous research facility as backup (i.e. in the event that space at a public venue is denied or not available). In addition, we have outreached to research peers for cooperation & commenced recruitment of our research team to help with project planning preparations.  It is anticipated that Lighthouse will have completed its re-emergence phase with research performance & outcomes demonstrated in the coming financial year.  A budget with diversified revenue streams circa $500k PA is sought to underpin a critical mass. This mass will include several senior investigators plus, 10-20 post-graduate investigators co funded & co-supervised with partner groups to expand research scope & themes. Re-establishing a WA head-quarter & satellite operations interstate is also planned. Key objects, aims & outcomes are summarized as follows:Object 1 Rekindle fundraising & in turn cash-flow to underpin core activities that facilitate research.Outcome: Four WA permit raffles were completed - An audit also undertaken. Charitable collection licences were applied/re-applied for (approved in the new financial year) _ Fundraising primarily occurred at WA shopping centres & to a lesser degree via pilot social media & crowd funding outreach programs interstate.Object 2 Improve the financial position, i.e. reducing liabilities, increasing assets, utilising volunteers & minimising expenditure.Outcome: The balance sheet is moving in a positive direction. Volunteers contributed 4000hrs using their own personal resources. Object 3 Explore & enable researchOutcome: Proposals & correspondence were prepared & presented to public research establishments & key government research authorities/officials - Research peers were engaged to explore opportunity for cooperation/collaboration - Recruitment drives for research personnel were implemented _ A conference was attended _ Pending research programs & projects have been planned, considered & explored. A detailed annual report will be appear on a pending revised website

column41: cohealth delivers a broad and diverse range of community health and support services in and around Melbourneês CBD, and northern and western suburbs.   cohealth operates from 40 sites across 14 municipalities. The community health approach ensures that services offered are the best value, most effective and meet the needs of the people using them.  cohealthês services and programs for local communities include specialist services to support people living with chronic illness; people at risk of harm associated with alcohol and drug use; people who are, or are at risk of being, homeless; children; Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people; and refugees and asylum seekers. cohealth also provides mental health recovery services; medical and oral health services and a range of therapists who support people to live independently at home and manage their physical and mental health; counsellors, and many more services and programs to meet peopleês needs and circumstances.  cohealth promotes health and wellbeing, works to prevent ill-health and better manage health conditions, and is a keen advocate for improved access to health care for all. cohealth works closely with the people who access services to design and develop programs to improve individual and community health and reduce costs to the public health system.

Brentwood kindergarten is a place where children, families and early childhood professionals are valued.  We believe kindergarten is a special time in a child's life and a place where children are recognised as being effective and competent learners.   Our play based curriculum‚      Implements the Victorian Early Years Learning and Development Framework(VEYLDF) along with the National Early Years Framework (EYLF)  ‚      Is implemented within a stimulating indoor/ outdoor learning environment all year round ‚      Recognises that all children are individual ‚      Supports children to be able to express their own ideas, see meaning in what they are thinking, meet challenges and solve problems‚      Ensures every child experiences success in their learning and development  ‚      Promotes secure attachments and trusting relationships ‚      Encourages, independence, resilience, critical thinking and informed risk taking; ‚      Promotes communication  ‚      Supports children to become caring people and motivated learners who are able to enjoy respectful, positive relationships with others.  Educators work in partnership with our families to achieve common outcomes for all children.  In our work with parents we  ‚      Understand respectful and caring relationships contribute to the delivery of effective learning experiences ‚      Recognise parents as their childês first and most influential teachers; ‚      Use each families understanding of their child to support shared decision-making about their child's learning and development ‚      Respect, celebrate and value the individual backgrounds and unique culture and customs of families  ‚      Communicate with families on their child's learning through formal and informal discussions, portfolios and program diary stories/reflections ‚      Encourage families (including extended family members) to become actively involved in our programs Sustainable living practices and healthy lifestyles are embedded into our kindergarten community.  Our centre is committed to making the world a safer and greener place for all through encouraging children to  ‚      Recycle ‚      Compost ‚      Interact with nature  ‚      Care for animals  ‚      Garden ‚      Bring a healthy lunch box  We understand our kindergarten community is part of our wider community.  We believe it is important to  ‚      Support children and families to connect with each other ‚      Connect with local child and family support services ‚      Connect with and develop relationships with local services in the community  ‚      Value and understand our Australian Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander culture ‚      Contribute to the ongoing training and development of high quality childrenês services educators through welcoming pre- service teacher placements from universities‚      Support the inclusion of work experience school students in the educational program

The Alternative Technology Association (ATA) is a not-for-profit organisation that enables, represents and inspires people to live sustainably in their homes and communities. Established in 1980, the ATA provides expert, independent advice on sustainable solutions for the home to households, government and industry.We have helped thousands of households save money, reduce their environmental footprint and make their homes more comfortable. ATA is well respected in our sector for our technical expertise, communications capacity and an informed membership.The ATA delivers in four main areas:‚ Membership services.  ATA has 14 active branches across Australia and over 6000 members who are actively creating a sustainable future in their own homes and communities. The ATA provides an online and over the phone advice service for members, and member discounts from the ATA Webshop.‚ Communications. ATA provides independent information on sustainable solutions though our magazines ReNew: technology for a sustainable future and Sanctuary: modern green homes, as well as our websites and online tools, conducting Sustainable House Day and Speed date a Sustainability Expert events, and promoting good news stories through mainstream and social media.‚ Advocacy & Projects.  ATA advocates in government and industry arenas for policies that support household sustainability. ATA conducts research into new and emerging technologies and associated consumer behaviours. We also provide consultancy services based on our technical expertise in energy, water, transport and communications.‚ International Projects. ince 2003, ATA has been working with East Timorese communities to provide clean, renewable lighting and electricity. We have helped install solar lighting and power to more than 1,800 homes, community centres, orphanages, schools and hospitals in remote rural villages. We have a strong commitment to capacity building and training and a focus on the poorest rural communities.For more information see the ATA Annual Report: http://www.ata.org.au/wp-content/general/ATA_Annual_Report_2016.pdf

column39: Other activity: SecondBite Future Trust is a charitable trust. Its objects are to hold and invest money and property for the benefit of Approved Institutions. Currently, SecondBite, a registered charity(company limited by guarantee), is the only Approved Institution, and therefore the Trust exists exclusively for the benefit of this entity. The current aim of the Trust is to assist SecondBite in becoming self-sufficient and avoid the need for continual fundraising activities. SecondBite exists to provide access to fresh, nutritious food for people in need across Australia. SecondBite does this by rescuing and redistributing surplus fresh food, building community capacity in food skills and nutrition and advocating for an end to food insecurity. In the year ended 30 June 2016 SecondBite rescued and redistributed 10 million kg of fresh nutritious food, enough to provide 20 million meals to people in need. Scarf's purpose is to build the skills, knowledge, networks and confidence of young people from refugee/asylum seeker and migrant communities. Engaging in our program enables participants to break the unemployment cycle and fully participate in the community. Our activities in 2015/16 included:- Ran three 10-week seasonal programs, each providing places to eight young people facing barriers to employment (from refugee, asylum seeker and migrant communities)- Provided hands-on, industry relevant training in: coffee-making, beer education, wine education, bar basics, cocktail making, resume writing, interview practice, and formal restaurant service/order-taking- Provided our trainees with real, paid work experience and mentoring from hospitality professionals during Scarf Dinners at The Empress, Rupert on Rupert and Higher Ground - Provided one on one employment mentoring and job-seeking support to graduates; 70% of Scarf graduates in jobs six months after finishing the program- Ran our inaugural ´Do More Than Dineê fundraiser in May 2016, hosted by Matt Preston with food by Cumulus Inc, which raised $48K (http://bit.ly/1UDfZ5E)- Rolled out paid work placement program at venues including: Robert Burns Hotel, Half Moon and Penny BlackRan _Do More Than Drinkî fundraising campaign in Dec 2015, raising $17K (http://bit.ly/1NUFPZP)- Ran new program _Scarf Tasting Plateî for young asylum seekers, with Red Cross (Migration Support Programs), in Nov 2015 and March 2016 (http://bit.ly/1KJclhk)- Increased advocacy efforts in line with Scarfês vision for fair hiring practices for all young refugees, asylum seekers and new migrants

Peninsula Christian Care is working tirelessly within our local community to bring relief to those who find themselves in crisis. We help desperate families in need through the provision of emergency food packs, also feeding 80 people every week through our food bank grocery store called Pantry Plus. We provide no interest loans for vital household items (under the auspices of Good Shepherd Microfinance), and run various important support groups and community connections. Our Community Chaplain is also increasing her level of visiting, caring for individuals and families within our local community with pastoral care and support, plus a growing connection with one of our local high schools. The need in our immediate community is great. In a typical year we find ourselves providing: ‚ Counselling, prayer, support, coordination of events, community liaison, referral to appropriate community services, pastoral care, and a myriad of chaplaincy interactions. Our Community Chaplain also supports and encourages women prisoners, and their families, either in custody or upon their release.  ‚ Over 1000 precooked meals to people in desperate need.  ‚ Groceries and personal items to several thousand people through Pantry Plus.  ‚ Weekly art classes, craft activities class, womenês weekly support group, and a menês shed occur at the Care House on most days of the week.    ‚ A support network of volunteers assisting one of our local High Schools with assistance in reading, character development, and community care.  We call this our PENS program.  ‚ No Interest Loans (averaging $800 each) with more than 120 loan enquiries developing into an average of 10 active loans per year.  ‚ Countless hours of volunteer time is donated throughout our Peninsula Christian Care activities ensuring all of our programs are run as cost efficiently as possible.  Lives are being changed through Peninsula Christian Care every day.  Those changed lives include our volunteers who get incredibly blessed helping others!

column2: The Trustee For Helen Macpherson Smith Trust
column41: HMSTrustês vision for a strong, just and sustainable Victoria is underpinned by its five program areas: Education and Vocational Pathways, Culture and Heritage, Land and Environmental Stewardship, Regional Resilience and Health Advancement. These, along with the Trustês key objectives, provide the funding criteria for all grant applications. HMSTrust has three open grant rounds a year across three grant levels that range from Community One-off Grants up to $30,000 to major Social Impact Grants up to $200,000. From time-to-time, the Trust will invite expressions of interest for major Social Impact Lead Grants over $200,000. HMSTrust distributes an average of $4 million each year in grants that meet current community needs and maximise social impact and long-term benefits that can be delivered through strategic philanthropy. As at June 2016, HMSTrust has distributed $113 million to charitable institutions for the benefit of Victoria. For further information, please refer to the Annual Report on the Trust's website: www.hmstrust.org.au Please note: A revaluation loss of $5,632,051 as a negative other comprehensive income cannot be entered in Section E: Financial information of this AIS due to the ACNC system limitation. The ACNC have advised us to make this disclosure in this manner. Therefore please note that the total comprehensive loss for FY16 was $4,581,311.

We provided vegetarian meal as we believe that it is a healthy and environmentally friendly diet. It also teaches us to show compassion and respect to all living things. We discourage smoking and consumption of alcohol/drugs. This program benefits the participants and the general community in Australia. 2) Weekly study of the analects of Confucius Philosophy -filial piety means to be good to one's parents; to take care of one's parents; to engage in good conduct , not just towards parents but also outside the home so as to bring a good name to one's parents and ancestors; not be rebellious, show love, respect and support; display courtesy; wisely advise one's parents, including dissuading them from moral unrighteousness -a strong family is the root of a stable society. 3)Holy assembly - we held 2-day Holy assembly to teach people about cultivation which is found in its reverence for heaven and earth; honour and admiration of enlightened teacher and deities in the cosmos. Its foundation lie in loyalty and truthfulness, honour and respect to one's parents, harmony among friends and neighbours, humility, purity in thoughts and virtues; to find peace within one's heart and mind and cultivating a sense of right and wrong to help ourselves and achieve harmony with others.4) Dao/Blessing receiving ceremony - we provided the ceremony to the public average once a month in the fiscal year 2016.5) Senior class was held twice a week to the public - praying, singing and doing exercise;6) Junior class was held once a week - teach traditional Chinese culture, sign language and craft.7) Home visits and outings - we provided counsel and moral support to religious members, their family /friends and inquirer of the faith. Through these events, we hoped to strengthen family bonds, seal up generation gaps and build better relationships with each other.

column41: Down Syndrome Victoria (DSV) works alongside people with Down syndrome and their families, so that they reach their full potential and live the life they choose. Established as a not-for-profit organisation in 1978, DSV is the statewide peak membership organisation representing people with Down syndrome and their families. DSV delivers its mission by:‚providing support for individuals with Down syndrome and their families based on a model of empowerment; ‚being a pre-eminent source of quality information and resources; ‚sharing knowledge and experience to build the capacity of families and professionals to support individuals with Down syndrome and ensure they meet their full potential; ‚and via systemic advocacy. DSV provides a whole-of-life service offering personal support and information to families particularly new parents after the birth of a baby with Down syndrome; advocacy, information and support for individuals with Down syndrome; peer support groups around the State (MyTime and NDIS and Me groups); an Education Support service to assist students with Down syndrome and their teachers in mainstream schools; Club21 _ a peer support and social groups for adults with Down syndrome; an annual Family Fun Day and other events; education and information sessions for families; information and professional development for health and education professionals; a regular member journal `Voiceê and subscriber e-newsletter `DNewsê; and a library of Down syndrome specific resources.
