The support from private philanthropic donors continues to be a source of encouragement for Trust for Nature staff. Their generosity in complementing government funding has been central to meeting the challenges of biodiversity conservation in Victoria. Such private support will be increasingly important as the Trust, guided by its 2013 Statewide Conservation Plan, pursues strategic priorities for conservation on private land across the state. The Trustês large 30,000 ha property near Mildura, Neds Corner Station, received a major boost with the Yulgilbar Foundation committing in 2015 to a three-year project supporting habitat restoration, including the scoping of fauna reintroductions. Support from the Helen Macpherson Smith Trust is contributing to landscape-scale plans and investment in the Habitat 141 area through the MATCH project. The R.E. Ross Trust continued to support Trust for Nature in a three-year project to investigate new sources of conservation finance and the Limb Family Foundation is funding stage 2 conservation project focusing on the Bay & Isalnds area of Victoria. The Trust's end-of-financial year appeal raised funds for the protection of threatened ecosystems, for example, the coastal and aquatic ecosystems such as salt marshes and mangroves.  Other activities included an 'eco-thinning' project supported by the Biophilia Foundation.  In the year, private Victorian landowners contributed an additional 1,706 ha of important natural habitat to Australiaês permanently protected estate, by registering covenants on their properties.

BLINDSIDE provides unique experiences for artists and their development, always striving to expand the sphere of artistic practice and empowering artists to see into fruition bold and spectacular ideas. We provide the opportunity for audiences to see the breadth of contemporary art practice from sculpture, drawing, painting and performance art, through to new media, video, sound, installation and craft. We take pride in supporting arts writers as well as artists. All of our exhibitions are supported with critical texts to contextualise the work. We are also committed to the role of education in the future of contemporary art practice and so we offer an extensive program of talks, workshops and forums for artists, the general public and visiting school groups. With an expanding program and strong organisational rigour, and after a decade of developing and presenting contemporary art practice within the city of Melbourne, we are committed to becoming more responsive and engaged with our audiences and community than ever before.BLINDSIDEês strategic direction is managed by a voluntary board of dedicated arts professionals.

LGBTI youth face higher rates of bullying due to homophobia and transphobia, which can lead to higher rates of depression, anxiety and suicide than non-LGBTI young people. Minus18 create safer space for LGBTI youth and to reduce the rates of homophobia and transphobia, and the subsequent mental health problems that can occur as a result of them.We engage in the national conversation of sexuality and gender identity, and provide a platform for those whose voice too often goes unheard.Social isolation due to location, homophobic and transphobic bullying can lead to mental health problems and lack of confidence. Minus18 combat social isolation through providing a place where young people feel they belong and are 100% safe and supported. Participation in Minus18 events fosters this sense of inclusion in a preventative model of mental health support.Our material is developed by young people, with the support of adult mentors. Weêre (mostly) pretty good at not coming off as daggy, and this makes a massive difference in our levels of inclusion.

Destiny Care provides Food support for disadvantaged people in the City of Kingston and surrounding suburbs.  Our food support includes Hampers for singles, couples and families, with ingredients to prepare nutritious meals for at least a couple of days, including fresh fruit and vegetables; fresh dairy, bread; frozen food; staple items such as rice and pasta; canned soups; cereals.  Our hampers are made up according to clientsê dietary and religious needs, as well as the size of their family.  We endeavour to vary the non-refrigerated components of our hampers on a fortnightly basis, so that our regular clients are able to access a varied diet.  Last year we assisted people from 47 different nations, and gave away over 2800 food hampers.  Each Wednesday we also provide a drop-in centre from 10am_3pm, supplying morning tea, and a free, cooked, 2 course lunch for those clients who wish to attend.  Here they receive a nutritious and tasty meal, as well as the chance to mix with each other, make friends and receive emotional support from our volunteers and/or each other.  From our interactions with our clients, we know that for some, this lunch provides the largest boost to their nutrition levels each week, due to the amount of vegetables we try to pack into each meal.

column39: Health professional education, Health promotion
column41: The National Asthma Council Australia is a collaboration of four member bodies:Australian Primary Health Care Nurses Association, Australasian Society of Clinical Immunology & Allergy, Pharmaceutical Society of Australia, and The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners.Our aim is to reduce the impacts of asthma _ health, social and economic. As a leading organisation for asthma, the NAC is the national authority for asthma knowledge and sets the standards for asthma care. We:- write the national treatment guidelines for asthma- educate and support health professionals to deliver best-practice asthma diagnosis and management- develop and disseminate evidence-based tools and resources for health professionals- promote best-practice care to people with asthma and their carers/family members- Identify products and services that may be better choices for people with asthma and allergies (through our Sensitive Choice program)- address the impacts of asthma through advocacy and collaboration with policy makers and stakeholders.The NAC has a patient-centred approach that is multidisciplinary and inclusive, relies on evidence-based information, promotes upskilling and capacity building, and takes into consideration practicality, cost-effectiveness and sustainability.We also have close ties with many other Australian and international organisations working in asthma and lung health.

Established in 2009 on the border of Indiaês most famous tiger reserve, this school was established in conjunction with an Indian NGO (GSK). We now support 120 students at this school, delivering a personalised curriculum that is reviewed daily and includes an excellent sports program to supplement the academic one. The students are drawn from 4 local villages, on land donated by a local farmer whose dream was to see his children at school rather than working in the fields.  Yatra actively support Sports programme with equipment in all four GSK schools. Recently seven children from these schools were selected for admission into a national sports academy, validating the importance of sport in our curriculm. We have regularly held medical and dental clinics at this school, reinforcing our desire to integrate personal and public health measures into our school environment, to maximize learning. The school is being rebuilt with architecturally designed spaces and classrooms, with the money raised by our 2015 Yatra bike tour in November, which rode to the school with the students and teachers. This school has now become a _modelî school for the region with numerous government schools now wishing to emulate our teaching methods. To this effect, we have now seconded several teachers to a local government school to empower the local teachers and leverage our influence on education in the area.Yatra Isha Vidhya School, Cuddlelore, Tamil NaduLocated in southern Tamil Nadu, nestled near the tsunami-prone shores of the Bay of Bengal, Yatra foundation provides Teacher salary and Teacher training to enable local children to attend this state-of-the-art facility in conjunction with Isha Vidhya foundation. These students benefit from excellent classrooms and computer facilities and learn in a full English-medium curriculum. These students receive a nutritious daily meal, cooked on-site in the school kitchen and are drawn from the numerous local fishing hamlets scattered along this picturesque coastal region. Yatra foundation provides teacher salary subsidies to recruit and retain the best available teachers. We also provide training to local rural teachers to enhance their classroom skills and again, leverage our effectiveness in reaching a larger number of needy childrenRecently, 150 local headmasters and young teachers from 50 regional schools attended a workshop at the Yatra Cuddlelore School to learn about teaching methods, evaluation, and resource allocation. We hope to continue these workshops on a regular basis so that these teaching methods and processes can be disseminated around southern Tamil Nadu. We are now seeing some extraordinary academic results especially in science and computing. The children at this school now have hope with a belief and confidence that they can dream and accomplish great outcomes. Many of our supporters have visited and marvelled at the level of education being delivered in this remote location. Please visit www.yatrafou

column39: Structured Playgroup
column41: Playgroup provides parents and carers quality time with their child, friendship and support, social stimulation and new experiences. At Playgroup children can develop physically, socially, emotionally and intellectually. They can have new experiences, make new friends, gain self-confidence and have fun. At our Playgroups children are aged from birth to five years. In these sessions the parent or carer participates in the activities. The Playgroups run on Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday mornings from 9.30-12pm and are guided by experienced Programme Leaders. We offer children a wide range of activities. These include free play in our outdoor area with a slide, cubby, swing, sandpit and outdoor toys. Inside we have a variety of gross motor skills equipment like tunnels, a slide and walk board. Many role playing opportunities are available too with dress ups, kitchen play and dolls being the most popular. We also have a reading corner, puzzles, games, and play dough. There are also always great planned art and craft activities.

column39: Connecting and supporting people with Acquired Brain Injuries and their families
column41: Heads Together Family Camp- This is a three day residential camping program for families, in Victoria, who have a child or young adult with an ABI. The camp provides a safe, welcoming and supportive environment where families can meet, connect and share experiences and become part of a community of people who understand.Outcomes: Held two camps, in Nov 2015 we had 23 families five of these were new to Heads Together and 47 volunteers, and May 2016 we had 22 families 3 of these were new to Heads Together and 45 volunteers. Heading Out Program- Monthly lunches which provide expanded social opportunities for young adults with an ABI. Our aim is to provide a safe and accepting environment in a mainstream community setting where young adults with an ABI can go out, make friends and build their independence and confidence with social situations. Outcomes: Hosted 10 monthly lunch events in 2015/16. There were an average of 12 participants per event with 28 total participants and 8 volunteers. We utilised Facebook as a means of promoting, connecting and coordinating events.ABILiTy-ABI Leadership Team received a grant from TAC in May 2015 and began recruiting a Program Coordinator to begin the 12 month pilot program. The peer consultants continued in their program development  role, and all acted as peer hosts for the Heading Out program, including one of them taking on the role of Heading Out Program Coordinator.

I CAN Network is a youth organisation that empowers young people on the autism spectrum to see autism in a positive light and to have a successful life with autism. We achieve this through running mentoring programs in schools and camps as well as delivering speaking engagements and professional development for teachers and school staff. In 2016, we delivered mentoring programs in 5 primary schools, 8 secondary schools, 2 communities and 1 university. We have run 2 camps for teenagers and 1 youth leadership camp. We delivered 28 speaking engagements as well as the Professional Development Conference for teachers and school staff.  The evaluation of our programs in 2016 demonstrates that we have made a positive impact on young people on the autism spectrum. In all our school mentoring and camp programs the most striking positive impact has been an increased sense of belonging amongst attendees and an increased self-belief in their strengths and abilities. Further as a result of our speaking engagements attendees have indicated that they have learned about autism and agree that how people think about autism needs to change.   These results highlight a positive step towards creating a world that benefits from embracing Autism.   http://ican.network/res/uploads/2016/12/I-CAN-Network-annual-report-15-16-DIGITAL.pdf

Many of the women housed have been victims of domestic violence, have been homeless, have very limited income, have experienced mental health episodes due to trauma experienced in their lives, may be recovering from drug and alcohol issues ‚VWHA is a not for profit company limited by Guarantee, with Public Benevolent Institution Status, and it is a registered Charity with Deductible Gift Recipient Status. VWHA is managed by a voluntary Board of Directors. The Board is comprised of women from the private, public, academic and community sectors who share the passion for improving the life choices for women and their families surviving on low incomes. ‚ The properties are exclusively for residential use and provide accommodation for disadvantaged women and their children. ‚VWHA charges no more than 30% of a womanês income in rent. ‚The increase in affordable rental housing stock for women is vital

column41: The purpose of the Victoria Law Foundation is to help Victorians understand the law.  Our community programs focus on breaking down the barriers to the legal system and empowering Victorians to access the law by improving their knowledge and level of engagement. Our community programs include providing high-quality legal information through the Everyday-Law website, and hosting a number of community events including Law Week, and the Law Orations. Our school-student programs reach out to Legal Studies students in rural, regional and disadvantaged schools, and includes Law Talks, Classroom Law Talks, and the provision of related resources.We offer training, and provide access to a range of resources to the legal profession on better ways to communicate the law to the general community.

The Foundation vision and mission to motivate and develop passionate leaders and learners and in doing so create transformational change in the primary education arena in Africa continues to drive our commitment to improve primary school literacy through the African Childrenês Stories program across many parts of Africa.This year the Foundation has expanded its presence into sixteen African countries. Formal launches of the latest African Childrenês Story Programs have taken place in Kigali (Rwanda), Nairobi, (Kenya) and Bishoftu (Ethiopia), Port Louis, (Mauritius) and Zandspruit, (South Africa). These launches provide a focus for the children, their teachers and the entire community. In each case, the culture of dance, music and African togetherness umoja is featured. It is a reminder of the importance of story in the lives of each respective community but also the opportunity to distribute many of the other country collections into classrooms and libraries. The Executive Director has visited most projects across 13 of the 16 African countries this year, an opportunity to build relationship and trust, oversee the development-based program, confirm and expand partnerships and train educators to assume a system wide approach. These visits occur twice yearly and are vital to our ongoing practice.

Engaging and empowering other organisations and individuals to provide benevolent relief is fundamental to the purpose and implicit of our philosophy of Partnering for Transformation. These are the words that stand behind our name P4T. We are a small core group but have highly developed skills sets and networks which we leverage to the benefit of the broader community. Our largest project is the Pingpongathon,  which engages people to volunteer to play table tennis in their local community as a means of raising both awareness and  funds for the cause of eliminating human trafficking and sexual exploitation of young people. In 2016 we have partnered with 60 community groups across Australia (churches, high schools, sporting groups, and even a hotel), who connected with their local community inviting individuals to participate and fundraise. In the process, P4T provides educational material to raise awareness of the existence of the problem of human trafficking and also challenges the attitudes of participants about respect for individual rights. This aspect is also aimed at reducing the incidence of domestic violence in the community. Local participating community groups encourage their participants to register and fundraise through the Pingpongathon website and online fundraising system. Funds raised through the pingpongathon project are distributed to partner organisations that provide on the ground benevolent assistance to the victims of human trafficking. We also ran forums where we brought thought leaders together to discuss ways in which individuals and communities can be more effective in seeing people flourish in their daily lives.

Aged and Community Services Australia (ACSA) exists to represent and be the voice of not-for-profit and faith-based providers of residential and community aged care and housing. We do this by undertaking policy development and advocacy in public and political arenas. The following ACSA activities meet these goals and purposes: ‚ ACSA engages professional researchers to investigate issues that affect the aged care sector now and into the future. In the past year, these issues have included the aged care workforce, housing for older Australians and care provision in regional, rural and remote areas of Australia. ‚ These research papers are then further developed through the National Advisory Committees and the annual National Policy Papers. ACSAês policy staff then develop these ´high levelê research papers into position papers and issues papers which are used to represent the views of not-for-profit providers to government ministers, members of parliament and Senators and government departments through formal meetings and submissions.‚ The Advisory Committees also raise sectorê concerns which ACSA then relays to government departments through written correspondence and face to face meetings.‚ ACSA staff and members represent the organisation on numerous government and industry related committees, putting forward the needs of not-for-profit and faith providers.  These forums play a key role in the development of policy at a national level and ACSAês involvement ensures that it is at the forefront of this process.‚ ACSAês Chief Executive and Media Relations and Communications Manager represent and advocate for not-for-profit aged care providers in industry and mainstream media by responding to interviews from journalists and by writing opinion pieces representing the views and policy positions held by members.‚ ACSAês annual national conference provides an opportunity for not-for-profit and faith-based providers to develop their voice by hearing from Australian and international experts, providing a platform for them to share their own learnings and successes and giving members an opportunity to hear from and engage directly with senior members of the government and opposition.‚  ACSA produces a quarterly publication called Agendas which promotes the sectors views internally and to government and consumers. The publication provides insights into key reforms and outlines the views of members to its diverse audience.ACSA coordinates an annual National Open Home Day throughout Australia, in conjunction with partner organisations in the UK, South Africa and Malta. These open days support not-for-profit and faith-based providers to promote the good work that they do through the media and direct engagement with the public. Without the coordination and oversight of ACSA, these open days would not be possible.

In the relatively short period since our official launch, The Animal Law Institute (ALI) has been busy:  1) Giving hundreds of hours of free legal adviceVia our band of volunteer solicitors and law students, we have strengthened the animal protection movement by giving hundreds of hours of free legal advice to numerous animal advocates and not-for-profit organisations. ALI's key focus is on matters that involve a broader public interest element and are of strategic importance to enhancing legal protection for animals. No matter the issue, clients can be confident that we will always give thoroughly-researched, clear and impartial advice. 2) Lobbying GovernmentALI works to challenge the way our legal system treats animals through effective advocacy. We have lobbied government on a range of matters to ensure animals are better protected under our laws and regulations. Our Policy Team has drafted and submitted a significant number of submissions on matters such as egg labeling, the greyhound racing industry, intensive farming and proposed ´ag-gagê legislation, as well as, more recently, a submission to the Productivity Commissionês inquiry into the regulation of agriculture. Notably, our submission in relation to the proposed ´ag-gagê legislation, the Criminal Code Amendment (Animal Protection) Bill 2015, was quoted a number of times throughout the Senate Rural and Regional Affairs and Transport Legislation Committeeês Report on the legislation. 3) Educating the legal profession and public ALI contributes to the education of the legal profession and the wider public on animal law matters as we believe that generating awareness is a key to creating law change.We successfully ran the Australia New Zealand Intervarsity Moot on Animal Law (ANIMAL) in 2014 and 2015, and preparations are currently underway for the third moot in September 2016. ANIMAL is the first and only national animal law moot in Australia and New Zealand. ANIMAL has grown from 14 teams in 2014 to 18 teams in 2015, making it one of Australiaês best-attended law moot competitions nationally. In 2015, ALI ran a very successful Animal Law Breakfast on the topic Dolphins and the Law - how to use strategic litigation to achieve a political outcome, presented by Australia For Dolphins. The presentation was both informative and inspiring, demonstrating how an alternative approach to animal welfare advocacy can achieve a successful outcome for animals.In 2016, we held the inaugural Animal Law Week, a week of presentations across the country delivered by an impressive lineup of people working at the forefront of animal protection in Australia and overseas. Topics ranged from puppy farming and animal law prosecution, protected species, the prosecution of animal crimes in the US and a day in the life of an animal lawyer.

Each year in Australia: 5,500 people die from alcohol related injuries, illness and accidents. 157,000 people are hospitalised due to alcohol. More people die from drug overdosesÜincluding from pharmaceuticalsÜthan die on the roads. The cost to the community from alcohol-related harm is estimated to exceed $15.3 billion. For illegal drugs it exceeds $8.2 billion.Research shows that creating connected communities is the key to preventing alcohol and drug problems. In these communities people feel valued, supported and purposeful.We design and deliver a range of community programs, services and resources targeted at preventing alcohol and other drug-related harm. We know that healthy and resilient communities are the best way to prevent substance use problems. Our programs work to prevent harm in specific environments, changing practices and attitudes to create safer places for people to live, work and play.Our Good Sports program is the first program of its kind to be proven successful in the world _ so we know it works. There are currently over 7,000 clubs involved in the Good Sports Program, making it Australiaês largest sport-based health initiative. Participation in the program has been shown to greatly reduce the odds of risky drinking in clubs. Good Sports clubs are 42% less likely to experience alcohol-related harms in clubs. In NSW, we have a program where the community has a real opportunity to make a difference in their local area through joining a Community Drug Action Team to take action to prevent Alcohol and Drug related harm. In collaboration with NSW Health and local agencies, we have produced a suite of resources that will help educate communities about crystalline methamphetamine (´iceê).

column39: SecondBite exists to provide access to fresh, nutritious food for people in need across Australia. We do this by rescuing and redistributing surplus fresh food, building community capacity in food skills and nutrition and advocating for an end to food insecurity.
column41: SecondBite exists to provide access to fresh, nutritious food for people in need across Australia. We do this by rescuing and redistributing surplus fresh food, building community capacity in food skills and nutrition and advocating for an end to food insecurity. In the 2016 financial year, SecondBite rescued and redistributed 10 million kg of fresh nutritious food, enough to provide 20 million healthy meals to people in need.  This was a 48% increase over 2015.  Founded in 2005, we now supply over 1100 community food programs with food, supporting people who are homeless, women and families in crisis, youth at risk, indigenous communities, long-term unemployed, people with disabilities, asylum seekers and new arrivals.

Conscious Creative Limited orchestrated and executed three main activities over the 2015/16 financial year to achieve its charitable purposes: 1) The HoMie Street Store The HoMie Street Store is a charity retail store that opened in Melbourne Central Shopping Centre on June 30th 2015, and then on Brunswick Street, Fitzroy, on June 27th 2016. HoMie clothes, trains and employs people who are experiencing homelessness in Melbourne. Clothing is distributed to the homeless community during monthly VIP Shopping Days in HoMie, where people who are homeless are invited to shop for free as ´VIP Customersê. On VIP Shopping Days, HoMie VIPs not only receive five complementary items of brand-new clothing and dignified shopping experience, but also receive free nutritious food, coffee and haircuts. VIP Shopping Days aim to increase feelings of social connectedness and bring our clients into contact with the HoMie Support Network. Alongside VIP Shopping Days, HoMie trains and employs young homeless Melbournians as retail workers. Through the training program, HoMie aims to provide a genuine pathway out of homelessness through the provision of confidence, skills and jobs.During the 2015/16 financial year, HoMie hosted eight (8) VIP Shopping Days for the homeless community, brought 217 homeless Melbournians into its support network, and distributed 1,085 items of brand new clothing to the homeless community. The HoMie Retail Training & Employment Program began in November 2015 and, although it is not currently an accredited course, has already assisted three (3) young homeless Melbournians. These young people worked a total of 251 hours with HoMie during the 2015/16 financial year, for which they received $5,975.00 in wages. In partnership with the Ladder Foundation, Knowledge Space, Cotton On and Bendigo Bank, HoMie is in the process of designing an accredited Retail Training & Employment Program, to be piloted throughout 2016-17. The Retail Training & Employment Program will see four (4) homeless Melbournians housed, trained as retail workers, and employed by the Cotton On retail chain upon successful graduation next year.2) Charity Tap: Charity Tap is a fundraising system that enables Australian hospitality businesses to fundraise effortlessly for charity. During the 2015/16 financial year, Charity Tap raised $13,333.10, of which 85% was pledged to Oxfam, the Melbourne Period Project, Kids Under Cover and the Self Help Addiction Resource Centre. 15% of funds raised by Charity Tap were used to cover its running costs. 3) Homelessness in Melbourne advocacy:   ´Homelessess in Melbourneê is a social media advocacy program which shares the stories of people who are currently (or have previously) experienced homelessness, to raise awareness of this global issue. Conversations shared through this platform offer an insight into each individual and their circumstance, regularly reaching an organic audience of over 250,000 people per post.

column41: The Principal Purpose of the AYCC is to protect Australiaês natural environment from climate change by educating young Australians to build a generation-wide movement of young people committed to taking action to reduce carbon pollution in their homes, schools TAFEs, Universities and communities. SEED: In FY2016 Seed, a branch of the AYCC and Australiaês first indigenous youth climate network continued to grow with volunteer groups extending across the country to bring our educational and leadership programs to a wider demographic of young people, giving opportunities to young people often missed by youth development programs. In FY16 we held a national youth Indigenous conference where 80 Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander young people from every corner of the country came together on Gadigal country in Sydney for a transformational summit. The four day summit included skills workshops, regional planning sessions, opportunities to share stories and knowledge, a sustainability project launch and a media action. SEED participants then engaged in sustainability projects in their communities to protect land, educate their peers and reduce pollution in their hometowns.Switched on Schools: Switched on Schools is AYCCês high school program that has been running for four years across Australia. In FY16 we delivered 11 summits, engaging around 1200 students. Summits are two-day events where high school students and teachers come together to learn about climate change, sustainability and how to create change in their schools and local communities. At these summits students start sustainability projects such as reducing paper waste, planting vegetable gardens and trees, and putting solar panels on the roof, that they then take back and develop at their schools.AYCC volunteers also delivered in school workshops to 130 schools and reached a further 20,000 students through presentations and online engagement platforms. The schools project has also worked with students from 390 schools through our Student Climate Action Network where students continue their engagement in their sustainability projects and create networks with students from other schools. Training: In FY16 AYCC empowered 450 young people through a combination of national, state and regional training camps, equipping young leaders with the skills, networks and information they need to lead sustainability projects and campaigns in their communities to protect the natural environment from climate change.  In FY16 AYCC also continued the Climate Leaders Training Program, an intensive 9-month training program which brought together 80 young leaders from around the country for 3 intensive 4-day training retreats, where they built networks and gained the skills and confidence they need to help solve climate change. In between these training retreats, participants applied their knowledge and skills to the movement by committing to 8 hours of volunteer work each week.

column2: Victorian Aboriginal Community Controlled Health Organistation Inc
column41: VACCHO is the peak body for Aboriginal health in Victoria representing 30 ACCOs. VACCHOês Members serve as an advocate for their community and in turn, VACCHO serves as an advocate for its Members, championing Aboriginal identity as an inseparable aspect of a comprehensive healthcare system.  VACCHO recognises the importance of education and pre-emption in effective healthcare implementation and exists to enable our Members to instil healthy attitudes and beliefs throughout their community.  This approach helps negate the many complex health issues causing a decline in the wellbeing of Aboriginal peoples by preventing serious illness.  Our determination to close the gap between the health equalities of Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal peoples is the driving force behind our approach.  An important factor in the success of this outcome is our holistic approach to health that ensures that administered care is representative of Aboriginal culture.  When healthcare is culturally safe the treatment is far more effective.  Achieving mainstream recognition of this correlation is integral to securing the funding that will demonstrate the long term effectiveness of culturally appropriate healthcare.   VACCHO strikes to convey that sickness does not only affect the physicality of Aboriginal peoples.  When Aboriginal culture is dismissed it can cause damage to our social, emotional and spiritual wellbeing.   Spirituality and physicality are inseparable in Aboriginal culture; that which affects one affects the other just as acutely.  Unfortunately, spiritual healing can be difficult due to the general incompatibility of mainstream health services and Aboriginal culture.  VACCHO recognises the importance of spiritual healing and its importance in improving health outcomes for Aboriginal people.  By allowing Aboriginal culture to thrive, so too will its people.   VACCHO advocates for Aboriginal health on two fronts: treating the physical illnesses affecting Aboriginal health and celebrating Aboriginal culture in a vibrant community.  ´In respect to the goals and principles of community control within the Victorian Aboriginal health sector, it is essential to ensure that the services VACCHO provides meet the needs of its Members, stakeholders and ultimately the community which it servesê.  VACCHOês leadership role involves building the capacity for community advocacy and workforce development by strengthening the support network of our Members.  This advocacy takes place in a range of private, community and Government agencies at a state and national level, recognising all issues relevant to Aboriginal health.  VACCHO represents the community controlled health sector nationally through its membership on the board of the National Aboriginal Community Controlled Health Organisation (NACCHO).  The Victorian Aboriginal Community, State and Federal Governments formally recognise VACCHO as the peak representative organisation for Aboriginal health in Victoria.

Over the past year Inclusion Melbourne has continued to implement our strategic plan, which is focused on four key areas: preparing for the National Disability Insurance Scheme; improving our organisational performance; promoting good practices and research that supports and enhances the lives of people with intellectual disability; and building the capabilities of the volunteers and staff.This work continues, and over the past year we are pleased that we have reached out to all off the people we support and their families to provide information on the NDIS and when it will be implemented in their local area. Further, we have hosted over two-dozen workshops for families in understanding and preparing for the NDIS. We are pleased that through this process of supporting families to imagine better lives, and of undertaking detailed pre-planning, they have been able to accurately articulate their needs as individuals and as a family. It is intended that in line with the aspirations of the NDIS that these people will begin to receive reasonable and necessary supports based off this work, and at the time of writing the first people we support and their families have been able to secure plans that for the first time recognise their global needs.We have also launched Inclusion Designlab and Inclusion Training. Together with our core business of supporting people to imagine better lives and developing lives of distinction within the local community, these new arms will support and learn from our sixty-five years of dreaming of better lives for people. The role of Inclusion Designlab is to pursue answers to the questions raised by the hundred people we support and their families and carers. Questions such as ´How do I vote?ê or ´Where do I go to get help for my teeth?ê or êHow can I participate on my local councilês Disability Advisory Committee?ê Through partnering with philanthropic foundation we can commit the time and effort to develop resources and training that not only benefit the people we support, but also other people with intellectual disability and their families and carers. Evidence of our work is beginning to mount, with materials developed by the Designlab being sold and adapted for use in Western Australia and Queensland. Likewise, electing to use the name Inclusion Training for the delivery of nationally accredited training as a Registered Training Organisation very clearly states our intentions to provide people with intellectual disability with every opportunity to become valued members of their community. Over time, both services will grow and broaden their reach.

column41: WISE Employment Ltd (WISE) a not for profit employment service provider is achieving its charitable purpose by providing employment, training, mental health and rehabilitation services to unemployed people with disabilities and other disadvantages.Many of our customers present at our services with multiple barriers to employment and social inclusion. Barriers include early disengagement from education, intergenerational unemployment, low levels of literacy and numeracy, language issues, poor work history or no work history, gambling, debt issues, institutionalisation, high risk antisocial behaviours, carer or parental responsibilities, justice issues and poor physical and mental health issues.A majority of WISEês customers are considered priority needs groups including; People with disability, Ex-offenders, Youth, Culturally and Linguistically Diverse people, Indigenous peoples, Refugees, Comorbid, Mental Health, Injecting drug users, and those experiencing Homelessness. WISEês strength is in delivering flexible tailored support consisting of vocational and non vocational activities endowing customers with life skills, work ready skills, strategies and confidence to overcome their challenges and barriers, as a means for achieving positive outcomes in education, training employment and personal well being.WISE currently delivers Disability Employment Services and jobactive  in more than 50 sites/communities across NSW, Victoria, South Australia, Tasmania and the Northern Territory. WISE also provides specialist employment services for ex-offenders in Darwin and Alice Springs (for the NT Corrections Department) and recently commenced the ParentsNext program in Burnie (Tasmania) for parents of young children. Through these services, WISE empowers disadvantaged customers to transition into competitive employment, while simultaneously helping employers to find the right staff to meet their needs. This is underpinned by WISEês belief that paid employment presents the best way out of poverty and leads to improved wellbeing, self-sufficiency and community engagement. In addition, WISE assists people with mental illness through the Personal Helpers & Mentors program (PHaMS) (southeast Melbourne) and Partners in Recovery (southeast Melbourne & western Sydney). PHaMs provides practical and holistic support to people with severe functional limitations as a result of mental illness and through PIR, WISE facilitates customerês access to clinical and other service and support needs. WISE is a National Disability Insurance Service provider in Tasmania for youth 15-24 years old, providing assistance to gain and maintain employment as well as personal supports.Through WISEês enduring vision of _enriching the community - empowerment through employmentî these services supported over 35,000 customers during the 2015-2016 financial year. column41: The Harold Mitchell Foundation Fund works with organisations that want to make a difference in Australia and the region. The Fund is increasingly focused on four key areas: health, with a focus on mental health and disadvantage, as well as medical research; education, with a focus on building the next generation of Australian leaders; arts, with a focus on big ideas that place Australia on the world map; and our region, with a focus on Australiaês leadership role. The Mitchell Institute is one of the Fundês ongoing projects, a venture in partnership with Victoria University, dedicated to tackling health and education policy issues affecting Australia. The Mitchell Institute aims to transform educational and health outcomes for people in our community by identifying the critical health and education issues in Australia that would benefit from deep enquiry, robust research, and vigorous debate to positively influence public policy and ultimately, the lives of people in our community. The Institute's focus is on socially and economically disadvantaged communities and the transformational change effective education and good health can deliver. Another of the Fundês key ongoing projects include the health travel fellowships, which enable promising young medical scientists to travel overseas to participate in seminal conferences, and receive mentoring and support from leading medical specialists. They will bring this experience back to Australia to begin a lifetime of collaboration.

column2: Friends Of The Earth Melbourne Inc
column41: Helped secure a state renewable energy target in Victoria (a VRET) of 25% renewable energy by 2020 and 40% by 2025. It is expected to double wind energy capacity in the state by 2020 and triple renewable energy capacity by 2025, creating 10,000 jobs and unlocking a $2.5 billion investment opportunity in the process. It is expected to cut carbon emissions in the state by around 15%.We helped sustain the moratorium on onshore gas drilling in the state of Victoria. Climate science makes it clear that the time for new fossil fuel production is over if we want to protect the natural environment, and additionally, methane pollution through fugitive emissions is increasingly of concern to climate scientists. We were heavily involved in the state governments Inquiry into the onshore unconventional gas industry. During 2015/16 we increased the work we do around the issue of ´energy shiftingê (moving from reliance on gas to electricity from green power sources), including commissioning a major report on the topic. We also worked to develop a clear plan for economic diversification in the Latrobe Valley.We helped establish the Victorian Roadside Vegetation Network, to highlight the vital ecological role of roadways, especially in largely cleared rural areas. We engaged with land managers and government bodies to ensure minimal impacts occur around major road widening operations, and helped secure the protection of several hundred very old Red Gum trees in a number of locations.We carried out research work into the population of the Strzelecki Koala (a genetically significant sub species) through scat surveys in the Strzelecki Ranges, to the south east of Melbourne. This research substantially filled gaps in knowledge about the species distribution and eating and other habits. During this time a new sub species of eucalyptus was identified for the first time. Surveyed in bluegum plantations in western VIC to identify koala numbers and the impacts of clearing operations. We carried out research into the ecological benefits of Indigenous Protected Areas. We worked locally to gain better management and funding for the Nyah-Vinifera Park, on the mid Murray River in northern VIC.  We researched the likely impacts (and subsequently opposed) planned ´ecological thinning trialsê on public land in both VIC and NSW. We organised a series of ´citizen scienceê workshops in forests on public land in East Gippsland (VIC) to identify distribution of a range of endangered plant and animal species.After more than 20 years of work to gain protection of key ecosystems in the Strezlecki Ranges, south east of Melbourne, the state government has announced the first formal transfer of land into the Strezlecki Cores and Links Reserve. This will form the basis of a reserve system which will protect the best of the remaining cool temperate rainforest and tall eucalypt forests in these ranges

column41: Principle activities and purpose of the company.  Rare Voices Australia (RVA) is an active charity committed to achieving our long term and short term goals. Established in 2012, Rare Voices Australia is a national, non-profit organisation with a vision to be ´the unified voice for all Australians living with a rare disease. RVA aims to collaborate and connect all Australians living with a rare disease; advocate for a national rare disease strategy; raise awareness of rare disease issues; and educate policy and decision makers. RVA Newsletter RVA publishes a Monthly E-newsletter which is sent to all our members and followers. In each newsletter RVA features a patient story from one of the RVA associated patient associations. In 2016 Speak Percussion delivered on a key strategic goal, to present work of significant scale, impact and of the highest artistic standards. As a major voice in the Australian art music scene this goal is truly commensurate with the organisationês international standing.Highlights included a collaboration with Ilan Volkov in his Adelaide Festival Tectonics which, amongst the other world premieres, included a piece with The Necks and the Adelaide Symphony Orchestra, Anicca and Bell Curve at Arts House and a return to Indonesia with two projects for the Salihara International Performing Arts Festival (SIPFest).Creatively the organisation integrated emerging and experimental technologies including the development of new hardware and software for 12 networked wireless click tracks, a rotary encoder tracking the movement of percussion instruments on a spinning table with light, tactile transducers and the development of ice percussion instruments.New partnerships were formed with entities such as Unconformity Festival, Hotel Hotel, Assemble Papers and RMITês Industrial Design Department. Importantly strong existing relationships were cemented including with MPavilion, Arts House, The Substation and the SIPFest.The successes of the year came in many forms, further to three Green Room Award nominations was winning the Art Music Award for Excellence in Experimental Music and a 4.5 star rating from Limelight for our Fluorophone season at The Substation.Another key artistic goal for Speak Percussion has been to make work which will endure and sustain meaning beyond the occasion of its premiere. This goal, as before, depends on quality, impact and scale but is importantly also linked to depth of practice, ownership and securing subsequent performances. I am also extremely heartened that many of the successes of 2016 continue to resonate in 2017, projects which premiered in 2016 including Bell Curve, Fluorophone, The Trading Routes, Brutti ma Buoni and Fault Traces have had confirmed repeat presentations in 2017. This is a testament to the strength of the work and artistic vibrancy of the organisation.Speak Percussionês artistic achievements were matched by significant organisational milestones and financial successes. These included:‚ Triennial funding _ 4 streams at three levels of government‚ Confirmation of 4 year funding from the Australia Council for the Arts (with 89% increase) and Creative Victoria (with 5% increase)‚ 15% increase in net assets‚ Bespoke program launched  ‚ Awards _ including Art Music Award for Excellence in Experimental Music for Speak Percussion and Emerging Melbourne Prize for Music for Matthias Schack-Arnott

Asylum seekers and migrants are the second largest group of clients.

Mayflower's purpose is to provide care without compromise through responsive and innovative aged care services and independent seniors living options that enhance independence, wellbeing and lifestyle.  We achieve this through our accredited residential aged care services at Mayflower Reservoir by providing holistic care options that suit the needs of residents, and their families, in relation to individual medical, physical, social, spiritual and emotional support.  At Mayflower we consult with every new resident and their family representative to develop an individually tailored Care Plan that meets the needs and wishes of that resident. This Care Plan is monitored and reviewed on a regular basis to ensure that Mayflower responds to any changes in health status or requirements.  Mayflower's focus on person-centred care is also reflected in our qualified nursing staff, who monitor and manage the health and wellbeing of our residents 24 hours a day.  In conjunction the personal care staff provides services including assistance with dressing, bathing, meals and other activities of daily living. Specialised services include dementia and palliative care plus we have respite places.  Each and every day our staff and volunteers continue to provide a range of social and physical activities as part of our buoyant resident lifestyle programs. These activities support the cultural and spiritual wishes of the residents.  Events such as concerts, outings, topical and celebratory functions are a frequent occurrence.

The need for Certificate IV and Diploma qualifications that specifically focus on Christian coaching arises from the needs of changed ministry perspectives and environments, and fluid leadership expectations as churches need to discover new ways of connecting within their own communities and the wider society.  A quality coaching program which develops skilled coaches within Christian organisations dynamically enhances the development and uniqueness of such organisations from within.   Rather than relying on external direction, where standards, consistency and capability may vary, organisations are learning to become _learning communitiesî where social engagement, spiritual development and communal involvement are explored and discovered in the local context.  The trend across many Christian organisations is to focus on the _leader as coachî approach in order to develop and equip emerging leaders in a constantly changing environment.  This trend also ensures a consistency of the organisationês intent, expressed in its culture and leadership programs. In addition, Christian leaders are finding they require much more than spiritual and theological formation; they increasingly recognise the need to lead change, develop leaders and connect socially and professionally with the wider community.  These strategic leadership skills are developed through these coaching qualifications. http://www.christiancoachinginstitute.com.au/blog/it-s-been-a-great-year  - Annual Report

column41: DKD's activities through the year involved raising money (via BBQ's, Auctions) to help cover costs of raising puppies and training dogs to become assistance dogs or companion dogs to a child with a disability. Our assistance dogs are trained to help their families access their local community by walking tethered beside their child preventing them from absconding or wandering off.  They help to reduce the intensity and frequency of melt downs, lowered anxiety and helps to build communication pathways for the children they are allocated to.  Our companion dogs play the role of confidante and best friend to their child, teaching them important empathy and friendship skills, helping them to feel connected to their family and the local community.  The placement of these dogs has helped us achieve our charitable purpose of improving the quality of life of children with a disability by placing trained companion or assistance dogs with the successful families

Environmental Justice Australia (formerly the Environment Defenders Office, Victoria) is a not-for-profit public interest legal practice. We use the law to protect our environment, and we work to change our laws to make sure they protect our rights to clean air, clean water and healthy ecosystems. Funded by donations and independent of Commonwealth government and corporate funding, our legal team combines a passion for justice with technical expertise and a practical understanding of the legal system to protect our environment. We act as advisers and legal representatives to the environment movement, pursuing court cases to protect our shared environment. We work with community-based environment groups, regional and state environmental organisations, and larger environmental NGOs. We also provide strategic and legal support to their campaigns to address climate change, protect nature and defend the rights of communities to a healthy environment. While we seek to give the community a powerful voice in court, we also recognise that court cases alone will not be enough. Thatês why we campaign to improve our legal system. We defend existing, hard-won environmental protections from attack. At the same time, we pursue new and innovative solutions to fill the gaps and fix the failures in our legal system to clear a path for a more just and sustainable world. We are always happy to discuss our work with existing and potential supporters. You can get in touch with us via our website www.envirojustice.org.au

WSA operates in Australia, New Zealand, the Pacific, China, South East Asia and India. In each region WSA is aiming to build relationships and collaboration with local companies, civil society organisations and government agencies; to facilitate projects that can demonstrate the successful and beneficial implementation of water stewardship; to build capacity of local organisations as promoters of water stewardship or as accredited service providers (auditors, consultants and trainers), and; to build local governance networks and bodies that can provide local leadership for the water stewardship system.  In most of these regions WSA acts as the regional partner organisation of the Alliance for Water Stewardship (AWS) although in India it acts in collaboration with AWS. Highlights of this year have been:‚ Progress of five projects to the point where sites have registered for certification or self-verification with the AWS International Water Stewardship Standard‚ Signing of an MOU with TEDA Eco-Centre, a leading advisory body for industrial parks in China‚ Second Asia-Pacific Water Stewardship Forum in collaboration with AWS and the India Water Stewardship Network‚ New demonstration project in Papua New Guinea and potential new projects in Greater Mekong region‚ First collaboration with traditional owners in the Kimberley  (WA)‚ Western Port project working with 15 water stewards and gains international recognition.Led by partner organisation Western Port Biosphere Reserve, and funded by the Helen Macpherson Smith Trust, the Western Port Water Stewardship Project is currently working with 15 water stewards with some already preparing for certification.  The project is looking to deepen its engagement with existing participants before expanding into new catchments within the Western Port Biosphere.  The project is a great example of collaboration between WSA and local groups who are interested in leading implementation of water stewardship in their community.

column2: Council For The Humanities Arts And Social Sciences
column41: The Council for the Humanities, Arts and Social Sciences (CHASS) exists to raise awareness of humanities, arts and social sciences (HASS) and their critical role in building the societies of the future. Through its membership of over 75 organisations, CHASS advocates for HASS learning and practice in the wider community and amongst decision makers. CHASS has an estimated reach of over 50,000 individuals through its member and affiliate networks. Throughout our history, we have sought to shape reform and positive change both drawing upon and gaining recognition for the strengths of the sector. This has included influential publications, including ´Humanities, Arts and Social Sciences: Itês everyoneês businessê published by Routledge in 2016, and our events, including the flagship ´HASS on the Hillê and more recently the annual CHASS National Forum fostering high-level interactions between CHASS members, parliamentarians, public intellectuals and thought-leaders. Our work has also opened new areas of engagement for HASS in government priorities such as science engagement and social policy arenas. Our annual CHASS Australia Prizes are designed to honour distinguished achievements by Australians working, studying or training in the HASS areas, including academics, practitioners, philanthropists, policy makers and students. In 2016, we received 230 nominations across the four categories, our highest haul since the Prizes were established in 2014. In 2015-16, we continued to strengthen engagement with our membership base through our robust communications strategy and events calendar. Tools of engagement included our improved daily media monitoring update (free service for members), monthly e-newsletter, revamped website, and active social media communication (Twitter and Facebook). Our President's Report for FY 2015-16 (presented at the 2016 AGM) is available here: http://www.chass.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/13th-CHASS-AGM-2016_Presidents-Report.pdf

Community Housing (Vic) Limited (CHVL) is involved in developing housing solutions for good quality affordable rental housing for those in need and/or assisting those who are disadvantaged by market failure in securing a pathway to home ownership. The charity is dedicated on developing viable accommodation options for those experiencing housing difficulty. The charity is committed to its object for providing shelter to persons in crisis and who have inadequate access to safe and secure housing. CHVL also provided housing advice and referral services, which may assist homeless persons to stable and long term housing. CHVL has always worked in partnership with national and state government authorities, social support agencies and local community groups to address local housing affordability problems. Thus CHVL has pursued its charitable objects by providing good quality affordable rental housing for people who are in need.

Indigenous field workers, social workers and leaders are trained to have a holistic approach by providing social development programs that meet spiritual and practical needs. Community transformation, compassion for the poor and needy, and justice for all takes place through:Education Centres and Schools Literacy and numeracy programs for disadvantaged children are essential to break the cycle of illiteracy, poverty and despair. Education and care for marginalized and vulnerable children is facilitated through fee-paying students. The schools range from kindergarten to equivalent Year 10. Vocational Skills Training Program Empartês vocational skill training is presently centred on the ´Sew & Sowê Project. The program provides a 6-month diploma course where poor women are taught to make traditional Indian clothes as well as embroidery and soft toys. At the end of the course, each woman is presented with a treadle or hand operated sewing machine (locally made) at a graduation service. With the ability to generate an income, these women gain dignity and status in the community, along with the security of knowing that they can provide nourishing food, a good education and health care for their children. Vocational skills training is being extended into new areas such as candle making and sanitary napkin manufacture. Mercy Homes Empart continues to care for the most down trodden of society, homeless people with a mental illness. 4 Mercy Homes care for permanent sufferers and a specially equipped vehicle provides meals, hygiene and support to those still living on the streets. Medical Care Empart also delivers medical care to areas where field workers are based as part of its holistic approach to ministry. Medical care is effectively provided through Mobile Medical Camps where basic health care ios provided through: preventative care, professional consultation, early diagnosis and treatment, free medication and ongoing health education.Aid &Relief includes both emergency relief as well as assistance to the poor. Empart provides circumstantial, emergency relief as required in natural disaster.  We also provide practical and economic assistance to the poor, to help them achieve a better future. Local field workers identify needs and suitable projects among their local community. Recent projects included blankets in winter, mosquito nets and flood recovery.

column39: The provision of education and legal assistance to promote, protect, and advance across the world, the human rights of children.
column41: CRI's main project is the creation of a child friendly court in Cambodia. Currently, children in Cambodia are processed through adult courts and end up in adult prisons without being provided a fair trial. CRI is working with UNICEF and Legal Aid Cambodia in Cambodia to teach Cambodian judges, lawyers and legal aid workers about children's rights and obligations. During the year, CRI worked with both UNICEF and AusAid in relation to this project by assisting in designing a child friendly court model (based on the foundations of the children's court in Australia). This has been a significant first step in Cambodia supporting the rights of children.

EVENTS: We held 25 events over this year including a two-day conference, with the theme of Collective Impact and Communication, and enjoyed the experiences and wisdom of four international expert speakers.  Highlights included hosting Jenny Curtis of the Garfield Foundation and Robert Tanner of Climate Nexus in the US, being moved and inspired by Stephen Heintz of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund and learning about yet another implication of climate change, this time for defence, from UK Rear Admiral Neil Morisetti.  Events this year covered the topics of climate change, biodiversity and inland waterways, sustainable food systems, divestment and impact investing.  On the 1 June we will hold our 2016 conference.ENVIRONMENTAL EXPERTISE:The AEGN continues to foster excellent relationships with experts in the fields of environment, economics and science,  for example Robert Tanner, climate change communications; Justin Maxson, Just Transitions; Mark Norman, biodiversity; Chris Ryan, food systems and urban sustainability; Peter Cosier, environmental policy and Dr Barry Traill, ecologist and change.NEWSLETTER & WEBSITE:We have produced seven newsletters and have introduced monthly Member Updates to provide members with the latest news, events and projects for funding.  The AEGN Blog is live and refreshed frequently to provide timely commentary on environmental philanthropy by AEGN members and partners. ENVIRONMENTAL NON-GOVERNMENT ORGANISATION (ENGO) INITIATIVES: We continued to expand the Directory of Environmental Organisations.  This searchable web directory now contains 1944 organisations and a more comprehensive list of both Sustainable Agriculture & Food Systems and Indigenous Land Management organisations. We commenced a project to identify how best to support capacity building for environmental organisations.   GIVING GREEN: The Climate Change & Energy (CCE) funder group includes 42 individuals who this year worked together to encourage growth in philanthropic funding to this important issue, and to direct funding more strategically. CCE members collaborated on initiatives to improve climate change communications. In February, we held our first truly national video linked meeting, with participation from members in three states and will use this successful approach again. The Sustainable Agriculture & Food Systems (SAFS) funder group has 49 SAFS members and has focused on the Ripe for Change initiative - an innovative approach to build philanthropic support for food systems work, using the principles of collective impact. The AEGN commissioned the Australian Futures Project to research and facilitate a process to develop a map of the Victorian food system, involving funders and others. During the year we launched a new Nature funder group and agreed to form an Environmental Impacting Investing funder group as a result of member demand.  We are also running a trial project to support increased funding to the Indigenous land and sea

Birth for HumanKINDês purpose is to relieve the distress of disadvantaged women during the often-vulnerable period of pregnancy, childbirth and the immediate post-natal period through providing free birth support, preparation and education.  We work specifically with women who suffer from social and economic disadvantage, and who are lacking adequate support.  This may include, but is not limited to young women, culturally and linguistically diverse women including refugees and asylum seekers, and those who have experienced or are experiencing poverty, trauma, abuse, or mental health challenges.  Through our work we seek to reduce the risk of psychological stress, birth trauma, and peri- and post-natal depression, and subsequently improve outcomes in maternal and infant wellbeing, childbirth recovery, and parent-child attachment for those who are most vulnerable.  Birth for HumanKIND is non-denominational and has no political agenda.  To do this the Company will undertake the following activities:  1.  provide a free service offering continuous one-to-one  doula care during the pregnancy, birth, and postnatal  period to reduce the distress and disadvantage of  vulnerable women;   2.  provide information and education about childbirth preparation, maternal health choices, and the maternal health system for women in Australia targeted specifically for disadvantaged women and recent arrivals;   3.  provide advocacy and onward referrals to relevant community and health agencies, and build community partnerships to support the relief of birthing women in socially and economically disadvantaged circumstances;   4.  raise awareness about the benefits of continuous doula care and informed birth choices in reducing the psychological and physical health risks of pregnancy and childbirth, and improving maternal, child and family health, with specific reference to disadvantaged women, their children, families and communities.  We have undertaken the following activities and achieved the following outcomes, as set out in our purposes:  1.  Free doula service: -  Recruited additional 15 volunteer doulas (total volunteer  doulas = 30) -  Supported 76 women  2.  Education -  Successfully piloted young mumês program with 6 participants  3.  Advocacy and onward referrals, build community partnerships  Link to the annual report: http://www.birthforhumankind.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/BfHK-Annual-Report-SCREEN.pdf

Over the past 25 years Cornerstone Contact Centre in heart of downtown Dandenong has provided a drop in home to many in our community who are experiencing hardship, and are in need of some extra support.Through providing a meal or food parcel, a safe place to meet, a place to belong, social connection, a positive environment, good friends or a listening ear, Cornerstone continues to be a home to many who come through their door (20,000 plus visits per year).Cornerstone is operated largely by a committed team of over 100 volunteers from the local community (including from a variety of local churches), and is located on the corner of Mason and Walker Streets in Dandenong (easy walking distance from Dandenong station).Many who come through the doors unfortunately do not have a safe place to call home, and many live without supportive family and friends around them. Many are experiencing homelessness, or living in unsafe and unstable housing, some have experienced relationship breakdown, mental health issues, addictions, unemployment, and some have come from overseas where they faced trials such as war and famine in their homeland, or any number of other complexities. Regardless of a personês background, everyone is welcome at Cornerstone, their home away from home.Cornerstone Contact Centre is open most days of the week, operates with a small part-time staff (just three) and relies heavily on a committed team of volunteers across their various programs.

column41: Board of Management Report for the year ending August 31st 2016Board members all act in an honorary capacityGovernance statement: Heartbeat Victoria is a Victorian state association founded in 1984 and incorporated under the Association Incorporation Act 1981(Vic). It is a not for profit charitable organisation, registered under the Australian Charities and Not-For-Profit Commission (ACNC). Heartbeat Victoria Council Inc. is the umbrella organisation for Heartbeat affiliates and branches. (Currently 9) Heartbeat Victoria has three Affiliates they are independently incorporated. Heartbeat Bendigo Inc., Heartbeat Epworth Inc., Heartbeat Sunraysia Inc., and six branches. Ararat, Ballarat, Grampians, Goulburn Valley, Knox, Latrobe, which are not separately incorporated. Heartbeat Victoria Council Inc., Rules of the Association were amended under The Associations Incorporations Reform Act (2012) from the Constitution of Heartbeat Victoria Council Inc.1984 and approved by Special Resolution, accepted by members at the AGM on August 27th 2015. The Rules are available on the Consumer Affairs Victoria website. Strategic Plan; The Board of Management are currently guided by Heartbeat Victoria Inc. Strategic Plan 2015-17. We are focused on building and maintaining a sustainable organisation which values its entire membership.  Our vision to be an excellent well recognised support organisation which assists in improving the emotional, social, and physical wellbeing of people living with heart disease or heart condition is the main focus of our objectives. The contracting of a consultant to assist the Board has enabled the professional development of the organisation to provide the best strategies to support our members and plan to further enhance and spread of the benefits of heart peer support groups across the state. The Board is currently working on improving communication and promotion of Heartbeatsê vision, mission and values to appropriate stake holders with improved promotional material, use of Facebook and currently developing  a contemporary website. Through the support of our consultant we now have a draft copy of Heartbeat Victoria Policy and Procedure Manual. This will be a valuable tool for office bearers and committees in providing guidance in governance, administration and pre-formatted forms to them in their individual roles within the organisation. Financial Sustainability: The Board of Management now has a board member who is a Charted Accountant to guide the development of a financial plan that ensures the financial sustainability of Heartbeat Victoria Council Inc. and its affiliates and branches. Part of this will be looking at revenue raising opportunities through government funding, philanthropic grants and sponsors. In June 2016 we were successful in obtaining a grant from Department of Social Services, Strengthening Communities, Volunteer Grant for $4943.00. column41: Ovarian Cancer Australia has had an excitingand busy 12 months.This year, we focused on using technology andinnovation to expand our reach, so we canbetter support women living with ovarian canceracross the country.Ovarian Cancer Australia ran a series of sixwebinars, thanks to funding from the JackBrockhoff Foundation. The webinars werehugely successful, covering a wide range oftopics including: survivorship, communicationand cancer, genetics and family history,clinical trials and research and a session onunderstanding ovarian cancer. The webinarsenabled women from all over Australia to takepart from the comfort of their own homes.As well as the webinars, Ovarian Cancer Australialaunched our new online forum, Ovarian CancerAustralia Connect. The forum is a great way forwomen impacted by ovarian cancer, families andfriends to connect with others going through asimilar experience, 24 hours a day seven daysa week.As well as our focus on technology, OvarianCancer Australia has developed its new StrategicPlan for 2016 _ 2020. The plan, which sets ourorganisational priorities for the next four years,aims to deliver best practice, accessible supportinformed by consumers; to ensure all Australiansknow the signs and symptoms of ovarian cancer;to strive to reduce the incidence of ovarian cancerby 25% and improve the five year survival rate by 25% by the year 2025.This year Ovarian Cancer Australia achieved amuch deeper engagement with parliamentarians with both the Prime Minister and Leader of theOpposition speaking in support of our work at ourTeal Ribbon Day Breakfast in Canberra. We wereheartened that many parliamentarians spokein parliament throughout February about theimportance of raising awareness of ovarian cancer.We were also honoured that both the Governorof Victoria and the Administrator of the NorthernTerritory hosted celebrations for our 15th birthday.It was encouraging to see how far weêve come inthe last 15 years and to meet with all the inspiringpeople who have contributed to the organisationin that time. The team is working together to help reduce the devastating impact of ovarian cancer onwomen and families, and to take action on behalfof all the women living with the disease. Together we can save lives and ensure that no womanliving with ovarian cancer walks alone.

In 2016 CMVic continued to make progress towards our overarching purpose of enabling all Victorians to have the opportunity to take part in music making. We supported, promoted and facilitated group music-making through our developmental program of group music-making leadership skills workshops, and through our active music-making program, which included two weekend music-making camps and a range of other gatherings. CMVic also: produced a monthly newsletter distributed free to about 2000 people, provided advice about choirs and instrumental music groups while continuing to gather information about such groups and further developed the website, www.cmvic.org.au, which has a search facility for people looking for choirs or instrumental music groups along with news and information. 2016 was a specially significant year in terms of one of our key aims _ enabling people from more diverse backgrounds to participate in inclusive group music making. Four projects have been outstanding in this area: Sing English _ working with EAL teachers in partnership with the Urban Lyrebirds, to help them gain skills and confidence in using singing in their classrooms teaching migrants including refugees and asylum seekers; Singing from Country _ linking Victorian songwriters and community to Aboriginal knowledge holders, naturalists and ecologists to create and sing songs that help reconnect people to place; StreetSounds _ a joyful explosion of new street bands of new street bands across Victoria with participants from many backgrounds; Singing for Inclusion, run in partnership with Creativity Australia, was designed in 2016 and will continue to increase the capacity of the networks of Victorian community singing leaders to lead inclusive singing groups and choirs. More details and copies of CMVicês audited accounts are available in the 2016 Annual Report, available at https://cmvic.org.au/about-us/cmvic-annual-reports.
