column39: All activities undertaken by Bush Heritage during this period were underpinned by the six goals of the 2012-17 Strategic Plan:Goal 1: Double the area secured for conservation, by direct acquisition and partnership, from 3 million to 6 million hectares;Goal 2: Maintain and improve conservation management outcomes;Goal 3: Demonstrate leadership and innovation in nature conservation;Goal 4: Increase to 30 000 the number of people we engage with and who support our work;Goal 5: Build the financial sustainability and operational capacity of Bush Heritage;Goal 6: Ensure an organisational culture of collaboration and commitment.For more information on Bush Heritageês activities towards achieving its 2012-17 Strategic Plan during 2016-17, please refer to the Annual Report - www.bushheritage.org.au/about/annual-reports. During 2016-17, Bush Heritage developed a 2017-22 Plan which focuses on the vision _Healthy Country, protected foreverî and purpose To return the bush to good health.
column41: This year was the second year in which Bush Heritage Australia used international standards, known as Impact Reporting and Investment Standards, to report on its protection and enhancement of the natural environment. These standards allow Bush Heritage to demonstrate the extent to which its on-ground conservation activities have improved the health of the native species and landscapes it manages, the extent to which it has reduced the severity of threats to those species and landscapes, and how it has leveraged the effectiveness of its operations to achieve the best possible outcomes for Australiaês species and landscapes.In 2017, Bush Heritage launched its strategic plan for 2017-2022, after achieving the goals set out in its strategic plan for 2012-2017. Those achievements include protecting and managing 6.2 million hectares of land for conservation, either directly through reserves or in partnership with others. That land and our management activity now protects habitat for 5812 species and of those species, 235 are listed as threatened on either a state or national level. In 2016-2017, Bush Heritage also contributed or played a leading role in 81 research projects with partners from 24 universities or other organisations. It also supported five science scholarships and employed two science interns, worked on reintroduction trials for five significant species, and saw 21 peer-reviewed papers published based on work that occurred on our reserves. These achievements are in line with the actions outlined in our Science and Research Plan for 2015-2025, and have contributed to us meeting our 2017 goal of demonstrating leadership and innovation in nature conservation. They occurred alongside the routine monitoring, management, survey and inventory work that occurs on all our reserves and partnership properties every day. Strengthening engagement with volunteers, supporters and the general public were also priorities. In 2016-2017, volunteers contributed 36,660 hours of their time to Bush Heritageês work _ equivalent to $1.29 million based on the national standard hourly rate. Approximately 27.5 million people across Australia were reached through local and national media stories about the organisationês work.   For the last two years, Bush Heritage has achieved its 2017 target of maintaining annual income at, or near, $20 million _ a powerful show of support for our work. We now have more than 32,000 financial supporters (exceeding our 2017 goal to have over 30,000 supporters) and over 460 volunteers, making it more important than ever to stay connected using modern and efficient systems. This year, we invested in such systems, including an interactive website and a new supporter relationship database. Further details can be found in the 2016-2017 Annual Report - www.bushheritage.org.au/about/annual-reports.

The Mutunga Partnershipês resources are targeted principally to its primary purpose, that of funding, managing and delivering a micro-credit/micro finance economic development project in Kenya. It tackles chronic poverty by providing micro-loans and training to micro-entrepreneurs, enabling them to graduate out of poverty by self-help means and to create employment for others. The Partnership has continued to provide micro-loans to hundreds of borrowers (70% of whom are women) and has lifted another 3,000 people out of poverty in 2016, by providing them employment, bringing its cumulative results to over 40,000 people lifted out of poverty over 11 years. During 2016 the work in Kenya has resulted in an expansion of the project and an increase the number of clients. The charityês secondary purpose is in Community Development through the Arts. The Mutunga Partnership has supported a musical skills-development program amongst Aboriginal choirs in remote communities in Central Australia, by up-skilling them and reviving 100 years of choral practice which had gone into almost terminal decline. The choirs present music in the Western Arrarnta, Pitjantjatjara and Yorta Yorta languages, and also in English, German and Zulu. The skills-development process and its associated performances have been effective conduits for the choirs to engage with the NT arts sector and led to measurable improvements in the physical and mental health of the participants and contributed to social development in remote communities in Central Australia.

Please refer to the Hotham Mission Annual Report-2016 @hothammission.org.au.Programs run in 2016:1 UCHM designed and developed Mess Club to reach out to children disengaging from education. This program includes staff from the primary school and closely liaises with the school to provide an extra-curricular club.  An average of about 12 students currently participate in Mess Club.2.The Venny Dinner Night program. Until this program received alternative funding, UCHM provided funding and staff support. The program itself provides a weekly meal for young people facing food insecurity.3.Food for Thought provides packs of food for students from Mt Alexander College, St Josephês Flexible Learning Centre and the Venny who are at risk of disengaging from education because of food insecurity. Students are referred to the program from their school or the Venny. The program has grown substantially over the past 12 months, and currently provides food to 72 families. Food vouchers for lunch time are also provided to identified students through the MACpack program. Lack of food at lunch time has been identified by the Food Insecurity Social Research Project as a problem in two other schools.4.North Melbourne Homework Club. With an average attendance of 9 students and 5 volunteers per week, this program continues to provide education support for this group of students.  5. Renshaw Education Support: provides small financial aid packages to students referred to the program from schools. The aid is paid through the school for educational materials to assist students to continue with their education. Students from Mt Alexander College, University High, and St Josephês Flexible Learning Centre are eligible.  6.Support for asylum seekers: Accommodation was provided to five asylum seekers on the Curzon Street site. Casework support is provided to asylum seekers through Lentara UnitingCare. Additionally, the UCHM community development worker and the Minister and the congregation of Mark the Evangelist provide support to residents as need arises.  A grant was provided to Kensington Neighbourhood House for English language classes for asylum seekers. 7.Provision of educational materials and goods to the children in detention on Manus Island and Nauru _ a one-off shipment of these materials, 98.The Food Insecurity Social Research Project is proceeding according to its approved research design.We are proud of the achievements of our programs. In total over the year, UCHM provided packs of food per week to up to 72 families through its Food for Thought program and 492 Macpack vouchers for students. The Venny Dinner Night program served an average of 8 children.  The Homework Club had an average attendance of 9 children. The Mess Club provided activities to 12 children, and prior to it, the BOLT program had 9 participants. Accommodation was provided to 5 asylum seekers, . The Renshaw program provided assistance to 50 students

column41: Our major activities this year have been to work with Aboriginal communities in Sunraysia. All our activities are described on our website at www.threeforallfoundation.org These activities accord with the principal purposes of the THREE for All Foundation Australia Fund, to provide relief to Australianês in necessitous circumstances through program development, provision of funding support and provision of professional development, administrative and governance support and other capacity building activities for organisations that deliver services to those individuals in need.

column2: Bubup Wilam For Early Learning Incorporated
column41: Bubup Wilam means ´Childrenês Placeê in Woi Wurrung language. Bubup Wilam is an Aboriginal Child and Family Centre in the suburb of Thomastown, in the City of Whittlesea, inMelbourne´s north. Bubup Wilam for Early Learning provides Aboriginal children, families and the community with access to an integrated range of services and programs, including: early intervention and prevention programs, early years education, and health and wellbeing services. Bubup Wilam currently provides a culturally strong, integrated and enhanced model of care, comprising of: ‚ A health and wellbeing program (BWEL) that includes an annual Child Health Check and an Education, Health and Wellbeing Plan for all children (in collaboration with the VictorianAboriginal Health Service). ‚ A 70 place early learning centre for children aged 6 months and over. ‚ A 3 and 4 year old kindergarten program, which is delivered within the long day-care program, and an extension program. ‚ A transition to primary school program, in partnership with the local primary schools. ‚ Supported referrals for families who need to access a range of specialist services (such as housing, health, welfare, pediatrician, OT, etc) and case management/care coordination for parents/carers with complex needs. ‚ Access to in-reach support services for children with special needs, including a visiting maternal and child health nurse and speech pathologist, facilitated referral to specialist services, access to disability support workers, etc. ‚ A culturally appropriate one-on-one enhanced learning model for all children that is underpinned by the National Quality Framework. ‚ A range of health promotion activities and events. ‚ An accredited training program and placements delivered on-site for Aboriginal people seeking to gain a Certificate 3 or Diploma in Childrenês Services. ‚ A professional development program for staff and available to staff in external agencies. Bubup Wilam has established partnerships with a range of local agencies, including the Victorian Aboriginal Health Service, Victoriaês Commissioner for Aboriginal Children and Young People, the local primary schools, the City of Whittlesea and other services which can support vulnerable and at-risk children

column41: Variety empowers Australian children who are sick, disadvantaged or have special needs to live laugh and learn.  Our vision is for all Australian children to reach their full potential regardless of ability or background.  In 2016 Variety Victoria directly impacted 2155 children across Victoria by providing grants through our three key programs - Freedom, Future and Caring for Kids.  We provided 67 grants through our Freedom program, helping 1851 children gain independence by providing financial support for mobility equipment, positioning and in-home care needs.  This includes the provision of custom modified tricycle and bikes, wheelchairs, specialist car seats and more.  We provided 43 grants through our Future Kids program helping 7117 children realize their potential by providing financial support for education and communication equipment. This includes the provision of specialist computer packages, communication devices, scholarships, camps, regional and special education school support, sensory playgrounds,   and more. We provided 8 grants through our Caring for Kids program, by providing 187 children with medical items and care equipment so that sick children can live happy, healthy lives. This includes nebulisers, electric beds for families at home, supporting paediatric hospital wards, children's respite and rehabilitation centres and more.

Thomastown West Kindergarten is recognised as servicing a disadvantaged community. On the socio-economic index for areas (SEIFA) Thomastown is listed in the lowest 20% for Victoria. A majority of the families at this Kindergarten are amongst some of the most financially disadvantaged families in our municipality. Most families are concession card holders (50%+) and new immigrants including refugees and asylum seekers. Many children come from single parent families, have unemployed parents and several families are supported by Protective Services, Child First and Early Start funding. We also have children supported by KIS funding. Our charity purpose is to ensure local families and children have access to universal high quality educational preschool programs. We are continuously at capacity and provide a low or no fee educational service for families along with building links with other charity organisation and schools supporting our vulnerable community. Our charity status provides us with ongoing financial sustainability to provide quality community educational services.

FSC Australia is a not-for-profit membership based organisation established to promote responsible forest management in Australia and in countries supplying the Australian wood and fibre market. The main areas of activity conducted by FSC Australia in pursuit of this mission in 2015 fall into five broad categories: National Standard, Indigenous Engagement, Strategic Partnership, Strategic Realignment, and Growth & Insights. During 2016 the focus of our policy development was advancing the first FSC Australian Forest Stewardship Standard through drafts 3 and 4, with extensive stakeholder feedback captured through waves of public consultation equipping our Standards Development Group to reach agreement on a range of areas. These included the High Conservation Values Framework, a simplified approach to Scale Intensity and Risk, a refined approach around Sustainable Yield and - with the help of our Indigenous Working Group, culturally appropriate and robust controls around Indigenous Rights. The draft Standard also includes new requirements for social impact assessment and refined provisions for engagement with stakeholders and local communities. During 2016 we made considerable progress in the development of an Innovate Reconciliation Action Plan (RAP) guided by our Indigenous Working Group, to express and deliver our commitment to recognising and advancing the rights, interests and values of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.  With financial assistance from Tork Professional Hygiene, FSC's Future Generations program, developed with Deakin University, was launched in TermTwo 2016. Future Generations aims to bring the cross-curriculum priority of sustainability into every subject - fro Arts to Humanities and English. Future Generations includes six series of lesson plans and activity sheet. These free lesson plans are available for primary school levels 1-6 and are in line with AusVELS curriculum.   FSC Australia supported communication around the Rio Olympics, highlighting the fact that all wood and wood products acquired by the Organizing Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games were FSC certified, from structures to stationery, from podiums to medal cases. We reached over 5 million people, with almost 500,000 taking an active role in sharing or visiting our related information. In 2016 we continued to deliver programs and services, provide advice, resources and support and advocate for change, to improve community health and wellbeing, with a particular focus on children. We continued to expand our work into the early childhood education sector _ supported by an Innovation grant from VicHealth, in conjunction with Softball VIC, supporting parents to be active role models to their children, and also through our Mighty Movers program in the ACT working with playgroups and parents using active play and movement to support the social, emotional, physical and cognitive development of young children and our of course our partnership with YMCA ACT for the Take Off Program, which won a Children Week Award.  Through all of our work we continued to focus on sustainable behavioural change. In 2015 we worked directly in 186 schools, early learning centres and playgroups, providing well over 700 teachers with a professional development program using physical activity and movement as a vehicle to support the learning and development of over 22,000 students. We also nearly doubled our online support to teachers with nearly 5,000 teachers supported through our online teacher resource centre.  We continued to build on our work in in disadvantaged communities with more than two of our work being delivered in disadvantaged and/or rural and remote communities.  We continued to expand our community partnerships in Aboriginal communities in the Northern Territory and East Kimberley Western Australia working to improve parental engagement and school readiness through the support provided by the Federal Governmentês Indigenous Advancement Strategy.  We also initiated a community partnership with Yok Djakoorliny to support fitness scholarships for Aboriginal women. The ACT Governmentês Healthy Canberra grants and philanthropic partners the Freake Family Trust, Give Where you Live Geelong, Barr Family Foundation, and Madge Brown Trust have enabled us to continue this important work as well as community donors and supporters. We also continued to support the fitness industry through our Physical Activity Australia Division which continued to strengthen linkages with the fitness industry to both improve standards and professionalism of the industry and recognise and value the contribution the industry makes to overall health and wellbeing. We continued to support Parentês Voice recognising the important role that parents play in supporting children to lead healthy active lives. We have developed further information for parents and the general community, making information available both through the Bluearth websites, the Victorian Government Better Health Channel and social media as well as distributing information through partners. We were also very pleased to launch our new Move More Sit Less campaign providing over 35,000 people with information, tools and resources to help them their families, schools and workplaces to move more and sit less,

Through a combination of specialist support services, training & consultancy, knowledge sharing & advocacy, we are working to remove the barriers young people face as they make Australia their home. 1. Providing direct one-to-one support for young people with family, housing, education & employment issues. 2. Delivering leadership programs that offer young people opportunities to contribute to Australian society. 3. Providing training, professional development & consultancy services for organisations to work more effectively with young people. 4. Building research evidence and sharing our knowledge. 5. Providing evidence-based policy advice & advocacy to decision makers at local, state & national levels. Young people can encounter significant barriers as they try to settle in Australia. Alongside the challenges of growing up, they are figuring out how things are done & adjusting to unfamiliar cultural, academic and social expectations. Their sense of wellbeing & belonging can be considerably diminished by factors such as racism & discrimination. These barriers are often compounded & magnified by services & systems that are ill-equipped to provide the specialist support needed. Despite these complex issues we know that young people have the enterprise, resilience & optimism to contribute to the continued prosperity of Australia. By engaging them as experts in their own lives & focusing on their strengths, they can be empowered to adapt and thrive.

Catalyst Australia Women Research and Consulting Limited provides resources for organisations to build more diverse and inclusive workplaces where women and men around the world, representing every dimension of diversity, have fair and equal  opportunity to thrive. At Catalyst we want to fuel breakthroughs through the creation of actionable knowledge. We achieve our purpose through our pioneering research, our tools and services, our events, and our Awards. - Our research, tools and practices raise awareness of how diversity benefits todayês global businesses, and provide guidance on how to enact real change. - Our multiple in-person and virtual meetings inspire action and guide individuals in their work to achieve their diversity and inclusion goals. - Our research in Australia helps us give clear direction, specific and actionable for Australian companies and firms.

Hope Ink is a non-profit organisation that believe through community development programs and social enterprises, impacts individuals at a local level. Hope Ink believes that by providing people with care, vocational training, leadership training and opportunity, they can develop their potential and become empowered members of their community. Hope Ink has a strategic focus on issues of disadvantage people in the West. As such it has established a pool of volunteers with varied skill sets and experiences that are ready to be mobilized. Currently, Hope Ink runs a Food bank every Wednesday afternoon distributing food to the ASRC (Asylum Seeker Resource Centre) and to families in need throughout the Inner and outer West of Melbourne. Hope Ink currently facilitates a weekly Adult English conversation group for newly arrived migrants who speak little English and who are extremely isolated due to cultural and language barriers. Classes are held in Point Cook. Hope Ink also currently facilitates two SHINE program, the first program is located at the ASRC in Footscray with women who are Asylum Seekers and are highly vulnerable and at risk and the second program is located at Louis Joel Arts and Community Centre in Altona with women from various backgrounds who would like to discover their value, worth, strength and purpose.Hope Ink recently developed its Social Enterprise called Scrubs For Change out of its Williamstown office. Medical Scrubs are manufactured by our Cambodian partners who have rescued and rehabilitated women and girls out of sexual exploitation _ given them a skill and employment. Our Medical Scrubs are packaged and sold from our Williamstown office to customers around Australia and the profits from the enterprise are fed back into Hope Inkês local community programs.

column2: National Ethnic and Multicultural Broadcastersê Council Incorporated
column41: The NEMBC continues to represent ethnic and multicultural community broadcasting to advocate, develop policy and to seek additional funding for the sector. Representation and policy strategies to support multiculturalism, multilingualism and community broadcasting include: liaising with government; developing and writing submissions; attending forums and events and creating partnerships and projects.See the full Annual Report of the NEMBC at: http://www.nembc.org.au/publications/AdvocacyThe NEMBC continues to be consistent in its a funding submission to the Federal Government and continues to prosecute itês case with a well-referenced fifteen page document explaining three key areas where additional funds are required for ethnic community broadcasting. NetworkingThe NEMBC has excellent working relationships with many like-minded organisations. The NEMBC continues to use networking and partnership as a means to strengthen issues of multiculturalism and multilingualism with relevant organisations such as the Federation of Ethnic Community Councils Australia (FECCA) and Ethnic Community Councils Victoria (ECCV). The NEMBC will continue its partnership with African Media Australia and Universities to work on the recommendations and actions from the inaugural National Migration, Media and Integration/Social Cohesion Conference held in April 2016.CommunicationsThe Ethnic Broadcaster journal, the publication of the NEMBC, is read widely, not only by ethnic and multicultural broadcasters but also by a range of people and institutions interested in ethnic and multicultural affairs and broadcasting, with an estimated readership of 8,000.There is a minimum of three issues published in the funded year, complemented by ebulletins and matching regular up-to-date and relevant news and information presented on the NEMBCs main website. ProjectsThe NEMBC is continuing with its ENGAGE project to work in regional and rural areas of Victoria to support those new and emerging communities who arenêt represented at their local community station and provide them an opportunity to receive radio training so they are ´radio-readyê to start an on-air radio program. The ultimate goal is to create the right environment for these programs to be sustainable so they can provide an important link of information, entertainment and news to their local community. The NEMBC, is working with the Shepparton community radio station ONE FM to commence 6 to 9 new language radio programs. Womenês State Forum A key priority for the Womenês Committee in servicing the needs of women broadcastersê. The NEMBC intends to hold state based forums on a yearly basis, the last one was in July 2015 in Sydney, for women broadcasters based in NSW.  Conferences The NEMBCês National Conferences for 2016 was held in Sydney from 25-27 November at Novotel Sydney Central. The Youth Media Conference was held on 25 November and the NEMBC AGM on Sunday 27 November.

Our mission is: -To promote and enable equality of access and opportunity for frail aged people, people with a disability, and those who care for them, so that they can maintain their independence and links to the local community.South PortDay Links (SPDL) is a local volunteer-based, incorporated Not for Profit organisation. SPDL, a registered charity with the Australian Tax Office (ATO) and Australian Charities and Not for Profit Commission (ACNC), has been operating for the last 28 years, deliveringservices, which contribute directly to the lives of residents residing in the City of Port Phillip (CoPP). The services allow residents to remain independent, connected to their community and able to live at home with a reduced sense of social isolation.The services are targeted to support the needs of older people, people with a disability and other eligible residents, encouraging them to remain active by supporting them to maintain their physical health and emotional sense of wellbeing. The services include:‚ DayLinks: Door to door community transport service‚ PetLinks: Support to residents in the care of their animals‚ WalkMates: Companion walking program, maintaining a person's fitness‚ GardenMates: Support to maintain the garden‚ InfoLink: Information service to local residents‚ Bettyês Bus Trips: Recreational programs for older residents‚ DriverLinks: Provision of mini bus drivers to community groups to support activities.These services are vitally important as they support the local community at a time when the number of older people is predicted to grow significantly within the municipality and baby boomers retire in larger numbers in coming decades.SPDL services are based on active service and ageing in place modelsê, which value a personês dignity and self-respect, by encouraging and supporting their independence.

The aim is to of this day is to connect community members, by holding community events on International Pregnancy and Infant Loss day (15 October). Each person touched by infant loss lights a candle at 7pm to represent each baby that has been lost, to create a wave of light around the world.

We believe a young personês experience with homelessness should not define their life and should be given the opportunity to be able to reach their true potential. We forge innovative partnerships to provide integrated housing, one-on-one support and a range of essential life skill development opportunities, so that the young people in our programs are able to transition to independence and reach their true potential irrespective of the barriers they face. Ladder offers aspirational programs and individual services which have been specifically designed to build talents, skills and capacities _ ultimately guiding towards a future of independence. Itês a holistic service response, which includes group and individual activities designed to improve life skills (e.g. communication, project management, problem solving), prepare and progress towards independence, support with education, employment and training activities, link young people to their communities, enhance fitness and wellbeing and offer mentoring.

Over the last year the VCCC partnership has grown to ten partners, with the addition of the Murdoch Childrens Research Institute. The expansion over recent years has been quite strategic aimed to align the VCCC partnership with partners of the Melbourne Academic Centre for Health and institutions affiliated with the University of Melbourne. This partnership provides access to large cancer patient populations, enables the further development of clinical research and clinical trials, deepens cancer research and education capabilities and will enable wider impact on more patients for improvement in cancer results.The VCCC partnershipês strategy for building a centre of excellence has been to generate new data to support cancer clinical service improvement, expand the cancer research capabilities of our partners and develop new methods for more rapidly translating research discoveries into routine clinical practice.The VCCC partnershipês research strategy has been to identify our cancer research strengths and gaps that must be filled, measure and benchmark our research performance, invest in the very best researchers, build innovative shared research platforms and build translational research structures and opportunities.The Leaders in Cancer Research Program has been the VCCC partnershipês vehicle to recruit and retain the very best researchers, clinicians and teachers. It is building depth, breadth and excellence in our people conducting cancer research. It has built new research programs in priority areas with recent appointments in nursing research, palliative medicine and genomics. Further recruitment of research leaders is underway in surgical oncology, psycho-oncology, bioinformatics and gynaecological cancers. Between them, these appointments provide a magnet for other talented cancer researchers and an effective mechanism for attracting additional research capability and industry funding. The Tumour Stream Leads pilot program is aimed at developing and translating new research directly into clinical practice and expanding research opportunities. Research and Education Leads across all VCCC partners were appointed for two tumour streams, melanoma & skin cancer and haematology, and one cross-cutting theme, primary care. The role of the leads is to bring together key researchers and clinicians around a particular cancer or theme to expand research opportunities and to embed new discoveries into practice more quickly. The leads have already initiated workshops to improve genomics literacy in haematology and on the evolving role of primary care in cancer. The appointment of Research and Education Leads for three further tumour streams/themes is currently underway, including for nursing, lung and gastrointestinal cancers.In 2016, the VCCC conducted a second Cancer Patient Experience Survey (CPES) across the expanded VCCC partnership, with data collected for over 3,500 patients. Annual report available at victorianccc.org.au

Redeveloped in the late 1990s as an arts and culture venue, The SUBSTATIONês new program respects the original vision for the building as an asset for artists and audiences _ this will include artists creating and presenting work across art-form where audiences are at times invited to collaborate in the making of the artwork. Reflecting the broader history of Melbourneês inner West, we encourage engagement with our unique post-industrial building and spaces, where we foster a culture of interconnectedness, collaboration and independence. With a commitment to developing artistic practice and building long term relationships with artists, we seek to provoke a conversation on how arts and culture interrelate with the rest of our world, and how artists can reflect those experiences back to us.

VISION 2020Express Media is valued and acknowledged as a leader and innovator and is the peak youth literary organisation in Australia, delivering a broad range of professional development opportunities and essential support for young writers. Express Media contributes to a vibrant literary sector by building community, supporting access, inclusion and participation and developing the next generation of writers that will emerge to populate Australiaês literary festivals, publishing houses and media outlets.MISSIONTo:‚ Encourage young Australians from all backgrounds to engage with the literary arts‚ Support young Australian writers from all backgrounds to produce and present their work‚ Raise awareness, increase support and build an audience for young Australian writers‚ Cultivate, enhance, improve and diversify the literary and broader arts sector in AustraliaBy:‚ Producing a vibrant national program promoting diversity, access and participation‚ Prioritising a broad spectrum of craft and skills development, nurturing talent and recognising excellence‚ Communicating the work and contribution of young Australian writers through publication, promotion and advocacy‚ Building partnerships, supporting professional pathways and fostering careersKEY GOALS 2016‚ Build awareness and engagement with Express Mediaês program of development, support, recognition and publication opportunities for young Australian writers‚ Increase geographic reach, delivering a national program of activities that are accessible to young writers across Australia‚ Develop and deliver a creative writing and publication program in Australian secondary schools‚ Grow audiences, leverage support and advocate for young Australian writers‚ Grow the financial and human resources of Express Media creating a sustainable platform from which to launch our programsACTIVITIES 2016In 2016, Express Media ventured into new terrain, both online and offline, to showcase the freshest writing from across Australia and deliver opportunities direct to young writers.We launched Tracks _ our new pop-up series of workshops, masterclasses and special events - which we presented at locations across the country in partnership with some of Australiaês most exciting youth and literary organisations. We reached young writers in region and remote locations with Toolkits, our new online writing program.We partnered with Victorian literary organisations to deliver the inaugural Blak & Bright Indigenous Literary Festival in Melbourne and published over 100 young writers in our flagship publication Voiceworks, and gave feedback to thousands more.Also featured in the 2016 program were prizes, fellowships and publications that ensure young writers keep discovering new ways to express themselves.

TEAR Australia is a movement of Christians in Australia responding to the needs of poor communities around the world. Our motivation comes from our belief that God loves all people, and in Christ offers them the opportunity of a new life. We believe that God is just, and has particular care for the poor and those who suffer as victims of injustice.We work in partnership with other Christian groups, including churches, relief and development agencies and community-based organisations, which are working with the poor in their communities. We seek to build effective relationships with these partners, grounded in mutual respect, trust and accountability.Priority is given to those programs that strive to involve the most marginalised and exploited members of each community, regardless of their religious or political beliefs.In Australia, we work to inform and empower Christians, in partnership with local churches, to make a biblically-shaped response to suffering and oppressed communities.For details about activities and outcomes during the past year, please see our annual report available on our website at www.tear.org.au

Reduced the impact of mental ill-health on young people, their families and society.Orygen is the worldês leading research and knowledge translation organisation focusing on mental ill-health in young people.At Orygen, the leadership and staff work to deliver cutting-edge research, innovative clinical services, and evidence-based training and education to ensure that there is continuous improvement in the treatments and care provided to young people experiencing mental ill-health.Orygen develops knowledge, and synthesises that knowledge with other learning from researchers and clinicians around the world to contribute to service development and broader policy discussions, as well as further research, in youth mental health.This work has created a new approach, and constructive attitude, to the prevention and treatment of mental disorders, and new models of care for young people with emerging disorders. It has been translated into a world-wide shift in services and treatments to include a primary focus on getting well and staying well, and holistic health care models that include partnership with young people and families.In particular, over these five years Orygenês key activities are to:1. Create knowledge: Establish in Australia the worldês leading youth mental health research platform, linked with a network of emerging international centres, that discovers better tailored and targeted interventions for young people experiencing mental ill-health.2. Apply knowledge: Establish the worldês leading youth mental health exemplar service system in Melbourne that provides young Melbournians with access to the highest attainable standard of mental health care and provides a model for national and international replication.3. Share knowledge: Establish the worldês leading youth mental health training service to develop world-class skills and knowledge in the youth mental health workforce in Australia and establish an extensive international youth mental health professional development network.4. Inform public policy reform: Support full national and widespread international implementation of high quality, evidence-based youth mental health models of care.These activities build on the significant achievements of Orygen to date. Since it was established in 2002, Orygen has enacted a comprehensive research program in mental disorders that occur in young people, and dramatically increased the publications that inform the fields of early intervention in psychiatry and youth mental health.Orygen continues to extend the field of youth mental health worldwide. Orygen's 2016 Annual Report can be found at: https://www.orygen.org.au/getmedia/b365a782-da68-486d-bdaa-cc26b213aeaa/Orygen_Annual-Report-2016_web.aspx

Weave Movement Theatre is an ambitious and diverse Melbourne based hybrid dance and theatre performance company comprising people with and without disabilities.Weave formed in 1997 through an Arts Access Victoria project and continues today developing high quality performances under the artistic direction of Janice Florence, a dance artist with paraplegia.Weavesê work subverts audienceês expectations and challenges conventional ways of seeing dance and disability. Weavesê work combines dance, physical theatre, spoken word and absurd humour to create bold ground-breaking performances.Weave presents a distinctive and progressive model for inclusive dance performance.In 2016, just some of the projects that the Weave Artistic Director and ensemble of performers completed include a short film that was screened at ACMI for the opening of a Disability and Human Rights conference in January, producing and running workshops for performers with disabilities, run by an international artist with a disability, Caroline Bowditch, workshops for children at Artplay, and a successful two-week season of performances at well known independent Melbourne venue, Forty Five Downstairs.

Court Networkês service is an important component of accessing justice, particularly for vulnerable and disadvantaged court users who may be attending court for the first time, be unfamiliar with court rules and processes, lack knowledge about what is expected of them, feel frightened and unsafe, be representing themselves in a matter, be challenged in being able to understand and participate effectively in the court processes, and/or be in need of someone to listen, provide support, and to assist in navigating the court system.  During 2015/16, our service assisted 162,560 people in Victoria and Queensland who were attending court for a criminal matter, a family violence matter or any other legal matters. Feedback from people used our service in the past year indicates that our service has made a positive impact on their experience of the court system and our service is highly valued by the community.    The achievement in our service delivery in 2015/16 was made possible by the dedication of our 461 Networker workforce, who have been professionally trained and supported by a team of talented and committed paid staff, contributed a collective 94,400 hours of time to support court users in Queensland and Victoria.

column39: Provide accommodation and support services for women and their children fleeing family violence.
column41: McAuley Community Services for Women provides services for women and their children who are escaping family violence; and for women who are homeless, primarily as a result of family violence or mental illness.  McAuley Care McAuley Care is the only safe house in Victoria that accepts women and their children 24 hours a day, seven days a week. Women and their children who escaping family violence are provided with emotional support as well as practical assistance with legal, medical and financial matters in order to help them assess their next steps and feel free to make choices.  McAuley also operates refuges as an extension of McAuley Care, offering longer-term accommodation and support.  McAuley House McAuley House supports women who are homeless or at risk of homelessness on their journey towards recovery, independence and social inclusion by providing accommodation, meals, intensive and individualised case management, social and recreational support and employment services.  McAuley Works McAuley Works is an intensive employment program that assists women impacted by homelessness to secure meaningful employment and increases their ability to support themselves financially.  Employer Awareness Program The Employer Awareness Program aims to improve employers' understanding of family violence, identify risks for staff, and develop and implement effective support practices.

column41: In subjects and issues relating to family history, the GSV continued to devote its resources and volunteers to provide a comprehensive education program and to manage its extensive library. Services are available to the public for a nominal fee, or free of charge to members and at certain times for groups such as seniors. Family research and preservation of records were encouraged and promoted in the community via a newspaper column, radio talk-back, the GSV website, presentations to community groups and responses to phone calls and correspondence. Detailed family historical research was conducted for public applicants, and volunteers provided one-on-one assistance to visiting researchers in the library. These included former migrants seeking help to access foreign records. Related services such as the obtaining of certificates and other records from local and overseas sources were provided. The GSV continued to monitor public issues and events concerning the protection of and access to family historical information, and provided informed advice when appropriate. This included provision of expert advice at a number of city and country family history fairs. GSV is a Place of Deposit under the Victorian Public Records Act 1973. Volunteers added to historical resources in the library by digitizing and indexing large numbers of records. Most of the work of the GSV is performed by 180 volunteers. Donations received are vital to the survival of the GSV and the continuation of its contribution to the cultural and social heritage of Victoria and Australia.

Friday Night School conducted tutoring classes every Friday night of the school term for the benefit of school aged students from non-English speaking backgrounds with a particular emphasis on assisting refugee students.  It provided scholarships to good schools for secondary education, assisted with fees for primary school students, provided financial assistance for text books for all secondary students, and provided a limited number of laptop computers and iPads to students.   Friday Night School supervised an associated program, Wednesday Night tutoring, whereby during the university year approximately 50 university students and young professionals tutor Friday Night School students in their homes (mainly the high rise flats in Richmond).  It gave students from private schools an opportunity to meet, understand and help the students who attend Friday Night School.   Friday Night School also conducted a camp for approximately 80 students and their tutors and conducted classes for parents of the students to practise their written and spoken English.

column41: Effective Altruism Australia exists to most effectively alleviate poverty, distress and suffering. In our first year of operations, we conducted our inaugural grant-making process and awarded grants to three organisations: GiveDirectly, the Schistosomiasis Control Initiative and Deworm the World Initiative (led by Evidence Action). We also partnered with the Against Malaria Foundation.We then undertook activities to raise funds to be able to grant to these partner organisations, including helping to organise the EAGxAustralia 2016 conference, recruiting volunteers and soliciting donations via our website.The organisations we partner with and grant funds to are regarded to be amongst the most effective at alleviating poverty by independent charity evaluators, including GiveWell and The Life You Can Save.By supporting their work we are supporting some of the most effective interventions that are proven to alleviate poverty. Provision of insecticide treated bed nets significantly reduces the burden of malaria and the impact that the disease has on economic outcomes. The treatment of schistosomiasis and other helminths not only reduces the health burden of these parasitic diseases but has also been found to result in improved education outcomes in children and also translate to higher income potential in adulthood. Direct cash transfers have been found to have large, positive and sustainable impacts on a range of factors including assets, ongoing earnings, food security, mental health and domestic violence.

column41: Kirkbrae Presbyterian Homes is located at the foothills of the Dandenongs, has been established since 1960 and comprises of a 110 bed residential care facility together with a retirement village of 74 cottages.The facility is owned and operated by the Presbyterian Church of Victoria Trusts Corporation whose mission is to provide the highest possible quality residential, community and health care whilst ensuring its residents' privacy and dignity is maintained, along with the encouragement of independence as far as is practically possible.Kirkbrae seeks to provide the highest standard of loving care to its residents within a comfortable, compassionate and friendly Christian community; along with ensuring the respect and welfare of staff at all times.Kirkbrae's philosophy is to involve residents, families and friends in determining appropriate individual care requirements, remembering always to treat our residents, as we would wish to be treated.The facility operates 24/7 and is managed by dedicated staff of approximately 160 comprising nurses, personal care workers, lifestyle, catering, gardening and administration. In addition, Kirkbrae provides chaplain and pastoral care for residents to comfort them during their time of need.Kirkbrae strives to maintain well-educated, dedicated and caring staff, committed to teamwork and to ongoing improvement in their respective disciplines and personal development.Under Federal legislation, the facility is assessed for Accreditation every three years.

ZFA believes in the protection of children from slavery and sexual exploitation and in their fundamental human right to freedom and a dignified future.  Our focus is the rescue and rehabilitation of children who are sold, or are at risk of being sold into commercial sexual exploitation, forced labour or other heinous crimes or abuse and the empowerment of survivors and vulnerable communities.  ZFA is working to address the causes of child trafficking by enacting holistic, sustainable and innovative responses. Through its partnership with ZOE International Foundation in Thailand (established in 2003), ZFA is deploying rescue, shelter, family reunification, healthcare, counseling, education, vocational training, relief and awareness campaigns. ZFA also runs awareness campaigns in Australia to galvanise local support and to equip and mobilise individuals, organisations and government to bring a permanent end to child trafficking.

As a Community Broadcaster we deliver a broad spectrum of information supply, entertainment, social advice, local sporting promotion, local news and matters of value to listeners within our broadcasting license area.  Volunteers are the backbone of the whole operation delivering both content, technical and front of office support.  As we now stream through the internet we have greatly increased our listener-ship opportunities not only for outgoing information but for inbound as well.  We have regular listeners in foreign countries when we run programs in languages other than English and when our content is of specific interest.  As Social Media increases its importance we have expanded to deliver podcasts for people to listen on-demand to programs that have already run. Community Radio has come a long way and communication in the modern era that is both from and for the local community and not bound but financial interests is a regime that should be protected and supported.  In recent times with the progressive withdrawal of grants self-funding has become a major challenge but with the strength and input of our volunteer base we maintain the best possible service.With our delivery tower supported by a backup generator we also are able to be a vital community conduit for all matters to do with public safety if threats such as storm or fire become a regional issue.

In our seventh year of singing together, we are a tight, strong performing group who have a diverse repertoire of pop, rock, traditional and jazz songs.We performed at the Exclusion and Embrace Disability, Justice and Spirituality Conference in August at The Jasper Hotel in the City. This was a Uniting Church conference, and the experience was uplifting for us and the audience. In October we participated in a workshop, and then performed, with Orkeztra Glasso Beshalde for the Village Festival in Edinburgh Gardens. Following this, we then performed a full length show with Orkeztra Glasso Beshalde for Darebin Music Feast. It was a great experience singing with and meeting the orchestra, and some fine dancing was done also.In December we did our customary performance at Carols In All Nations, followed by a break-up Christmas party and performance at St Vincent's Hospital.These events were enjoyed by all and attended by extended family members. They also furthered our choir's aim of demonstrating to the community the commitment and talent of our members, many of whom are living with moderate to severe disabilities.We also did a story session which was quite profound for all who were able to attend. Choir members worked with Jenny and Peter in a very trusting way and the result was a sharing of aspects of people's life stories which deepened our connection and respect for each other. It was a wonderful experience and gave some inspiration as to the deeper conversations we could be having. During the first few months of the year we basked in the glory of the Darebin Community Group of the Year Australia Day award received the year before and presented in January 2016. It is still a lovely reminder of the communityês esteem of our choir. A Communication Strategy was written in April 2016 and is a helpful guide for future thinking and planning. We also conducted a 'Relationship Building Project' with the aim of increasing our contacts with professionals, as well as promoting and educating the community about our choir. We have also made contact with staff of the NDIS, which is involved with a number of choir members. We will continue to learn about it and how to educate planners and participants about the choir.

Eastern Community Legal Centre (ECLC) offers free legal assistance from its offices in Box Hill, Boronia and Healesville during the day and at night. The Centre also operates nine outreach locations and two family violence health-justice services across Melbourneês east. ECLC is committed to reform that achieves equality and social justice within the legal system for communities and people experiencing disadvantage. In addition to direct legal services, ECLC also undertakes community development activities that empower clients, workers and the general community. ECLC raises awareness of legal issues and provides education through projects and partnerships, workshops, media, events and publications. ECLC has a team of about 40 staff and over 100 volunteers. ECLC is located in the Eastern region of Melbourne and serves the Cities of Whitehorse, Boroondara, Manningham, Maroondah, Knox and the Shire of Yarra Ranges. In the last year the Centre assisted 3211 clients (an 8% increase on the 2014-15 year) directly and pursued community development, community legal education and partnership projects for the priority communities of: - children & young people - people experiencing or at risk of family violence - Indigenous Australians - older people - people who experience language or cultural barriers - people experiencing or at risk of homelessness - people with a disability or mental illness.

AFL SportsReadyês primary purpose is to assist two groups that traditionally face barriers in obtaining employment: young people; and Indigenous young people. In 2013 AFL SportsReady delivered training and education to assist these cohorts to obtain long-term employment and to meet the recognised need for additional services and supports for young people in this area. In 2013 AFL SportsReady delivered traineeships to over 800 young people (including over 200 Indigenous young people) and provided ongoing mentoring and support, case-management and assistance with problems encountered by young people navigating the workforce for the first time. In 2013 AFL SportsReady continued its focus on creating sustainable Indigenous employment through the delivery of our Indigenous Employment Program, delivering Indigenous traineeships, accredited education, trainee support and cultural awareness training to create genuine career pathways for young Indigenous people. Further, in 2013 AFL SportsReady partnered with organisations such as Australia Post, ANZ, CBA, NAB, Telstra and Westpac to provide traineeships for Indigenous young people; YMCA Ballarat to deliver traineeships for local young people; and partnered with the Collingwood Foundation & City of Yarra to deliver traineeships for Indigenous young people that lead into ongoing employment.

Cycle Saloon's purposes:a) provide a shared bicycle workshop for the community to repair and recycle bicyclesCycle Saloon has been open 5 days / 40 hours per week for most of 2016, allowing visitors plenty of time to use the workshop.b) to repair the bikes using recycled components unless safety requires new componentsVolunteers and employees restored about 150 bikes over the past year using approximately 90% recycled parts.c) to provide a learning environment for participants to develop and share mechanical problem-solving skillsOver the past year more than 1000 people used the workshop and received advice on repairing their bicycle.d) to provide access to affordable bicycles for disadvantaged/unemployedThe average price of the 150 bikes serviced and sold through Cycle Saloon was $150, which is less than half the price of a new bike of equivalent quality, giving lower income earners cheap, reliable and safe bicycles.e) to promote cycling as a sustainable form of transportThrough the repair and sale of recycled bikes, Cycle Saloon has put about 150 good, safe bikes back into use, with about 10% of the carbon footprint of producing the same number of new bikes.

column39: Gender equality activities
column41: WLIA has led a range initiatives to further the promotion of women in and into leadership positions in Australia and to highlight the importance of gender balance in all public forums and organisations. This has been achieved through the Women for Media initiative, which seeks to increase the visibility of female thought leaders and experts in the media, as well as the Panel Pledge which has grown and been committed to by all Male Champions of Change in Australia. We have also worked to _mainstreamî the 40:40:20 target of gender balance (40% men, 40% women, 20% unallocated) for boards, panels, conferences and decision-making bodies or teams. We publicly advocated for the Australian Government Boards (Gender Balanced Representation) Bill 2015. We continue to advocate directly to the federal government and publicly for an increase of women being nominated for and awarded an Australian Honours. WLIA has also supported to innovative research in the fields of gender equality and women in leadership via the WLIA Women in Political Leadership Swinburne PhD Scholarship and the WLIA Research Fellowship. We have offered our Women for Media members events specifically covering how to engage with the media and social media in order to increase their visibility in public debates and conversations. We have also worked with the Male Champions of Change movement to advise on various issues and strategies relating to the advancement of women into senior executive roles in organisations. WLIA continued to oversee and advise on the work undertaken by the Property Male Champions of Change _ in partnership with the Property Council of Australia. We oversaw and advised on the implementation of the inaugural Pathways to Politics Program for Women, an initiative from the Trawalla Foundation and the Melbourne School of Government at The University of Melbourne. The WLIA leadership team have been involved in a range of panels and conferences, as well as made comment in print, radio and TV shows on issues relating to women in leadership, gender equality, and gender diversity in the workplace.

Westside Circus had a strong year in 2016: we saw greater participation and engagement from our community, consolidated our financial position and continued to deliver exciting programs for young people. And our new home looks amazing (thanks to Jane Hartnell and Jade Borjesson)!In terms of numbers, we delivered over 25 workshop programs each term and filled over 15,000 workshop places. But the exciting developments in 2016 were around the renewal of our strategic vision and program improvements. The primary goal of increased sustainability was addressed by prioritising community engagement, program review and stakeholder management.Our success engaging communities is evidenced by growth of our term program and relationships with local councils, in particular our own Council, Darebin, with whom we commenced an Arts Partnership Initiative in 2016. We enjoyed ongoing partnerships with Moreland Council and Hume Council and, a new long term project starting in 2017 sees us partnered with Banyule Youth Services, Headspace and Concord School.Our program review affirmed access and inclusion as a foundation of our activities and resulted in a strengthening of our arts in education programs. In 2016 we were approved as an NDIS provider, and planned for our disability circus program, MY Circus, to move from a funded project to a self-sustaining social enterprise. Our other access and inclusion programs had us working with Furlong School for Deaf Children and Ignition Theatre, as well as building new projects in partnership with Occupational Therapy Service providers to deliver more structured and targeted circus programs to a broader number of young people living with a disability.As for Arts and Education, we worked with Melbourne Polytechnic to deliver a tailored Certificate IV in Training and Assessment. This was done in response to one of our education partners, Shepparton ACE College, wanting to bring circus into their curriculum. It also presents an opportunity for Westside Circus to formalise a more structured approach to the way we use non-formal education methodologies within formal education settings. In 2016, Westside Circus became one of four partners to deliver an international project, funded by the European Union. National Treasures is a collaborative research project, youth exchange, creative development, and a platform for future international opportunities.

Foodbank Victoria is an independent not-for-profit organisation with more than 80 yearsê food relief experience. We are the stateês oldest and largest organisation of our kind.Our aim is to provide healthy food for all. To do this we work with a network of almost 800 corporate and community partners to source and distribute food to people in need across Victoria.At Foodbank we collect excess food from farmers, manufacturers and wholesalers. This includes products that for one reason or another canêt enter the retail chain. The food we collect is a mixture of top quality, end-of-line, mislabelled and overrun stock. All of which is still suitable for people to eat. This includes fruit and vegetables that do not meet retail specifications; excess produce from high yielding harvests; and goods that may simply have damaged packaging but are still entirely safe to the consumer.In the 2015-16 financial year, the equivalent of over 13 million meals was distributed from our Yarraville warehouse with a further 5.5 million distributed by our community partners.  As a member of the State Governmentês Emergency Response and Recovery Committee, we are also there in times of disaster as the leading provider of emergency food relief to Victorian communities.

BrainLink is a non profit charitable organisation committed to reducing the impact of acquired brain disorders. These may be caused by trauma, hypoxia, infection, tumour, substance abuse, degenerative neurological diseases (such as MS, Motor Neurone disease and Parkinsonês disease) or stroke. We are dedicated to improving the quality of life of people affected by conditions of the brain and providing support to families in Victoria. We currently service 1300 families in Victoria a year as and when they require assistance.  Our core services include Information/Support and Referral (including a state-wide hotline), Carer Education and Support programs, Respite Programs and _Slow to Recoverî Case Management for non_compensable clients with severe brain injury. We are unique in our service provision which provides full respite care (ie. professional care for the person with the acquired brain injury (ABI) so that the carer can attend information, education and respite programs) in order for our services to be affectively delivered. BrainLink also provides education to health professionals and runs LifeMoves, which is a peer support group for people living with acquired brain disorder.
The HEARing CRC has carried out research into more effective prevention and improved remediation of hearing loss.

The Australian Children's Literature Alliance is responsible for the Australian Children's Laureate Program. The Laureate is an outstanding author and member of the Australian Children's Literature community who by example and through a rigorous touring program inspires children to develop and expand their interest and understanding of literature and of story Every two years a new Childrenês Laureate is announced and act as a national and international ambassador for reading. This work builds the foundation of culture in our society and inculcates a love of reading in young people.  More broadly, children all across Australia who have access to the Laureate, through school visits, festival attendances, regional touring programs, creative projects, social media and traditional media.A particular focus of the Laureate program has been working with children and families with low levels of literacy and children living in the remotest areas of Australia who would not readily have the chance to ´touchê literature up close and be inspired by Australiaês most talented and engaging storytellers.

column2: Australian Foundation For Palestinian Children Inc.
column41: The key activities and achievements of the Australian Foundation for Palestinian Children (Olive Kids) during the 2016 financial year are summarised below. Sponsorship projectOlive Kidsê sponsorship program expanded to support 214 orphans this year. Olive Kids is committed to the ongoing continuation of this critical program, offering sustainable support from our kind Australian sponsors to our children in Gaza totalling $128,400 in annual aid.Olive Kids also continues to improve this program, to ensure orphans services are covered and a portion of the sponsorship is set aside for the orphansê education. Additionally, this year Olive Kids began making arrangements for the construction of an Olive Kids wing at Al-Amal Institute for Orphans.Clothes DrivesThe ongoing clothing drive program continued during the year. High quality used clothing and toys were collected throughout the year. Shipment is expected at the end of the calendar year. As per usual arrangements, the shipment is targeting the refugee camps in Jordan, and will be distributed in partnership with UNRWA.Annual DinnerThe Olive Kids 8th Annual Fundraising Dinner was held on the 29th of May, at Peninsula on the waterfront of Victoria Harbour, Docklands. This yearês event was the most successful one to date as reflected by the astounding fundraising effort. As a result of this event we were able to raise $100,500 in pledges towards the construction of an Olive Kids wing at Al-Amal. In total, including major donations both local and international, Olive Kids has raised $229,379 for this project.    This yearês Empower Gaza campaign aims to accomplish the following:‚ Install solar panels at Al-Amal to enable them to have a more constant source of electricity and significantly reduce the current monthly energy bill of USD$20,000‚ Sponsor 50 additional orphans‚ Send a new medical mission to Palestine‚ Ship another container of aid to the refugee camps‚ Fund the expansion of Al-Amal in Gaza by building an Olive Kids wing. This new wing will enable Al-Amal to host children from as young as 1 day old up to 5 years of age. At a total cost of $200,000, a whole floor would allow the orphanage to house a total of 75 additional children.Medical MissionsIn collaboration with the Union of Health Work Committees  (UHWC), Olive Kids facilitated an Australian medical mission to Alwada Hospital in Gaza. Lead by Associate Professor David Croacker (General and Neonatal Paediatric Surgeon) and also including Mr Paul Chicchio (Nurse) and Ben Wagstaff (Doctor), the team conducted many operations and ran multiple training sessions for local surgeons. Per the ongoing arrangements, Olive Kids covered the costs of airfare and accommodation. The next mission is planned for May 2017.Other activities include an ongoing collaboration with Children First Foundation to provide medical assistance to needy Palestinian children and our partnership to support HCEF's Youth Leadership Pro

The Children's Cancer Foundation's mission is to enable children with cancer to access the worldês best treatment and support and to build awareness of childhood cancer in the community and within governments.  Through an extensive grant making program, the Foundation supports families undergoing treatment, partners with hospitals to deliver clinical excellence and funds clinical research and clinical trials with the aim to develop new and kinder treatments for children with cancer. In 2015/16 the Foundation supported families through the stress of cancer treatment by funding the salaries of Family Resource Coordinators, and by providing therapeutic storybooks and Music and Art Therapy to assist children with adapting to treatment. The Foundation also funded The Beaded Journey, a therapeutic program which helps each patient mark every treatment milestone with a special bead; this program assists children and their families to cope with their cancer experience and relate their experience visually. In 2017 the Foundation will announce major new grants for projects that span the cancer treatment journey, from family support and clinical care to ground breaking clinical research and clinical trials, including one national project.At all times, the Foundation endeavours to raise funds in a way which is both efficient and ethical. The Foundation does not conduct public raffles or telemarketing. Nor do we receive government funding. Funds are raised through The Million Dollar Lunch, community fundraising, corporate sponsorship and donations. A volunteer board of directors and a large team of dedicated volunteers help us maximise our fundraising income, while the generosity of many pro bono supporters _ office space, marketing, design, legal and insurance _ ensure that our administration overheads over the past 5 years have averaged just 9%. For the latest news from the Foundation, visit: http://childrenscancerfoundation.com.au/news

column41: For mama with love is a small locally based charity that aims to assist women and their children when they are experiencing difficulties in their life due to many issues such as relationship breakdown, financial issues, mental and previous drug issues and they find themselves in desperate need of assistance.  Each woman and mother we help is in a different situation and due to our small size we are committed to tailing help to each individual and we have the freedom to help as the need arises promptly whereas larger charities have much paperwork and at times women can wait long times for assistance to be obtained.We do this organically and while the practical assistance such as food, housing, daily needs can be done straight away the building of trust and providing extra emotional support over  longer period we find gives them the strength to change their lives for their sake and more importantly their children's.We have been able to help a mum move into her new home with her children after been living in a car, provide support in a women who was fleeing a domestic situation, link in women to other organisations, provide food, clothing and emotional support that allows them and their children to be a safe environment.All funds go toward this and changing their lives not just in the short term but long term.

column41: Fairtrade Australia and New Zealandês mission is to connect disadvantaged producers and consumers, promote fairer trading conditions and empower producers to combat poverty, strengthen their position and take more control over their lives.Fairtrade seeks to change the way trade works through better prices, decent working conditions and a fairer deal for farmers and workers in developing countries. We promote the purchase of Fairtrade-certified products in Australia to enable people to create change through their everydayactions, and to support farming communities to improve their lives and invest in their future.Fairtrade Australia & New Zealand is a full and active member of Fairtrade International and has the sole right to license the use of the international FAIRTRADE Mark in Australia and New Zealand.Fairtrade ANZ's objectives are to:‚ Improve economic and community development of Pacific rural communities through Fairtrade certification and market access.‚ Expand market access in Australia and New Zealand for Fairtrade certified producers with a particular focus on Indo-Pacific supply chains;‚ Build awareness of the Fairtrade Mark and convert awareness of the Fairtrade Mark into regular product purchase; and‚ Provide assurance to consumers of the Fairtrade Mark via a credible and independent certification program.To achieve these objectives, Fairtrade ANZ undertook a wide variety of business development, public engagement and advocacy and producer support activities, including: ‚ Fairtrade Fortnight Campaign‚ Protest With Your Purchase Campaign‚ Participation in Trade Shows‚ Participation in Industry Forums/Presentations‚ Producer Support Work supporting producers in the Pacific region, particularly in PNG, East Timor, Samoa, Vanuatu and Tonga.For further information about Fairtrade ANZ's activities and outcomes, please see our 2015/2016 Annual Report: http://fairtrade.com.au/en-au/policies-reports-and-standards

Ross House Association achieved its purposes in 2015/2016 though the following activities and outcomes. ‚ Ross House Association (RHA) Committee of Management (CoM) met eleven times during the year to oversee strategic direction of the organisation. ‚ During 2015/2016, RHA employed 10 staff (3 full time, 3 part time, 4 casual). RHA staff manage and administer the resources and facilities of the Ross House building. ‚ During 2015/2016 there were 52 Ross House tenants (all small community organisation), all of whom are provided with reduced rental rates on office space, access to equipment, resources and facilities, including meeting rooms. Opportunities for skill sharing and development is also readily available. Additionally, there were 34 non-tenant members, all of whom can access reduced rates on meeting rooms and resources also. ‚ The building was managed by the CoM, its sub-committees and staff democratically and efficiently. Representatives from the tenant groups and appointed members make up the CoM, therefore decisions made about the management of the building come from the heart of the community. ‚ Working parties continued to review and update the Constitution ‚ The revised RHA Enterprise Agreement 2015 came into effect January 2016. ‚ Regular newsletters were distributed to all members, tenants and other organisations with similar aims. ‚ Various workshops were offered to members and tenants, free of charge, covering topics such as volunteer recruitment & management, crowdfunding, media and IT.

The Social Studio is a grass-roots social enterprise that strives to create pathways to employment and further education for young people from refugee and migrant backgrounds. Established in 2009, the Studio uses fashion and hospitality as a vehicle to engage with at-risk, unemployed and vulnerable young people from refugee and migrant backgrounds through the provision of pre-accredited and TAFE training, work experience and entry-level employment in retail, hospitality and manufacturing. The Social Studio values opportunity, quality, creativity and community. Located in Smith St Collingwood, we have a retail-clothing store, manufacturing business, digital fabric printing studio, caf_, catering business and a training school. As testimony to the work of the organisation, The Social Studio was the 2nd Prize Winner of the Ethical Enterprise Award 2015.

The Victorian Serrated Tussock Program has conducted and/or sponsored a wide range of serrated tussock programs. These include undertaking research into pastures and herbicide technology, production of appropriate extension materials, provision of incentives to land managers and community groups and comprehensive mapping, extension, monitoring and compliance campaigns. A coordinated management program where a combination of control methods is used has shown to be the most effective way of controlling this noxious weed.Since its formation the VSTWP has been responsible for the development and implementation of a number of management strategies; these documents have not only provided direction but have been fundamental in promoting a coordinated community-led approach to serrated tussock control throughout Victoria. The VSTWP has strived in partnership with all levels of Government and their agencies, industry, research institutions, Landcare and the wider community to achieve the original recommendations of the Victorian Serrated Tussock Strategy 2012-2017. Purpose of the VSTWP(a) To facilitate and encourage management of serrated tussock in Victoria.(b) To be responsible for the development and implementation of detailed action strategies and to provide oversight for on-ground program delivery (including local government).(c) To develop any specific policies (and seek DEDJTR endorsement) that relate to the implementation of the Victorian Serrated Tussock Strategy.(d) Submit/support & review funding allocations and submissions for Federal and State initiatives, partnership business and other programs that impact on the implementation of the Victorian Serrated Tussock Strategy.(e) To develop and negotiate service delivery outcomes and budget allocations with the DEDJTR/Catchment Management Authorities for service delivery of the particular programs which effect or impact upon serrated tussock control activities.(f) Seek advice from and provide direction to Government on resource management objectives, targets, activities, priorities and budgets to ensure working party objectives are reflected within their respective Business Plans.(g) Establish technical and advisory groups to assist the VSTWP.(h) Provide information to the wider community from relevant stakeholder groups regarding their particular program.(i) Report on achievements of objectives and targets annually by 1 November each year (annual progress report).(j) To do all such things as are incidental or conducive to the attainment of these purposes and to exercise the powers of the VSTWP.
