The Rabbinical College of Australia and New Zealand is Australia's first and largest tertiary residential institute of higher Jewish studies. It provides facilities for local, interstate and overseas students to further their Jewish education at an advanced level. Students completing the full time course are awarded a nationally recognised Diploma of Talmudic Studies. Part time classes are available for primary, secondary and tertiary students. The college also trains students to become communal religious functionaries for the Australian Jewish community. Regular weekly community visits and Festival outreach projects are conducted to advance Jewish religion. Students serve as counsellors and learning teachers at weekly youth groups, seminars and overnight camps. The collegeês library facilities contain an extensive collection of reference and other texts on a wide range of topics which are available for borrowing. Publications on various religious topics, students' essays and analytical research papers are prepared on a regular basis and distributed throughout the community.

Global Ideas is on a mission to create and connect the next generation of global health leaders, and therefore seeks to engage young people in Australia to build their capacity to lead change for better health equity in Australia and our region.  Recognising that global health challenges are complex, unpredictable, interdependent and often driven by factors outside the health sector, our programs draw participants from our diverse, next-generation, interdisciplinary community to provide action oriented learning to build the capacity of young Australians to lead change. We currently offer three learning experiences:  ? Our FORUM engages and inspires action on global health inequities. The program is shaped around five ´personasê that capture the diverse spectrum of action that leads to global health impact. Participants leave with new knowledge of the range of global health issues and the ways we can act individually and collectively; and empowered to continue their educational journey with new networks to connect to opportunities and new tools to approach challenges systematically and creatively.  ? Our LABS inspire and engage more deeply by providing more detailed analysis of a single issue in global health. A content expert leads highly interactive small group sessions aimed at translating and transferring the latest academic work into insights that change the way we live and work. We encourage shared peer-to-peer learning through reflection on various aspects of the action agenda including leadership, advocacy, collaboration and ethical deliberation.  ? Our DESIGN JAMS provide problem-based experiential learning for global health action. Jams are highly facilitated immersion in the process of design to move beyond empathy, understanding and ideas into building and testing solutions that may be further developed and applied by our program partners. Our facilitators embed training in design thinking in the global health and development context to advance our understanding of both.  Through our programs young people in Australia are equipped and motivated to make a difference to the health of their communities.

Boundless connects students from disadvantaged outer-suburbs and regional schools with professional work experience opportunities. By improving access to work experience among disadvantage students, we can improve their educational and career outcomes. Immersion in the workplace helps young people to feel that their aspirations are tangible and achievable. Better access to work experience is also an important part of promoting better social mobility and addressing high youth unemployment. Unfortunately, access to work experience is very inequitable. Finding work experience requires connections and social capital. As such, students from low-SES, regional, migrant or Indigenous backgrounds often miss out, or have a very limited range of placements available to them. Our model is to match students, based on their aspirations, with professional work experience opportunities. We promote work experience to businesses as a simple and rewarding way to meet their objectives in community engagement, workplace inclusion and leadership development. We provide expert training and support, drawing on our experience as classroom teachers to develop student-led, project-based work experience that is engaging for both students and staff.We were founded in 2014 and incorporated as a charity in April 2015. In the period April 2015 to 30 June 2016, we saw some wonderful outcomes for the students and workplaces we partner with.In this period, we connected 96 students with one-week work experience placements. We were uniquely student-led in our approach. Through conversations with students and their teachers, we helped students to unpack their interests and to identify their strengths and growth areas. We saw that work experience had a valuable impact on studentsê knowledge, confidence and agency. After work experience, students indicated that they are more motivated to work hard at school, and better prepared to make informed and confident choices about their post-school pathways.For example, one of our students told us:_I was actually thinking about doing easy classes next semester at school and becoming a tradie, but when I finished work experience I have a completely different thought. I'm now thinking about doing more challenging classes and actually going to uni. Saying that scares me but I am going to try and do my bestî.We partnered with eight public schools in disadvantaged parts of Melbourne and regional Victoria. This included all four Shepparton-region public schools as part of the Better Together Alliance (Wanganui Park Secondary College, Shepparton High School, Mooroopna College and McGuire College); Melbourne schools Mill Park Secondary College and Keysborough College, and Horsham College in north-west Victoria. For students from Shepparton and Horsham, we worked with schools to coordinate a ´work experience campê to Melbourne, where we held workshops with students and helped them to reflect and share experiences throughout their place

We are incredibly blessed with an amazingly committed group of leaders, volunteers, staff members, pastors and support crews. An example for me would be the emergence of our Sunday night team who have crafted a new format for gathering people together on a Sunday evening around the concept of being a Worshipping Community. The diversity of those attending this weekly event gives opportunity for a different style of gathering. This allows for moments of the release of Holy Spirit gifts, to times of reflection and prayer, and often giving a younger Christian the opportunity to lead us around Communion. These services are led and crafted by a committed band of people who want to assist in the strengthening of this church family. Our Coffee Team of expert baristas recently reported that through the support of our church family, this simple ministry has seen a profit of $14,000 since its commencement. I was absolutely amazed. These funds have gone to help finance mission projects locally (generally to support programs through Peninsula Christian Care), to supporting missionaries overseas (Keith & Lolita in India and Pastor Radu in Romania have been direct beneficiaries). Every time you see, or hear, the coffee machine operating please know that it is creating work experience for those using it, in addition to funding a mission project somewhere.  I could spend much more time boasting about the things our Childrenês Ministry is achieving; or the passionate growth of our Youth Ministry; the many people still connecting through The Alpha Course; the expanding role of our Reach In ministry; the level of commitment from our Music Ministry team; our weekly service Hosts who coordinate the First Impressions Team every time we meet; the regular gatherings of our Nexus (over 50ês) family; the Connect Groups that meet all over our region; plus the many stories of people volunteering in a host of ways within our local communities.   The impact that our church community has had internationally is staggering. Tens of thousands of people are being directly impacted whether through our finances, direct contact or support for those that are overseeing vital aide and ministry programs. The world may never know our name but heaven rejoices with the souls that have been transformed because of our willingness.  All of this, and more, creates a community. Thatês what we are - a faith community. On the 4th August 2017 Peninsula City Church will celebrate 70 continuous years of ministry service to the community of Frankston and the region of the Mornington Peninsula. It has been an amazing privilege to be a part of this Peninsula City Church family throughout the journey thus far. Letês not get weary, there is much more to do. Pastor Jim & Jan Jung
